    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (1,'Squirt Ranch','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Carver','Estacada','1300','1500','3000','45.3822','-122.4442','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','This is truely a Epic spot in Oregon. Our prize jewel. Below 1000, theres just not enough water coming from the side channel.  Above 3000 is pretty powered up munchy!  The only access is to do the Barton to Carver section and hit it on the fly(ive camped out on the squirt ranch island), or hook up with us locals for private access right at the spot.','14210000','cfs','18','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (59,'Pearly Gates','Arkansas','','US','US Mountain','CO','Buena Vista','NATHROP','','','','38.7103','-106.0533','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=07091200','','There is a super powerful spot on the Arkansas river in Colorado on the browns canyon section two eddies above the canyon doors hole, it has unofficially been named the pearly gates. I got sent so deep last summer that I had three completely independent thoughts and came up about 30 yards down stream of my buddies, I knew I got sent pretty good by the size of their eyes when I finally came back to the surface.\r\n\r\nYou definitely cant drive to it, but you might be able to mtn bike to it on the railroad tracks. It is a few miles down the tracks. I just boat to it. I recommend squirt boating the entire river as there is epic squirt play all over the place down there. \r\nEventually you do get used to the pain and discomfort, I swear! The entire trip is 5 to 7 hours total and I squirt it every weekend in the summer, it can be done. The river is near Buena Vista Colorado.','07091200','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (3,'Buffet, The','Lower Washougal','','US','US Pacific','WA','Camas','','300','1000-1500','3000 +','45.5880','-122.3662','https://fortress.wa.gov/ecy/wrx/wrx/flows/station.asp?sta=28B080','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?WASW1','On the lower Washougal River, less than a mile above the Columbia River confluence, is The Sandy Swimming Hole, a Washougal city park, complete with rest room’s, parking spaces, and a deck cantilevered out over the high water zone. This is a long, deep pool with a shallow rapid entering at the upstream end. There are two rocks sticking out at low water, with fun at both spots. \r\n\r\nThese rocks are the high spots on a hard rock ledge at the top of the pool. In the winter (this is a low elevation, rain fed winter run river)a seam forms as currents converge below an island just upstream. To get the FAT goods, were entering the seam, sinking to head disappearing when the bottom of the slab falls off the underwater ledge. Were doing an underwater eddy turn to keep smoothly dropping with a last couple o strokes, then letting go of the paddle when it pulls, and spiraling smoothly, slowly down with the gloved hands to 6, 8, 10, 12+.... \r\n\r\nLeveling off and flying is fairly easy, once having spent enough time underwater to maintain composure. Consistent 10+ second rides, and plenty of epic rides approaching 20 seconds or more. The 30 second ride is there, no doubt. Many times have I hit the up button, out of breath, still 6-8 feet down. We are using goggles, and 15 visibility is common in the cold water. NOT A SINGLE THING IN THE ROAMING ZONE- TOTALLY SAFE! \r\n\r\nSince discovery in January, 7 people have copped my charc and roamed heavily. Only one had ever had any deep, long rides. \r\n\r\nIt happens during most moderate winter, rainy weather flows- half the year. That would be the cold half- bring a hood! \r\n\r\nBy, Tim H.\r\n\r\nEF Lewis gauge isnt really for this spot..but its a good idication of whether or not it would be in.... the noaa washougal gauge, and the gauge at hathaway park(state ecology dept), both dont seem to tell us if this spot is in.\r\n\r\nThe best way to tell if this spot is in, is visual:  look at the concrete unit that is just down stream on river left. If you dont see it, then the water is probably too high. You want to have at least one corner of it out of the water.\r\n\r\nTwo Gages:\r\nhttps://fortress.wa.gov/ecy/wrx/wrx/flows/station.asp?sta=28B080\r\nhttps://fortress.wa.gov/ecy/wrx/wrx/flows/station.asp?wria=28 \r\nhttp://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/text/WASW1.HG.0.0.1.0.txt','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (4,'Weasel, The','North Santiam','','US','US Pacific','OR','Mill City','Niagara or Mehama minus Little North Santiam','900','1500','2200','44.7741','-122.5683','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?14181500','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MEHO3','Home of the 2011 Mystery Worlds and a part of the 2016 Mystery Worlds squirt tour extravaganza.  Our first official Weasel Gathering was in 2009.\r\n\r\nTake I-5 South from Portland to Salem...take highway 22 east from there. Just past Mehama, turn right onto North Santiam State Park Road and take the gravel road down to the river.  The spot is at the bottom of the island just downstream.\r\n\r\nWe have had great luck here at this newly found spot, with many epic, deep, long, easy rides. Its a convergence just like the squirt ranch.  the river splits around a small island and creates a sweet convergence coming off the gravel bar point.  both lefties and righties are very easy here.  the deeper water is on the eddy side, so back cutting to the right can result in deep, very slow rides.  there are several major rocks in the deep zone, but so far it has been a very friendly neighborhood.\r\n\r\nJono Der and Tim Hollar first probed out the upper spot at the Weasel, which is now considered to be as good or better than the lower main spot at higher flows.  You can sink at the upper spot and connect under water to the lower spot.  Sweet!\r\n\r\nThis gage release data from 2007 shows that this spot will probably be hold good levels with releases from the dam through June, July, Aug, Sept! These are the most beautiful and sunny months of the year in oregon anyway! A great summer play ground.\r\nhttp://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2007/pdfs/14183000.2007.pdf\r\n\r\nPrediction gage for the next couple days...\r\nhttp://ahps2.wrh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=pqr&gage=meho3&view=1,1,1,1,1,1\r\n\r\nCamping: \r\nThe best camping as at North Santiam State Park, right at the Weasel.  There are nine first-come-first-served spots on the river, with water and facilities available.  From the campground you can walk or float to the Weasel.  \r\n\r\nthere is also camping 3.6 miles upstream at Fishermans Bend Rec Site.. a BLM site. First come first serve. Its very crowded and Team Nevada said it was full of little kids crying and running around, and therefore they searched out sweeter camping.\r\nhttp://www.blm.gov/or/resources/recreation/files/brochures/Fishermen%20Bend%20Recreation%20Site.pdf\r\n\r\nMore sweet camping is available at Rock Creek Campground in Mill City:\r\nTeam Nevada dialed it in. go into MillCity.. make a right and go down by the bridge which is actually the takeout from the Packsaddle to MillCity run. go over the bridge over the river..youll be on 1st ave. eventually you get to the post office..make a left. now you are on Kingwood Ave. in this same area there is a little grocery store and a laundry mat. going on kingwood ave, youll see a tiny little sign on your left that says Rock Creek campground.. turn right there and the paved road will quickly turn into a gravel road. Booyaa.','14181500','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (5,'Bender','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Carver','Estacada','700','1100','1500','45.3917','-122.4851','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','Went to the Bender to explore late summer 06, but it was just too low. No ones been here in a couple years, but people say it used to be really really good. Its setup kinda like squirt ranch.Its upstream from squirt ranch two bends in the river. Access is from Carver Park:  hike up river right side, and you will have to cross a small stream. Then continue upstream on the clackamas, on the small side channel untill you get to the top of the island. Get in your boat here, and paddle up stream to the next island..the spot is there at that convergence from the island.','14210000','cfs','17','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (6,'Joe Bobs','Upper Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','Three Lynx','3000','5000','7000','45.1903','-122.1705','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14209500&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?TLYO3','This big glassy surfing wave is just downstream to Bobs hole…this is only a high water spot and not in that often. When this is in, you may see some locals(Dominic and friends) out on it with surf boards.\r\n','14209500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (24,'Blue River Confluence','Mckenzie','','US','US Pacific','OR','Blue River','Vida','1','1.5','2','44.1539','-122.3431','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00065&format=img_default&site_no=14162500&set_logscale_y=0','','This is the confluence of the Blue River and the Mckenzie River... \r\n\r\n5-10sec mysterys possible.. might not be a 30sec spot, but worth the 45min drive and fun for Eugene locals.\r\n\r\nmight need to look at this blue river gage too, for reference:\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?site_no=14162200&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','14162500','ft','18','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (25,'Southern Pacific','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Oregon City','Estacada','800','950','1300','45.3792','-122.5757','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','The Watch Tower aka Southern Pacific was found summer of 2006. went to go to the Chanpange Jam but it was too low, and found this spot just down stream of it. Its a good spot, but your charc must be dialed in, and then you can go big. Park and play access off of Clackams River Road at the large pull off on river left.','14210000','cfs','18','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (26,'Root Cellar','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Carver','Estacada','2500','','3200','45.3952','-122.5249','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','This spot is a eddy line off Shoe Bootie beach on the river right side,  Your charc has got to be right on, but can go big here, Its just downstream from the Carver Bridge about a mile or so. Access is park and play on river left.. the pull off is where the guard rail stops and a fence begins. \r\n\r\nThis spot comes it when its too high for the ranch...','14210000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (27,'Champagne Jam','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Oregon City','Estacada','750','','2000','45.3801','-122.5747','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','The Champagne Jam changed significantly in the winter of 2012-2013, and the spot does not exist as it did in previous years.  The top of the bowl where the old entry zone was is now completely filled in with rock and is only a foot or two deep.  There is still a very deep pool below with some drop potential, but it pales in comparison to the old Jam.  After a few hours of trying to unlock the door, we were able to only get modest 8-10 second rides.  Ryan Young got one massive mystery, proving that it does still exist, but it will take some work to figure out a consistent entry.  The new entry zone is at least 100 feet downstream from the old entry.  Ferry out from the river left eddy into a the flow where it starts to drop of the shelf, and spin your way down.  Getting neck deep right away is critical.  The quality has been dropped back to \\\\Exploratory\\\\.  As of now, the DT is moderate at best.\r\n\r\nAlso, we no longer use the parking on river left, as there have been multiple vehicle break ins.  Now we take the Gladstone exit off of 205, and park next to the Safeway and High Rocks restaurant.  Walk down behind the restaurant to the obvious trail to the river, right behind the Comfort Inn.  Head upstream under the bridges on river right and follow the trail up to the spot.  it is the next little riffle upstream of the little rapid with the brick tower on river left.','14210000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (28,'Barton Buster','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Barton','Estacada','1500','2600','4000','45.3884','-122.4228','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','This spot is a half mile or so downstream from Barton Park.  The drop zone is formed by the convergence of flows around a large island in the river.  The drop is simple and immediate, and you can drop to the bottom with very little effort.  Its not at all scary (below 3250cfs), yet you can still get plenty deep. The downtime is very fast and covers a long distance.  A ten second ride takes you a good forty yards downstream.  The door downward is accessed by ferrying across from surfers right to left, and initiating going left on the obvious seam (reminiscent of the move at Sweet Cheeks on the Gauley).  The backcut is also nice and easy, and allows for a slower ride.  \r\n\r\nNo park and play access has been found yet...ie dont try and hike back up to Barton Park (Joel and Weaver had a epic adventure trying to do that).  Currently the only access is to do the Barton Park to Carver Park section, which is 5 miles. Or do the Barton to Squirt Ranch run with the locals and take out at Thoms place, which is a 2 mile run.  This spot is officially off the exploratory list and is the new go to when the Ranch is too high.','14210000','cfs','17','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (29,'Cliffs of Insanity','Lower Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Carver','Estacada','3000','3500','4100','45.3942','-122.4907','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14210000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?ESTO3','Just around the corner from the rock wall, and the signs that warn of a under cut..  Exploration spot...only had one session here and i was just ok, but got a few good rides. Its on the Barton to Carver section...just upstream from Carver park. Access is to paddle or hike up from Carver Park.','14210000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (30,'Holtwood','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Holtwood','Harrisburg','6','','15','39.8201','-76.3335','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','Put in just below the dam... and do the run down to before the bridge in your glass boat. Alternative take out is below the dam through the maze of islands ...on river right.  I would bet money on it that there is a Epic mystery move spot down there somewhere...but i never explored to much... Nosal talked about sick rides theyve gotten in the channels below the bridge.\r\n\r\n<Im upping the minimum from 5 ft to 6 ft.  Not sure if 6 ft is any good, but Im sure 5 ft is no good.> dan mayer.\r\n\r\n<Note that the aerial photo in the map depicts an extremely high-water situation.  There is a whole network of islands above and below the bridge.> danmayer','01570500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (36,'Bobs Hole','Upper Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','Three Lynx','1800','1900','2000','45.1905','-122.1707','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14209500&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?TLYO3','Classic playspot on the Upper Clack. Park and play. Ive gotten some 5 seconds moves off of the eddy line formed by the rock below Bobs Hole.... nothing that great...its not very deep so you cant go big here.. around 1800-2000 seems the best for mystery potential.. Joe bobs is A surfing wave at the same location that comes in at higher flows..','14209500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (57,'Big Rock','Lower Sandy','','US','US Pacific','OR','Troutdale','Bull Run','600','1400','2200','45.5378','-122.3763','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=03_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14142500&set_logscale_y=1','','There is a summertime spot on the Sandy River just 15 minutes from downtown Portland Oregon that gives up sweet mysteries and blasts (cool clue spot, too). Take 84 East from Portland to the Lewis and Clark Park exit #18 (just after you pass over the river leaving Troutdale). Take a left at the river and go less than a mile to a stop sign at a bridge. Park next to the bridge and take the trail to the river. \r\n\r\nThe spot comes in at low summer flows (800 cfs,??), when a house size rock on river left forms an pourover shoulder/eddyline for sinkin. There is also a small blast hole just in front of the rock, and another in the pourover as flow comes through the split rock (can clue in with head under). \r\n\r\nThe spot works best at LOW tide if the Columbia is over 9-10 feet at Vancouver, otherwise you don\\\\t have to worry about the tide. Check this gage for current times: http://tides.willyweather.com/or/multnomah-county/columbia-river--sandy-river-entrance.html\r\n\r\nThere are four hazards here to watch out for: 1) check for large trees that may wedge in the eddy as flows recede, 2) when the salmon and steelhead are running, this is a prime fishing hole...be nice to the locals, ask them what is biting, and you can trade sinks with their casts), 3) fishing jet boats can rip by (rarely), and 4) this is a popular sandy beach sunbathing spot, and you might need your mirrored goggles on bright sunny days when there is more than just the sun in your eyes. Enjoy!\r\n\r\nUpdate May 2016:\r\nBig Rock is back and better than it every was in the past. There is much more support on the seam and big 20-30 second downtime is now possible.  The old charc next to the rock still works, but you can now sink right into the seam about ten feet down from the rock.  If you get a huge ride (25+) and travel, there is a piece of small rebar sticking up from the bottom of the river, but reports are that it is not that bad.','14142500','cfs','20','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (60,'Big Eddy','Upper Clackamas','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','Three Lynx','3000','3000','6000','45.1807','-122.1697','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14209500&set_logscale_y=1','','There is a fun winter play spot on the Clackamas River in Oregon, though not really a real mystery venue. It is upstream of the Bobs Hole rodeo spot, at a rapid known as Big Eddy, half-way through the Fish Creek to Bobs Hole run (class 3 play run with one class 4 drop). Big Eddy can be assessed directly for park and play at a roadside turnout, where the out house is (or was...not sure if the Forest Service rebuilt it after someone blew it up with dynamite!) I cant give driving directions from Portland, Oregon (about an hour and a half drive) but it is in any OR white water river guide. Just look for BOBs \r\n\r\nThe deal at big eddy with squirts is that at about 3000 cfs (high winter flows) there are these dynamic exploding whirlpools that you can get real vertical spins in...just like the W. Nealey cartoon with the view out of the eye of the whirlpool from 3 under...you set up on the eddy line, wait for a surge, and throw the bow down into the whirlpool, brace, and hold on for the ride....full flotation pfds recommended. sometimes it sucks you in bow first, sometimes stern first...dealers choice. mystery’s are possible here, but this is a very dynamic spot! \r\n\r\nThe same place has great pulsating eddy lines for screwing and mushing around, but have not had much opportunity to explore without the pfd...kinda intimidating at these higher flows. \r\n\r\nThere is a mild mystery spot behind a rock wall outcropping just downstream on river left. this is a safe mystery spot, short couple-o-second head deep moves, but not epic (i.e., not worth the drive just for these mystery’s) \r\n\r\nBy, Michael Tehan','14209500','cfs','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (61,'Ingas Hole','N. Cal Salmon','','US','US Pacific','CA','Orleans','Somes','1','2','4','41.3749','-123.4217','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ca/nwis/uv/?format=img&site_no=11522500&period=4&PARAmeter_cd=00060','','N.Cal Salmon: Below Ingas Hole: River Right eddy line that breaks out in the main flow about 150 yards down stream from Ingas Hole( approx. 1.0 mile below Butler creek) on the Butler Ledge section. This can be accessed from the Salmon River road at the bottom of Ingas. Float down from the road access. The best levels are low and around 1-2.5 ft on the Somes bar gauge, but be prepared for a wild ride at any level. At this level you wont have to worry about other river traffic. The eddy line is deep and cleean but it does run out against the river left wall. It works good for back cuts as well straight on. \r\n\r\nForks of Salmon to Nordheimer Creek: A good 3,5 miles of whipping eddy line turns. A usual beginners Class II surface run that has no real  rapids,but the nature of the run is wild, deep ,boiling eddy lines/walls, good splat rocks and general squirty mayhem. Good at all levels, but gets really BOILY at below 4 ft on the Somes Bar gauge. \r\n\r\nThe water quality is as clear as Gin and nearly as intoxicating. These are only two of a multitude of spots available here...we need more squirtist here to probe some untouched goods.\r\n\r\nTo get to the Cal Salmon, Take US299 east from Arcata, Ca (about 350 mi. north of SF) to Willow Creek, then go 45 miles North on HWY 96, crossing the Klamath River, past Orleans until Somes Bar, turn right on to Salmon River road and proceed about 10 miles upstream to Ingas Hole. The forks run is about 15 miles upstream from here. The closest town is either Orleans, pop. of 2-300 or so, which has a good little grocery store, and a bar, or Willow Creek, pop of 1000, has pizza, groceries, bar etc..\r\n\r\nArcata on the Coast or Redding in the Valley are both a couple hours drive so stock up there. Arcata is the cosmic center of the universe (read: bring your bong). Redding is the red neck capital of the world. Take your pick. Also, you can come over from Yreka via HWY 3, be careful on this road as sudden snow storms can close it in the winter.\r\n\r\nBy,Tyler Robertson ','11522500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (62,'Vortex','So. Fork Smith River','','US','US Pacific','CA','Cresent City','JED','35000','','','41.8046','-124.0826','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ca/nwis/uv/?format=img&site_no=11532500&period=4&PARAmeter_cd=00060','','So. Fork Smith River, Ca.(This run is choked full of potential spots!!!!)\r\nVortex: Big whirlpools forming river right with cones about 3 ft deep (at 7k on the JED gauge) below the G spot about 1/4 mile. Various levels will go...Usually the water is VERY cold when it is working. I have not spent much time here due to my aversion the bone chilling water and HUGE whirlpools...but man oh man...Drop in. \r\n\r\n\r\nSmith River drainage is about 20 miles north of Cresent City, Ca on HWY 119. This area is possible the most spectacular in California. You will drive up to the Smith thru Giant Redwood trees. Stop and check it out... give me a call and I ll meet you there! Take a right from the 119 heading east on the South Fork road. Go about 7 miles upstream until you cross the second bridge. Look for a turn out on the river left. The G spot is right there...Vortex is between there and the rapid you can see from the second bridge. Like I said there only a few have probed the depths of this one so proceed with caution. G spot is beautiful p/p hole that is squirt friendly at levels around 3.5k and up on the JED gauge.\r\n\r\nBy,Tyler Robertson \r\n','11532500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (63,'USS','Cache la Poudre','','US','US Mountain','CO','Fort Collins','','1.5','2.0','2.75','40.5951','-105.0768','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/co/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=06752260&set_logscale_y=0','','Near Fort Collins CO on the Cache la Poudre River. Head up Rt. \r\n14 from intersection with Hwy 287 about 14 miles. Go past \r\nMishawaka Inn, and it is about 3/4 mile on the right (if you get to \r\nthe tunnel you have gone too far). It is on a sweeping left turn \r\n(going up canyon), which is probably posted with no parking signs - \r\nignore these. On the other side of the river you will see a slab of \r\nrock sloping into the river and a nice pool with boils. Usually enter \r\nfrom river left - work you way up along the rock and cut into the \r\ncurrent entering the pool. Works from about 1.5 to 2.75 feet on the \r\nrock gage at Pineview ( around 300-550 cfs at Canyon Mouth, but \r\nthere are diversions that make this number not as reliable as the \r\npainted gage), with optimum from 2-2.5 feet. Deep, smooth spot \r\nwith no major worries, except possibly the rock at the end of the \r\npool (but only if you are getting looong rides).\r\n','06752260','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (64,'Kyoot','Big Piney Creek','','US','US Central','AR','RUSSLEVILLE','Hwy 164 Gauge ','2.8','','5','35.5838','-93.1717','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ar/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00065&format=img_default&site_no=07257006&set_logscale_y=0','','The locals call it Kyoot, Whirly-rock as many know it. Located in North Central Arkansas. In the Ozark Mtns. The Long Pool run is the section of river to look for, Heltons Farm to Long Pool camp. About 2.5 miles into the run, youll come around a bend in the river. Two rocks protruding in the river, on river left, gravel sand beach on the right. Here it is man, paddle up towards the outer-most rock, and drop. We like the spot. Its Starting to give up really long rides, gotta love it. Local access requires a well equipped . I hate to say this , well equipped Suv. Not your moms truck either. Maybe something along the lines of your neighbors monster truck. No not really. Just some aggressive tires , about an hour trip down to the spot. Over rock slabs sticky red clay an occasional down tree, a small creek crossing. Graves creek, at high water a sweet 4+ micro gorge. Some serious hill climbing. And wa-la your there. Long Pool camp, is located off of Hwy 7.  \r\n\r\nRiver levels 2.8 min on the Hwy 164 Gauge 5 ft it starts getting really dynamic,(longer rides) As for bigger levels tan 5 ft go for it, it will rock your world. \r\n\r\nTO RUN THE RIVER .---TAKE HWY 7 NORTH OUT OF RUSSLEVILLE, ARK, TURN ON HWY 164 WEST ABOUT 5 MILES TURN RIGHT ON OLD HWY 7, GOING PASSED MOORE OUTDOORS, (YOU CAN STOP IN HERE TO GET INFO ABOUT THE RIVER. KERI, DEBBIE, AND NASH WELL BE GLAD TO FILL YOU IN.) CONTINUE NORTH 4.5 MILES TO THE CAMP. YOU CAN SET SHUTTLES FOR THE RUNNING THE RIVER HERE. GO BACK OUT TOWARDS MOORE OUTDOORS, RIGHT AS YOU GET TO THE FARM ON THE RIGHT TAKE THE DIRT ROAD ON THE LEFT,1805. HEAD NORTH TOWARDS HELTONS FARM, TO PUT IN. THE RUN IS TEN MILES LONG.-----THE DRIVE IN OPTION IS THE WAY TO GO WHEN SQUIRTING. LETS START AT KERIS PLACE FOR DRIVE IN DIRECTIONS. BACK OUT ON HWY 164 WEST, CROSS THE TWIN BRIDGES, LOOK FOR ROAD 1800 ON THE RIGHT. DRIVE NORTH TO THE SPLIT IN THE ROAD, TAKE THE RIGHT FORK THAT GOES UP THE MOUNTAIN. WHEN AT THE TOP, YOU WILL PASS TWO ROADS ON THE RIGHT , YOU WANT THE SECOND 1800 D, FOLLOW IT TILL IT GOES INTO A BLUFF AREA, IT IS NO LONGER NATIONAL FOREST MAINTAINED, IT IS RUGGED. YOU’LL KNOW IT LOOKING INTO GRAVES GORGE. FOLLOW DOWN, ABOUT 45 MINUTES DRIVE FROM NOW. DRIVE THE TRAIL, DOWN THE MOUNTAIN, CROSS THE CREEK, UP THE OTHER MOUNTAIN, DOWN, TO THE RIVERS EDGE, CONTINUE FOLLOWING IT THROUGH THE GIANT MUD AREA, USE THE SIDES OF THE HOLES UNLESS YOU HAVE LARGER THAN 33 INCH TIRES, GET TO THE FOUR WHEELER SAND PIT, CROSS IT, AND YOU ARE LOOKING AT THE SPOT, HAVE A GREAT SESSION.\r\n\r\nBy Chris Anderson','07257006','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (65,'Rockport Ledge','Quachita River','','US','US Central','AR','Malvern','Remmel Dam','500','3600','','34.394614','-92.842809','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=07359002','','Most notable for its almost worth something playhole (the rodeo boaters say). \r\n\r\nWater is generated from Remmel Dam on the Quachita River below Lake Catherine. \r\n\r\nTake the one and only Malvern exit off of I-30 and head towards Malvern. Turn right onto the street right before Walmart. You will immediately see a Bridge Out sign. Take the last road (dirt road) before the end of the road where the bridge is out. Stay left on the dirt road passing under the overpass. Just past the overpass the road will open up and there will be two roads (maybe three). Continue staying left. When the roads merge youll approach a road to the left that heads into a teardrop shaped parking area. Park your vehicle and walk down the magnificent steps which mysteriously appeared one very appropriate weekend. \r\n\r\nBy now you have seen the ledge and no itï¿½s not up or down river...youre there. It doesnt get bigger but it does get better.Put in and cross the first section of current. Once in the eddy, head to the top and start reaching in to the eddy line with your bow looking for the ledge. It is about 15 below the rock that forms your eddy. There is a small piece of current that is easiest to reach with a paddle, but hand paddles are the preferred method. If anything your paddling arms will get a good workout. \r\n\r\nYoure not going to get epic rides here but when you add it to a summer day at 100+ and some good friends, it is only then that youll understand why you stopped for a quick few sinks. \r\n\r\nThe releases are most often short but happen every day throughout the summer during the week. Most of the weekend releases are a bit shorter. \r\n\r\nYou get in a trance at Rockport and you learn how to wing the boat down. With your hips alone youll wing through the current causing a wet-dog-look out of your beautifully groomed toboggan. Rockport will sneak up on you, catching you without a breath. The longer the boat, perhaps the better. \r\n\r\nBy,\r\n\r\nBarton Perrier','07359002','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (67,'Fishers Ford','Illinois','','US','US Central','AR','Siloam Springs','Savory','100','','400','36.1235','-94.5174','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ar/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=07194800&set_logscale_y=1','','There is a small rapid on the Illinois river which runs west of Fayetteville into Oklahoma, called fishers ford. For more directions go to www.ozarkpages.com/whitewater and look under creek info. Fishers Ford is just under 30 minutes away from Fayetteville and it can be used year around, even in the dry season. The spot consists of a sloping ledge to the right, the water gains speed and drops off the ledge forming a small hole where the current comes together. The seam is directly behind the hole, both front and back cuts work well from the left and right sides of the current. There is also an excellent eddyline seam further down on the left that you can catch on your way back into the eddy. This is a low water spot usually running 100-400 cfs but never-the-less it yields helmet deep 5+ second rides on a regular basis. This is not an epic downtime arena, but it is a perfect place to perfect all your squirting technique. \r\n\r\nDirections\r\n\r\nThe playspot is on the Illinois R. south of Siloam Springs. Follow Hwy 16 West toward Siloam and turn on Hwy 244 West a short time after you pass Lake Wedington. Follow 244 for a couple of miles or so and take Cincinati Cr. Rd., a gravel road, to the north. You can look for the old, white Nicodemus Church sign that is mostly hidden by bushes at this turnoff. The Hwy 244 bridge over Cincinati Cr., a medium sized creekbed with a gravel bottom, is just past the turn you need to make, so if you cross it, youve gone a bit too far. If you reach Hwy 59, youve gone a little over a mile too far. Follow the gravel road north about a mile, and youll come to an intersection. Go straight on what is now Fishers Ford Rd. The road makes a few bends, but just keep following it north toward the river. When you come to the old metal bridge, park on the river left, upstream of the bridge and be sure to pull off the road. Dont block the little road leading down to the river by the bridge, since local fishermen use it to lauch johnboats. Unload and walk down to the river and put in and paddle down about 100 yards to the ledge. When youre finished playing, either paddle or walk back up the streambed to get back to the bridge. Please respect landowners rights around this spot, and DONT TRESPASS on the river banks at the ledge, which are clearly posted. Ask permission from the landowner in advance if you want to walk through the field to reach the playspot.\r\n\r\nBy,\r\nNoah Frazer','07194800','cfs','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (68,'Mulberry Spots','Mulberry River','','US','US Central','AR','Ozark','','1.5','3','5','35.6886','-93.7907','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ar/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=07252000&set_logscale_y=1','','North of I-40 in western Arkansas. For more directions go to www.ozarkpages.com/whitewater and look under creek info. This is a sedimentary creek which means it has deep pools and clean eddylines. There are many different runs possible on this river and nearly every eddy yields at least neck to helmet deep mysteries. But there are several specific spots that must be mentioned. From the put in at the Little Mulberry Creek to the take out at Birds Canoe rental (8miles which can be broken up many different ways) there are three main downtime arenas. \r\n\r\nNOTE:This spot had changed last time I was there in the spring of 2007 and was not as good for DT.\r\n1st: just around the corner from a low water bridge crossing is a rapid called PHD which has changed in the last 3 years to a mystery paradise. The current splits with the main channel flowing straight into the bank which creates 2 very powerful elevator eddies, the smaller channel comes in from the right at a 90% angle creating a crazy stationary whirlpool. This spot is tricky but has yielded 10-15+ sec deep mysteries during which there was no downstream movement, very unique and cool playground. \r\n\r\n2nd: about 2 miles below High Bank Access area the river narrows and runs along a rock wall on the river right. You will see a strong elevator eddy at the top and directly behind it is a smaller eddy on the right along the bluff. At the top of this eddy the river drops over a ledge and if you can catch the surge you are rewarded with a very fast and powerful mystery. Be careful to stay on a level flight path because the river is not very deep, although your head will still be at least 3 feet under water. There is also an access point just below this rapid, if the level is 3-3.5 feet on the gauge you can easily spend a lot of time here. \r\n\r\n3rd: 2 miles from the take out at Birds, directly below the largest rapid, Whoop and Holler (it is the ozarks), a ledge extends out from the river right and creates a very strong eddy with good downtime potential. It is fairly difficult to figure out but there have been some long deep rides here. \r\n\r\nThese are just 3 highlights of this short run on the mulberry, I have at least 3 other places downstream that have very good potential. The Mulberry River is an excellent squirt run, easy rapids, deep eddylines, and beautiful scenery. \r\n\r\nI have squirted the Mulberry for 9 years now and it is still one of my favorites. \r\n\r\nDirections\r\n\r\nNewton, Johnson, and Franklin Co., S1: Take Hwy. 23 north of Ozark form I-40. Put-in at Wolf Pen Recreation Area on NFR 1003 east of Hwy. 23. Take out at Redding Campground on NFR 1003. (Alternate take out is Byrds Campground east of Redding.) S2: Take out at Hwy. 23 bridge. S3: Take out at Milton Ford on NFR 1501 west of Hwy 23. S4: Take out at Hwy. 215 bridge north of Mulberry. (Alternate take out is dirt road south of Shores L.) \r\n\r\nBy,\r\n\r\nNoah Fraser\r\n','07252000','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (69,'Cowbell','Nolichucky','','US','Dirty South','TN','Erwin','Embreeville','600?','1800','4000','36.0980','-82.4363','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03465500','','Directions to the Nolichucky River, just upstream of Cowbell. The nearest town is Erwin, which is located in eastern Tennessee. Use this town for reference. \r\n\r\nFrom the North: On Highway 23,(aka I-26) take Exit 15, turn left off ramp. \r\nFrom the South: On Highway 23,(aka I-26) take Exit 15, turn right off ramp. \r\n\r\nAfter exiting as directed above:\r\nTurn right onto Temple Hill Road, the first right after exiting the highway. Go ï¿½ of a mile (you will pass a Holiday Inn) and turn left at the Chestoa Recreation Area sign onto River Road (which follows the Nolichucky River). Go ï¿½ mile and turn left crossing the bridge. Turn right immediately after crossing the bridge onto Jones Branch Road. Youll see a USA Raft sign. Continue for approximately 1ï¿½ miles to the end of Jones Branch Road. The campground is to the left. \r\n\r\nCowbell is a couple hundred yards downstream. \r\n\r\n1000 to 2000cfs is ideal level for Mysteryï¿½','03465500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (70,'Carousel','Ocoee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Ocoee','','','','','35.1233','-84.7194','','','There are a couple of spots on the Olympic Section of\r\nthe Ocoee, the best being right above the most\r\nsignificant rapid on this section. The upper is\r\npretty powered up so stay on your toes at this spot. \r\nThe spot is on river right just above Humongous rapid.\r\nThere is a small ledge against the bank here. The\r\ncurrent always seems to want to take you to the middle\r\nof the river when you are down so be ready to paddle\r\nlike hell back to the eddy when you surface. (I might\r\nnot be steering correctly, you might get a different\r\nsurfacing location from other folks).\r\n\r\nBy, Benji Salter\r\n\r\nHi there. I added a small edit to this post. The spot\\\\s name is Carousel.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (71,'Sweet Cheeks TN','Ocoee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Ocoee','Ocoee #2','1100','1250','1400?','35.1233','-84.7194','','','This is recognized\r\nby this weird looking rolling seam on river left just\r\nas Moon Shoot rapid flattens out. This spot serves up\r\n0-7 second mysteries. Have heard that once youre\r\ndown you should switch rotation from counterclockwise\r\nto clockwise and youll drop into the green room\r\nwhich is sort of an underwater eddy. Have been there\r\nonce on accident when my skirt blew. This is a fun\r\nspot. Can at least consistently get your head wet,\r\nhave seen folks do much better.\r\n\r\nBy, Benji Salter\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nNote- May be the easiest access & most rewarding pay off for new zombies. You can park and sink here or park at Slice and hit Frustration Alley on your way down to SC. Many ways to hit it. Nice place to hang out for a while while going down river.\r\n-JC','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (72,'Cats Pajamas','Ocoee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Ocoee','','','','','35.1233','-84.7194','','','At the bottom of this rapid there\r\nis a seam on river left right up next to the rock on\r\nriver left. It seems youve got to go as far back up\r\nstream as you can on this side of the river and do a\r\nregular entry. This spot is pretty powered up. I\r\nunderstand that long distance travel can be had. \r\nYoull have to probe it yourself or ask some of the\r\nvets. Mysteries can also be had on the river right\r\npour over. Downtime seems to depend on how boily it\r\nis.\r\n\r\nBy, Benji Salter','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (73,'Whirl Pool','Nantahala','','US','Dirty South','NC','Wesser','Hewitt','1','','4','35.3314','-83.6029','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00065,02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=03505550&set_logscale_y=0','','Fun spot, convenient access, deep pool (one of very \r\nfew on the Natty), but a few drawbacks: Timing is \r\ncritical and typical mysteries are just head under, \r\nits hard to get extended DT. Water is always cold (45-\r\n50 degrees) and the open boaters are completely \r\ninconsiderate in the squirrely eddy while they wait to \r\nsurf the small top wave. \r\nThe whirlpool is located about a mile below the \r\nFerabee Putin just past Quarry rapid (fun rodeo hole \r\nby the way). If youve never been there before, the \r\neasiest way to find it is to putin at Ferabee and \r\npaddle down until you find it (the whirlpools are \r\nobvious). Once you know where it is you can park on \r\nthe side of the road near the spot & hike down to the \r\nriver and upstream a little way. Its hard to see from \r\nthe road. \r\n\r\nThe Nantahala River is halfway between Topton and \r\nWesser, NC on US 19.\r\n\r\nBy, Kegs\r\n\r\n\r\nLocation, western North Carolina, upstream from the NOC outpost which \r\nis in Wesser NC, along Hwy 74.\r\n\r\nTo get to Whirlpool, go upstream from the NOC outpost about 5 miles. \r\nTurn around at Ferabee Memorial Park which is a large picnic area on \r\nthe right. Driving back downstream, park at the second large \r\npull-off on the left. There, a steep short trail cuts down to the \r\nriver and you walk upstream on the path for about 300 yards to \r\nWhirlpool rapid. This is a dynamic eddy line with fast current \r\ncoming around a right hand bend and an angular rock jutting out from \r\nthe left. The whirlpool forms about every 5 seconds. Consistent \r\nmysteries of about 3 to 6 seconds are possible. But...., dress like \r\nits winter because the water is cold year around. Wear gloves, \r\ndrytop, and a beanie. Interesting fact: Because of the consistent \r\ntemp of the water, in the middle of the winter it is warmer than \r\nrivers like the Noli. The water comes off the bottom of the highest \r\nlake in NC. Water quality is fantastic. The standard release level \r\nis good, up to about 4 feet. Watch out for large quantities of \r\nrafts, rafters, swimmers, and newbie boaters bobbing around the eddy \r\nout of control in the middle of the summer. Great place to sit and \r\nbe entertained between sessions.\r\n\r\nBy, Greg Hall','03505550','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (74,'Railroad','Salmon','','US','US Eastern','NY','Pulaski','Call 800-452-1742 Then enter the sight code number 365123 to get river level info.','700','750','850/900','43.5569','-76.1057','http://www.h2oline.com/365123.asp','','Take RT.81 to Pulaski, NY. (North west N.Y by lake Ontario ) Get off at the Pulaski exit 36. At the top of the ramp head to the East( right if coming from Syracuse, left if coming from Water town)On rt. 13, go to the first left hand turn and turn Left(rt.2A). You will cross the river. (This is where all the surface boaters putin. They call this Putin the trash compactor.) Keep going on this road until you come to the Railroad Tracks. At the Rail Road Tracks there is a small dirt pull off on the left, park there. Put on you gear and grab your boat ad get ready to walk. Not far maybe 400 to 800 yards. Walk down the Tracks on the same side you parked until you reach the river The Mystery spot is above the rail road bridge on river left in the recalculating eddy. There is a small wave that forms then turns in to a small wirl pool. Enter in to the wave as it forms at about a 45% angle. If you time it right it is a smooth drop with rides 7-15 seconds, and good rides up to 20 seconds. The river level should be at 750-850/900 cfs on the Water Line Report line. Call 800-452-1742 Then enter the sight code number 365123 to get river level info. Or go to the water line web sight-- http://www.h2oline.com/365123.asp -- for current release info.\r\n\r\nBy Jason Kirk','04250200','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (75,'Letchworth','Genesee','','US','US Eastern','NY','Dansville','portageville','0','8.75','9','42.5874','-78.0209','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=18_00065&format=img_default&site_no=04223000&set_logscale_y=0','','In Letchworth state park just below the lower falls. I was getting 5-8 second and longer drops almost every time I went in. It is kind of hard to get to you have to paddle up stream from the put in, get out portage around a short rapid, get in and paddle up stream over to river left ( some hard paddling) Walk up to the top of that, get back in you boat and paddle 300-500 yards under a foot bridge to the bottom of the last rapid below the lower falls, where there is a small horse shoe shaped pore over. At low water the water comes down the center and off the river left side slamming together and forming a nice seam. Paddle half way up the pore over that is on your right so your hip is even with the upper part of the notch in the pore over. Sink your bow in the foam on the river left side of the seam with a stern pry and then a cross bow draw to get your rotation going . Try and stay chin deep on the river left side of the seam ( you can see it from here) It will drift you into the good spot take a deep breath and Down you go just like Smoothie on the Ottawa. If you drift to far right you will smack the under water cliff and it will stop your rotation and up you will come. It might be possible to get longer rides here I will have to try it at different water levels. If the water is above 9.5 ft. you cant get to the spot. The river never get much lower than 8 ft. and we where there at 8.75 and it was good ! There is one more spot on the river that has very big whirl pools when the water is very low that looks to be very interesting. It is on the way up to the Falls spot. If it turns out to be good i will let you know!\r\n\r\nThe Put in is in Letchworth State park. Ask at the park entrance for a map, and how to get to the boaters put in. \r\n\r\nDirections\r\n\r\nTake Rt. 390 to Dansvill, NY Get off at Exit 5 ( the dansvill exit) Take Rt., 36 Two miles or so (I believe south or east) to Rt., 436 W. Folow 436, 15-20 miles. To the park entrance on your right. (436 does join up with Rt. 19 after it makes a right for a short distance, just before the park entrance.) \r\n\r\nBy, Jason Kirk\r\n','04223000','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (76,'Wing Dam (Playdium)','Delaware','','US','US Eastern','NJ','Lambertville','Trenton','3000','','5500','40.3546','-74.9462','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=05_00060&format=img_default&site_no=01463500&set_logscale_y=1','','The easiest way to get to us is by Interstate 95. Take exit 1 (Last exit in NJ before entering Pennsylvania) in New Jersey the Lambertville Exit. It dumps you on to Route 29. Take Route 29 North to both Scudders (about 1/2 mile from exit), and Lambertville Wing Damn (10-15 minutes from exit).\r\n\r\nFirst is at the Lambertville Wing Damn on the Delaware River. \r\n\r\nThe put-in to the wing damn section is behind the Inn at Lambertville Station Hotel at 11 Bridge St. Lambertville, NJ 08530. Drive past the Inn and around back to the boat launch. Park and put-in. Paddle downstream (flatwater) for about 300-400 yards to the wing damn. Eddy out on Pennsylvania (river right) side.To check out the spot by walking along the damn. At the most upstream corner of the damn is the mystery/squirt spot. It is generally a good squirt spot at all levels. There is a service eddy directly next to the damn (pennsy side, most upstream side). The trick is that the entry looks to be a righty charc out of the eddy. It is actually a lefty charc after you ferry across the small wave and attain back up and hit it lefty. You want to dip in above the wave at be aggressive in the hips for a good ride. From levels of 3000 to 5500 cfs on the Delaware River, Trenton gauge it forms a small wave/ripple. This spot is perfect (my opinion) at 3600-4200cfs. and will be good for people who wait to get the drops for solid 3-8 second drops. Not bad for NJ. Once you figure the spot out, it is one after another. \r\n\r\nBY, Brad Michael','01463500','cfs','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (77,'Scudders Falls','Delaware','','US','US Eastern','NJ','Lambertville','Trenton','11000','','13500','40.2657','-74.8491','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=05_00060&format=img_default&site_no=01463500&set_logscale_y=1','','The easiest way to get to us is by Interstate 95. Take exit 1 (Last exit in NJ before entering Pennsylvania) in New Jersey the Lambertville Exit. It dumps you on to Route 29. Take Route 29 North to both Scudders (about 1/2 mile from exit), and Lambertville Wing Damn (10-15 minutes from exit).\r\n\r\nThe spot is Scudders Falls in NJ. Basically if you start from Lambertville, NJ drive south on Route 29 outside of town, and for about 10-12 minutes. You will see a sign for Interstate 95 North off to the right with a right exit. Take this small road/ exit to 95. As soon as you take the right, make another right and go over a small bridge. You are now at a small park (name escapes me). Either park up top if gate is closed, or drive down to lower lot. This is a small class 2+ wave and eddy line here. The eddyline is gauged off the same gauge as the Wing Damn from above. But, this eddyline is only good from 11,000 cfs to 13,500 cfs. Its a pretty apparent eddy towards the bottom river left of the rapid. Its somewhat rocky and can put a little abuse on the right back edge of your boat as it too is a lefty charc. But a lefty charc with a rock at the sweet spot. If you want the nice drop, you will hit your boat 90% of the time. This is more of a quick down force then flushes you out at what seems to be 100 miles per hour. Those in the eddy should be aware of flying sharp ends. It would be a great setting for a Nealy cartoon of some squirtboater spearing some unassuming surface boater.\r\n\r\nBY, Brad Michael','01463500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (78,'z-turn','Lehigh','','US','US Eastern','PA','White Haven','White Haven','500','','900','41.0311','-75.7415','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=01447800&set_logscale_y=1','','Z- turn is about half way between the put in and Lunch rock on the upper section of the Lehigh river in Whitehaven,Pa. There is a big eddy on river left. in the middle of Z-turn. The entry is in the middle of the eddy not at the top like most Mystery spots. I have only bin there at 500 cfs and was getting 3-5 second rides. But it looks like it would really go off at between 750-900 cfs. There is a draw back. The river is only class 2 and very long, not a good river for running in a designation chop boat! \r\nIf you had a trailer for a mountain bike you can bike to the spot along a trail ( Level old railroad bed ) that runs right along the river. \r\nThere are some very promising looking features on this river in the first half above z-turn that might turn in to good DT spots with enough water! ( 900 or more cfs.)\r\n\r\nBY, Jason Kirk','01447800','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (79,'Kennebec','Kennebec','','US','US Eastern','ME','West Forks','','','','','45.3527','-69.8721','','','The Kennebec River Gorge is about 5 miles long and is constant Class IV= whitewater which increases in intensity from the put-in on, and culminates in Magic Falls which is a Class IV drop. The put in is about 12 miles off of Route 201 outside of the\r\nWest Forks, ME. While traveling north on 201 with the Kennebec river on your left take the right hand turn just before going over the bridge that goes over the Kennebec and into town. Follow this road all the way to Moxie lake where you will vear left and\r\nonto a dirt road over a bridge. The take out is about 3 miles down this dirt road. It is a left after your second of two small yellow bridges. It is the Carry Brook emergency access road. Follow the road all the way in to the parking lot. This will be your take out unless you want to do the 8 mile float out in your glass boat. Treck back out of this road and take a left back onto the main dirt road. This will lead you right into Harris Station. You will encounter and FPL (Florida Power and Light) gate where I believe the gate fee is still a dollar. Driver through the gate and stay on the pavement and head into the parking lot. If you get there real early (8am) you may be able to drive down and drop off boats. This is a commercially run river with 1200 allocations a day for the commercial rafting season. The\r\nrafts put in from 10am to 12pm and water flows are typically from 10am-2pm. Try and put in after the rafts, otherwise you will be avoiding tons of SPORTS (stupid people on rafting trips). The Gorge itself is characterized by 70ft cliff walls and very string and pushy currents. The river itself is very deep and having been down at fish level flows there are limited to no bottom hazards to be wary off while going deep. There are\r\nnumerous mystery spots along the river with the first being right off the bat at The Throat where the river begins to pick up momentum. Cathedral Eddy is also full of numerous lines varying in strength and all kinds of large boil lines to have\r\nfun with. There are usually a handful of squirters on the Kennebec on any given day and many private boaters to help with shuttle.\r\nCamping accommodations are numerous and river lies flow at The Marshall Hotel after a few beers. The water is incredibly clean and very warm in the middle of the summer.\r\n\r\nBy, Andrew Whitaker\r\n\r\nFor the latest flow information call (800) 557-3569 Dial 5 for Kennebec.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (283,'Cle Swimin Hole','Cle Elum','','US','US Pacific','WA','Cle Elum','','550','800 inflow','1500','47.383948','-121.095452','','','Head up to Salmon La Sac and just before you pass the cooper river bridge you will see a large rock in the river. Thats the spot','','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (284,'Kanpo','Tamagawa','','JP','','','','','','','','35.8028','139.2181','','','Tamagawaâ€™ new spot ,is â€œKanpoâ€.\r\nThe spot is near  by â€œKanpo no yadoâ€. That is a hotelâ€™s name.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (285,'Tombo','Ketagawa','','JP','','Shizuoka Prefecture','near Hammamatsu','','','','','0','0','','','Tombo was first explored by JT, Buddha, and Joel D. on Sunday the 12th of September, after the Squirtogether awards ceremony.  The spot is a few hundred yards downstream from the campground on the Ketagawa, at a left hand turn in the river.  The left side flow slams into a channel from the right, creating an epic smooth arena.  We decided to name it Tombo, which is Japanese for Dragonfly, as there were thousands of drangonflies flying around when we got there.  We sampled the spot until after dark and determined it to be easily as good as any other spot wed been to, including Borobus. The level was approximately .62 meters on the gage.  The following morning we sampled it at .57.  While it was still smooth, it was not nearly as epic as it was at .62. Our third session was at .59 and everyone got big mysteries.  The TN crew described it as being very similar to Fishing with Gandhi','','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (286,'Half Falls - not McKees','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Montgomery Ferry','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','4.0','4.5','5.0','40.491332','-76.949145','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=ctp&gage=harp1&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','Totally unconfirmed at this point-9/26/10.  Structure is very similar to McKees, but twice as many eddylines to inspect.  Runs higher than McKees.  Starts to look promising around 4 ft and up.','01570500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (81,'Dunbars','Lehigh','','US','US Eastern','PA','Lehighton','','2800','3000-6000','8500','40.8332','-75.7032','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/pa/nwis/uv?01449000','','Description: This is several bridge piers with a drop of ~ 2-3 ft through\r\nthe channels followed by a large recovery pool/eddy. The channels get\r\nprogressivly deeper and steeper to river left. Very convenient park &\r\nplay.\r\n\r\nAt low levels (<1000 cfs) only the left channel is deep enough for sinking but it provides two strong seams and a surfable wave train. There may be some large riprap at the top of the chute (under the trestle) so evaluate prior to sinking at the top. There is little obstruction out from under the trestle. As levels rise, the center channel opens and then river right.\r\n\r\nAt 1700+ cfs, the center channel has a good seam on the river right side,\r\nwhich can be tapped at several places, the river left line is very broad\r\nand confused. The river left channel is the strongest with well defined lines\r\non both sides and its wave train has flushed out considerably. The left seam\r\non this channel is fed by a strong compact eddy next to shore. The right seam\r\nof this channel should be tapped under the trestle for the strongest suck.\r\nThe river right channel is too shallow and rock strewn to mystery at this\r\nlevel but can still provide entertainment in the small eddy river right of\r\nthe chute.\r\n\r\nThe eddys & lines hold up to at least 6500 cfs although the saplings\r\ndownstream begin to form a strainer. Sink with caution at these levels.\r\n\r\nRiver: Lehigh\r\nLocation: Lehighton, PA\r\nDirections:\r\n* Mahoning Valley interchange of PA Turnpike NE Extension (I-476)\r\n* US-209 South to Lehighton (NOTE: South US-209 runs north between Lehighton\r\n& Jim Thorpe so careful with your internal compass)\r\n* Long US-209 bridge crosses the Lehigh River (lights at each end.)\r\n* Make right at end of bridge (stay on Rt 209 South, heading towards Jim\r\nThorpe)\r\n* ~ 1/2 mile from bridge, Rt. 209 splits & becomes ONEWAY, stay in right\r\nlane\r\n* make right at Dunbar Beverage (purchase apres squirt libations)\r\n* Follow dirt (primitive, but car accessible) road under RR trestle and to\r\nthe river, large cobble bar for parking.\r\n\r\n\r\nLehighton Gauge: (~1/2 mile downstream of trestle - no additional inflow\r\nbetween)\r\n\r\nBy,\r\n\r\nTim Luce','01449000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (189,'Deschutes Run','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Madras','','3000','','8000','45.1747','-121.0819','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14103000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','adding this in anticipation of some exploration there.\r\n\r\nthe classic run (class 3) is from Harpum Flat to Sandy Beach.. a 10 mile section.\r\n\r\nTechnically speaking, you need a permit to do the run ... look here to buy a $2 dollar pass online:  http://www.boaterpass.com','14103000','cfs','9','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (127,'Gyro','Columbia','','CA','','BC','Trail','Birchbank','4.0m (1500cms)','5.4m (2200cms)','6.2m (2700cms)','49.106137','-117.710719','http://www.bchydro.com/info/res_hydromet/data/bir.txt','','The City of Trail is 2-1/2 hours north of Spokane WA.  Heading through Trail on Highway 22A/3B, turn North (upstream) on 2nd ave for about a mile until you see Gyro Park on your left.  When first discovered at low water, this spot offered up rides long enough for 3-4 spins with virtually no downstream travel, hence, Gyro.  \r\n\r\nA small portion of the river comes into a large bay.  As it exits the bottom of the bay the stream is directed back towards the main flow where it collides at a right angle.  The best results require a small surf across the exit of the bay to access the seam higher up.  \r\n\r\nThe season usually starts at the beginning of August and continues through the winter until March when flows drop for a month or two.  When spring arrives there is a relatively short window between too low and too high.   ','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (83,'Forks','Lehigh','','US','US Eastern','PA','Belvidere','','','','','40.6889','-75.2029','http://pa.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=01446500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00010','','There are several bridge piers here with large sub-surface buttressing to act as a ledge when the levels are high enough . Theres also the seam where the two rivers join but theres no bottom feature to promote a drop. \r\n\r\nUnder proper conditions, with high Lehigh flows & a moderate level in the Delaware the convergence occurs at the pier closest to the Lehigh. With the high flow coming in at near right angles to the bridge pier and the Delaware current a very strong line forms under the bridge. Unfortunately, Ive not been able to sample the seam at those times, only observe it from my desk :-( \r\n\r\nOne of these days...\r\n\r\nTimothy Luce','01446500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (128,'Chassezac spot','Chassezac','','FR','','Rhône-Alpes','','','0.70 m','0.75 m','','44.405075','4.188988','http://www.rdbrmc.com/hydroreel2/station.php?codestation=514','','100miles south west of lyon in Ardeche. City of Les Vans\r\n\r\nTwo possibilities :\r\n  - From les vans take D104a and D452 towards Casteljau. In the place named Endieu 44.405558 4.196697 theres a small way that goes down to the river. A 15minutes walk down will take you to the spot.\r\n  - From les Vans go to CevenAventure campsite 44.408515 4.179454 http://www.ceven-inscriptions.com. You can drop in there. The spot is 1km downstream. The dropout is the camping at Mazet Plage 44.396403 4.199027\r\n\r\n\r\nSquirt gathering here at the end of april 2008 will update spot after the event.\r\nThe gauge is very tricky as all the summer it can be set at 0.70m. The best is to check that the graphic of Cotes has small variations. \r\nBest times are spring (april-may) and fall (october-november) depending on rain. In fall and winter the spot is very cold.\r\n\r\npierre says: [quote]I think late april is still the right time to come over to the Chassezac. Unless the winter would be very dry, which is no the case so far (lots of water in Ardèche these last weeks) youll certainly would catch some releases during the week. This is the main time of the year where they produce electricity with the river. Did you had daily releases last april? I guess it would be excactly the same scenario for next year. Just be warned that dam releases are still unpredictable and could occur for the entire day or for a few hours only.[-quote]','','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (129,'Darkside Eddy','Menai Straits','','GB','','North Wales','Menai Bridge','','','','','53.2253','-4.1633','','','','','cfs','14','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (84,'Beaver Drop','Delaware','','US','US Eastern','PA','Easton','Delaware River at Belvidere NJ','8900','9900, 16000','18500','40.6958','-75.2044','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/pa/nwis/uv/?site_no=01446500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00010','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=phi&gage=BVDN4','Beaver Drop is the local dunkin spot here in Easton. Although nothing epic, it does provide some down time at wide range of flows from spring high water to summer minimums. During summer, the difference in temperature between the Delaware & spring fed Bushkill can be 20 degrees or more, adding a new sensation to the help balance on the convergence line. You need to be in predominantly cold flows to get the Beaver Slap on the main seam - too much warm water & you only go neck deep and shoot over the strong suck zone. \r\n\r\nTOPOLOGY:\r\nThe feature is formed by a portion of the Delaware flowing between an island and the PA shore, then over a crumbling 2-step dam. Flow from the Bushkill Creek joins from river right at right angles flowing across the base of the dam.\r\n\r\nPREDICTED LEVELS:\r\nTo predict levels a few days in advance use the following link (5-7ft is 6-13kcfs)...\r\nhttp://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=phi&gage=BVDN4\r\n\r\nCHARCS:\r\nAt high water >11 kcfs the working area is right next the PA bank ~ 8ft up the Delaware from the Bushkill. There is a small eddy that feeds up to the upper step of the dam. Slip your bow into the downstream flow, just above the dam crest and set your hip as it swings past the lip of the dam. In most situations youll drop to within a few inches of the dam shelf, putting your head 1 ft under for a couple rotations. The shelf is ~10ft wide before dropping over the second drop into the Bushkill flow. The obstacle to extended DT is the reaction flow off the first drop bouncing off the ledge, causing an upswell just before the second drop. If you make it through that you can take advantage of the Bushkill currents to drop further.\r\n\r\nAt flows below 10kcfs the line moves out to the center of the dam where the upper section has collapsed onto the shelf. Depending on the levels it is possible to initiate off the remains of the top lip & float neck deep down to the second ledge where the two streams converge & drop, this is the 9 kcfs charc. \r\n\r\nIf the level is too low for that youll need to find the convergence of the two flows, cross over the Bushkill current & engage the Delaware flow at a point high enough up that youll get the drop off the second ledge and be able to spin your 1/4 or 3/4 turns to engage your edge the the converging Bushkill flows. The tricky part of all this is the variability of the two stream flows makes the convergence point move around from day to day. \r\n\r\nBelow 6500 or so there is a small eddy formed to the left of center in the main dam flow by a chunk of the upper dam creating a pourover & then a full fledged eddy. This can be used to stage for lefty charc into the convergence of the two streams as mentioned above or to use a righty into the main flow wave train. The convergence zone at the end of this eddy  can be quite strong resulting in a full mush to the unwary.\r\n\r\nLOCATION:\r\nBeaver Drop is 100 yds north of US-22 on PA 611 North. \r\n\r\nIf arriving in Easton on I-78 youll follow signs for downtown & 611 N. On 611 you pass a green link bar suspension bridge (free to/from NJ) on your right, as you approach the second bridge on  US-22 (tol from NJ to PA only), turn right to go under the bridge and stay on 611 N. After looping under the bridge you come to stop sign and a right turn onto the bridge over the Bushkill, look for a parking spot on the road. The path down to the creek is off the triangle of grass between the two streams & the road.\r\n\r\nIf coming from NJ on US-22 take the exit immediately off the toll bridge & find a parking spot.\r\n\r\nIf coming from the west on US-22, exit at the 4th Street exit (last exit in PA). Bear left at the light at the end of the ramp. Get into the left turn lane for the next light @ 3rd St. Turn left under US-22 & pass through the next light. As 3rd St bears right to climb the hill, turn right onto Bushkill Drive, a one-way road along the base of the hill. At the stop sign, turn right onto 611 South, park on or after the bridge.\r\n\r\nTimothy Luce','01446500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (85,'Tville','Farmington','','US','US Eastern','CT','tariffville','','1.8','2.3','3.2','41.9008','-72.7568','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ct/nwis/uv?cb_00060=on&cb_00065=on&format=gif_default&period=31&site_no=01189995','','- the gauge is Farmington river at tariffville on the ct usgs page. the best levels are 1.8/1.9 on the low side, and a little above 3 ft. on the high side. My favorite levels are between 2.2 and 2.5, but either way up or down it is still good. \r\n\r\n- To get to tville, take i-91 thru Connecticut...either north or south depending on where youre coming from. Take exit 40 off 91 towards bradley airport. Once you are off 91 you will be on another multilane highway, you will pass a few exits, but keep an eye out on the right hand side for the exit for rt. 20 towards East Granby, this is the exit you want. After you get off the exit ramp you will merge onto a road and almost immediately you will come to a set of lights. Take a left at the lights onto International drive...it will be divided for a bit, then merge into a regular 2 lane road...about a mile after it merges into a regular 2 lane rd. you will see a left hand turn called Spoonville rd., take a left onto this. follow Spoonville rd. and eventually you will come to a weird 3 way stop. after you pass the 3 way stop you want your second left...it looks like it is labeled Spoonville rd.. go down the hill and you will turn and run along the river. To get to the downtime spot, watch for the first road on the right once you are running along the river (this is a landmark). About 100 ft. after the first road on the right will be this little dirt road with a fence gate on the left hand side. you will see a little northeast utilities sign on the fencepost....just drive into the road and park along the side, but make sure you are out of the way so others can come through.\r\n\r\nHere is the gage.\r\n\r\nhttp://ct.water.usgs.gov/rt-cgi/gen_stn_pg?station=01189995\r\n\r\nBy, \r\n\r\nChris Towles','01189995','ft','17','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (86,'Canisteo Spot','Canisteo','','US','US Eastern','NY','Cameron','','4.28','','7.4','42.2208','-77.4199','http://ny.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=01525500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','','The spot is right next to the USGS river gage. The Seam is formed by the wall the USGS put up to get a better reading on the river level. When the river is 6.72- 7.4 the seam is on river right. At lower levels the seam is on river left. It works as low as 4.28 at that level you only get as deep as you forehead. The entry is a regular charc. You get a quick drop and a 3 to 5 second ride. Longer rides might be possible. I have not bin there enough to tell what level the seam works best. \r\n\r\nIt is located on Rt.119 in Cameron, NY. From Rt. 86 ( rt. 17 new name) in Painted Post by Corning, NY. Get on rt. 15 south Take the Addison Exit. Take a right at the bottom of the ramp on 417 going in to Addison. In Addison get on rt. 119 west it is a right hand turn, just before you cross the river. The river will be on your Left until you go through Cameron ( don’t blink or you will miss the town ) you then cross the river on a steel bridge. After about 1 mile or so you will cross back over the river on a newer bridge. Pull over and park right past the bridge . The seam the just down stream of the bridge.\r\nBy Jason','01525500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (87,'Dryway Section','Deerfield','','US','US Eastern','MA','Monroe','Deerfield #5, Monroe Bridge, MA','900','100','1200','42.6743','-72.9949','http://www.h2oline.com/255122.asp','','Take Rt. 2 to Charlemont. MA to get to the local outfitters (Zoar). They can help you with Info on the river and camping.\r\nTake Rt. 2 to Charlemont. MA to Zoar Road. After about 2 miles the road will come to a T, take a left at the T. Drive about ten minutes to get to the Dunbar Brook Picnic Area access road. Take a right onto the Dunbar Brook Picnic Area access road, follow it down the hill (1/10th mile) were you can park or, take a right and continue down the hill till you get to the (about a 1/4 mile) to the Dryway takeout parking area. To get to the Dryway put in continue another few miles up Zoar Road into the town of Monroe, in\r\nthe center of town take a right and follow the road across the dam to the put in area (1/10th mile). Put in parking is another 1/10th mile up the road.\r\n\r\nAccess to the Dryway takeout is via the Dunbar Brook Picnic Area access road. This is also the road that leads to the power plant, so be careful to observe posted no parking areas to keep the power companys access open. The town of Monroe has complained of boaters speeding through town, so keep it down. The Dryway is too great a run to lose over inconsiderate boater behavior. Also, State police frequently run radar and ticket on Rte 2 and Zoar Road.\r\n\r\nWater level information for the Dryway is available through the Deerfield River information phone (888 356-3663). Listen for the spill at the #5 station dam. A schedule of the release dates for the coming year can be obtained from a local outfitter at. http://www.zoaroutdoor.com/home.htm\r\n\r\nThe Dryway section of the Deer Field River has two good spots. \r\nThe first is about half way down the river on river right where the rafters stop to take a break. There is a rock that creates a small pore over. Paddle up to this spot facing the river right shore, slide in to the pore over leaning your boat down stream. Once all the way in drop your right hip and Down you go! The ride is only a couple of seconds before you have to surface, because of the rock down stream that is taunting you to come visit.  Please be aware that getting to and from the first spot requires passing through Class 3 and 4 water.\r\n\r\nThe next and probably the best spot on the river is 100 yards up stream from the takeout. There is a rock in the middle of the flow that only barely sticks out of the water. Enter the seam at 45%, as the water builds on the rock dive you bow in about a foot deep then impact your hip. You will get a good 5-10 second ride here. This spot has the potential for longer rides. There is one problem with the takeout spot. If the water in the lower reservoir is not low enough the Mystery spot is then covered with water. As far as I know there is no way of telling if the spot is submerged except for going to look at it.\r\n\r\n----------------------------------------------------------------\r\nEric who lives just 15 minutes from CJs told me about another spot(not sure if it the same as the two mentioned above) that is a convergance at the bottom of a small island, directly under the railroad tracks. Got 5-8 second mysterys there... this is the only spot ive sampled on the dryway section. it was pretty fun. i updated the map to point to this spot. Eric said the water release gets to this spot in just 20 minutes... so hit it first, then drive down to CJs when the water gets there.\r\n-weaver\r\n-------------------------------------------------------------------','255122','cfs','18','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (88,'Consumption Junction (CJ)','Deerfield','','US','US Eastern','MA','Charlemont','Fife Brook Dam, Florida MA','700','800-1000','1500','42.6405','-72.9265','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ma/nwis/uv/?site_no=01168500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','http://www.h2oline.com/255123.asp','Well, I found a really sick new DT spot. I have to first off give credit to Chris Martin, as he was the one who first told me of the spot a few years back. We looked at it, and Chris tried hopping into it without a whole ton of success, so I kinda wrote it off. I went back there today to actually try it myself, and I was floored. The spot is on the Fife Brook section of the Deerfield river in Massachusetts. The spot is at the confluence with the\r\ncold river, but the squeeze and the eddyline are actually formed by the convergence of the Deerfield with itself after it wraps around an island.  The entire thing reminds me of smoothy as far as entry and things like that are concerned. The eddyline is extremely benign looking... it looks just like a small convergence of currents feeding into a deep pool. There are no real whirlpools, and not really many boils to speak of. The entry is almost exactly like smoothy once you get near the squeeze. What you do is paddle down the main current and across the small V shaped eddy just above the convergence. you aim for the secondary current that meets the main flow just above the convergence. You hit the current and drop up to your shoulders, and slow motion screw down as you get sucked towards the squeeze. When you\r\nhit the squeeze, its just like smoothy...you feel the tug, grab a breath and drop in. Once youre down its incredibly smooth...I dare say smoother than smoothy. There is almost no current underwater, and not a whole lot of layers to speak of. however, once youre in, there isnt much that brings you back to the surface. If you hit it right, you will continue to drop deeper and deeper (6-7 ft), otherwise you can just hang 2-3 ft. below the surface as long as you can hold your breath. It reminds me a bit of the spot at pushbutton on the Ottawa (the little swirlies in the flatwater near the island) in that there isnt much current there, but once youre in you will just hang at the same level forever. The water is incredibly clear, and you can see the surface above you the whole time cause its basically flatwater above. I was consistently hitting big rides (15 sec range) and it was extremely easy on the body. Its defiantly a long boat spot, cause you need a boat that can just sorta hang underwater, but if you have the right boat and\r\ndecent technique at screwing in, hold your breath! Im pissed I never went there before this. I feel like a little kid on x-mas right now, you couldnt tear the smile off my face. The spot is park and play. Its a benign looking spot, but if you have the screwing down charc dialed you can go big there. \r\nIts a long boat/ hands paddle spot for sure.  Chris T.\r\n\r\nParking for Consumption Junction(CJ) by Bruce K\r\nCJ Parking has changed. The town/state put up no parking/live parking signs in the old parking spots\r\n1 - Find Zoar Outdoor on Rte 2 in Charlemont, MA\r\n2 - Head west on Rte 2, in 2.2 miles from Zoar, take a right onto Tea St Exd (an unmarked road where someone rents/sells tubes).\r\n3 - Go to the end of the road and park in an orderly fashion.  This is the last parking spot that is close, so we want to protect it.\r\n4 - Grab your boat and gear, cross the railroad tracks onto Rte 2, turn right and walk .2 miles.  The mystery spot will be on your right where the two rivers converge. Look for the path marked by stickers on the guard rail.  If you don\\\\t want to cross the railroad track or if there is a train, you can walk back down Tea ST Exd, turn right and walk .3 miles.\r\n\r\nWater gets to CJ about three hours after it is released from the Fifebrook Dam and (as you can figure) shuts off at CJ three hours after the flow is shut off at the Fifebrook Dam.  \r\n\r\nClosest camping is at Mohawk Trail State Forest, about 3 mins / 1.2 miles from CJ:\r\nhttp://www.mass.gov/dcr/parks/western/mhwk.htm\r\n\r\nA little more history, I met up with Chris Martin one day after running the dryway in 2001. We got to talking and I told him about this spot I had checked out, at the time I was calling it the Rope Swing due to the rope swing on the river left shore. I was having moderate success with head dunks in my Angst. Chris was the first to hit it big with his Shred and it was amazing watching him. Because of his epic rides he got to name it Consumption Junction which was all to fitting. Jay D','01168500','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (214,'clifden','clifden salt lake','','IE','','co.galway','clifden','','','','','53.4736','-10.0191','','','Clifden is a tidal race that runs through two arches of a bridge and the second arch forms a lovely play hole and two nice eddy lines.Clifden hole is one of the most beautiful places to go squirting. Its tidal so its saltwater. The feature works all year round and the water is quite warm in the summer months. \r\n\r\nHowever Clifden only works on Spring Tides, the feature forms about 2 hours before Galway Harbour High tide. The tide must be 14 foot+ to be any good. It works best at around 16 ft +/-.\r\nIts a great place to be for a couple of nights with friends. For camping go to Dun Loughan, a nearby beach with camping in the dunes. There can be surf here as well if youre lucky. \r\n\r\nHow to get there \r\nTake the N59 out of Galway City which leads directly to Clifden which is about 70km from Galway. The drive is through one of the most scenic areas of Ireland, Connemara. When in Clifden you need to take the road to Ballyconeeley. So drive into the town and as you approach Market street instead of turning right onto this street go straight ahead. The road narrows and you drive over a small bridge. The road widens again as you leave the town and drive for about 1 km and you will see a school on your right. Park here. \r\n\r\nYou can paddle across the saltlake to the hole from here (10 mins paddle). Climb over the wall on the opposite side of the road and paddle across the bay to the right until you come to the bridge. \r\n\r\nIf you want to drive and take a look: about another half a kilometer from the school is the bridge and arches that form the hole. \r\n\r\nTo find dun Loughan (good luck with this!) head towards Ballyconeley but turn right before here. Youre looking for a turn to the right - the sign says dunloughan but its hard to see - instead look for a no dumping sign. Drive down here until there are three sand paths. Follow one of these across the dunes untill you come to the beach. Find somewhere to camp here. Be discrete and clean up before leaving and respect the local area please! \r\n\r\nIf you are in Galway city pick up tide tables from Galway Harbour Company behind the docks or from Galway Maritime on Merchants Road. Also River Deep Mountain High have tide tables and can give you advice. Failing this chase Internet tides but I cant guarantee how accurate this is. Ive always used Galway Harbor Company Tide tables! \r\n\r\nThe land around the saltlake is private property - please respect the area. Thats why it is best to park at the school and paddle across the lake. Please do not block any gates.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (89,'Fascination Alley','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Albright','Albright','500','700-1,800','1800','39.3971','-79.6887','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv?03070260','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=pbz&gage=psnw2','This multi-faceted spot is named after a Black Oak Arkansas song for a place where you can get anything you want....   It lies about 100 yards below Calamity Rock Rapid on the Narrows section of the Cheat- 10 miles upstream of the Canyon. It is frequented throughout the summer because the medium low levels are the best. \r\n  There are many charcs available- most of them developed in recent years.  The favorite charcs are available at the medium levels and are based off the eddy in the middle of the river(attainers left of the slab).  The easiest charc is to go backcut and travel.  You can also go backcut and stall and hang around 5-6 deep in the Ballroom at the top of a boil pile in the eddy.  At this point you can spin much faster without traveling.  The best realmhogs often leave this arena by dropping deeper and then traveling.  You can also go very high in the eddy and drop hard and stall right next to the rock, spinning slowly (you might bump the rock). \r\n  You can also get traveling and Ballroom charcs going regular and/or dropping early.  The traveling charcs tend to be initiated in the back of the second baby wave at the top of the eddyline.  But you can also initiate regular on the attainers right side of the first wave-  Carls Charc-  named after Carl Gittings who pioneered the righty regular charcs here.\r\n\r\n  The river left charcs tend to be simpler- but yield good results at the lower levels.  The easiest charcs are basically a lefty regular where you drop steep and fast and come back for support from the eddy- traveling slowly spinning.  The other lefty is where you drop about 3 from the shore rock- tapping into a subtle seam generated from the rocks pillow and drop deep and cross the slab to get support from the river right eddy.  There you stall until the mystery plays out.  A final regular charc is to drop hard and travel to the boil piles on river left down below and exploit them for all youre worth.  Backcut charcs are also available but tend to stall pretty much- although you can get your head wet pretty well.\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you are driving up from Albright- head towards Rowlesburg and after you see some easy class 3 rapids close to the road slow down and look for a huge rock in the river as high as the road (the road is bending right here).  The next pull off to the left is the parking spot (like a 20 car spot).  There is a trail down at the upstream and downstream ends of the parking  lot.  The downstream trail is the easiest but often has locals partyin it up- so dont leave shoes on the shore here.   The Alley is at the top of the eddy here (duh).\r\n\r\n\r\nCFS at Albright is the way to go. Anything 700-1,800 is worth traveling for. We play as low as 500- but don\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\t talk about it\r\nby jim\r\n\r\n\r\nWondering how to predict when The Alley is in?? Heres some links.\r\n\r\nThe WV streamflow page will get you to Rowlesburg, Parsons, Bowden, Cheat Bridge, Hendricks, and Davis all upstream from the alley.\r\n\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/current/?type=flow\r\n\r\nThe Parsons prediction is very useful for planning.\r\n\r\nhttp://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=pbz&gage=psnw2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1\r\n\r\nThe AFWS is another excellent tool. Fascination Alley is fed from streams in Randolph, Tucker and Preston counties.\r\n\r\nhttp://afws.net/states/wv/wv.htm\r\n\r\nThe USGS Rowlesburg gauge is no longer reporting, so switched the gauage to Albright.','03070260','cfs','12','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (90,'Slam Dunk','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Albright','Albright','2','','3','39.4947','-79.6443','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03070260&set_logscale_y=0','','This is a powerful mystery spot about 60 yards downstream of Armadillo Rock, halfway down the Cheat Canyon. A large low rock splits the main slab of the currents just to the left of center. You leave the eddy breaking left and try to engage your upstream hip fully and drop pretty much level but winging down. Only do three turns underwater at the most or you will have a chance to whack a shallow rock that waits off to river right or you may go too far downstream to recover into the eddy easily. This is a good place to perform dervishlike black attacks and is an excellent play spot at the right levels (2-3). The drawdown is profound and can be disconcerting but there is no history of anyone ever having a bad ride or getting whacked here. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nPaddlers go by gauge on bridge in Albright.\r\nAlb. Bridge = (1.55 * Alb. PS) + 0.5 \r\n\r\nso go to this page and use the calculator:\r\nhttp://www.keelhauler.org/khcc/cheatalawa.htm\r\n\r\nADMIN NOTE: THE CURRENT FLOW YOU SEE BELOW IS FROM THE ALBRIGHT GAUGE, NOT THE BRIDGE!','03070260','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (91,'Cueball','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Albright','Albright','2.3','','2.5','39.4947','-79.6443','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03070260&set_logscale_y=0','','Cueball is famous for its blasting hole which is similar to Swimmers Hole on the Lower Yough- but cranked up about double. The optimal level for the hole is 2.3-2.5 when it is fluffed up a bit and has strong shoulders but still an intense slab. Good squirt boaters can achieve blasting transitions and shudder Rudders at will here although it isnt easy. There is an excellent mystery spot on downstream 100 feet just to the left of the big splat rock. Here the currents pile into steep sided bedrock slabs which form the river left shore and form ponderous but fickle seams. The trick is to wait just on the upstream flow section of the seam area and wait for a big seam to lumber your way. When it does attack it quickly and drop fast winging down hard but level into the encroaching slab and seam. If you get lucky your head will disappear for a few seconds and you will get up to 4 deep as you spin. This is a very powerful and dynamic arena and doesnt lend itself well to roaming. But it is definitely worth a detour if you are ever passing by. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nPaddlers go by gauge on bridge in Albright.\r\nAlb. Bridge = (1.55 * Alb. PS) + 0.5 \r\n\r\nso go to this page and use the calculator:\r\nhttp://www.keelhauler.org/khcc/cheatalawa.htm\r\n\r\nADMIN NOTE: the current flow you see below is from the Albright gauge, not the bridge.','03070260','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (92,'Recyc','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','albright','Albright','0','','6','39.4947','-79.6443','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03070260&set_logscale_y=0','','Short for Recyclotron this was once one of the best mystery spots in the Appalachians. After the flood of 1996 the pool level below the slide type hole dropped 2 and destroyed the mystery capabilities the arena had. When it was good- from 1985-1996 you could easily get 3-5 seconds DT and often 8-10 seconds. This was one of the first places where paddlers experimented with big DT (over 6 seconds). It was named by Jim Snyder after Paul Marshall named the flume-like drop below it- the Cyclotron in the spring of 1986. The Cyclotron disappeared in the flood of 1996. The best charc was breaking left from the center to dive with a shallow charc into the thin slab and drop sideways to a point where the bedrock bottom fell away. At this point you could drop deeper into an underwater eddy with the currents passing just over your head. Then when you had enough you could easily hit the up button and erupt vertically next to the waiting mystery riders. A few people and boats were speared this way with rude bows. You could also break right from the center and get respectable DT although you would often travel in this mode and so couldnt roam as peacefully. In the final days before the 1996 flood, squirt boaters were starting to have a problem with boogie board riders who would drop in for verrry long rides- to the excitement of no one. They ended up trying to work next to the boogie boardom and that was often a successful solution. When Recyc was big - anything over 3- it was (and still is) way burly and gave violent and dynamic- although not impossible rides. Jeff Snyder was master of riding these levels- often jumping in at 6 and higher. At this level the foam pile is at least 6 tall and 50 wide and the slab is about 2 thick. The ride is often so violent you often become an end throwing speck. Jeff seemed to bide his time calmly and well though in all conditions. There is good footage of him in there with just handpaddles at 6 in the video Token of My Extreme. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCHEAT:\r\n\r\nPaddlers go by gauge on bridge in Albright.\r\nAlb. Bridge = (1.55 * Alb. PS) + 0.5 \r\n\r\nso go to this page and use the calculator:\r\nhttp://www.keelhauler.org/khcc/cheatalawa.htm\r\n\r\nADMIN NOTE: THE CURRENT FLOW YOU SEE BELOW IS FROM THE ALBRIGHT GAUGE, NOT THE BRIDGE!','03070260','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (93,'What Rapid','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Albright','Albright','','','','39.4947','-79.6443','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03070260&set_logscale_y=0','','What Rapid is the last significant rapid in the Canyon but still about 2.5 miles from the take-out. At the very bottom of the rapid is a large rock splitting the currents in the center of the river. You eddy up behind the left side of the rock and leave the eddy very close to the rock with a steep diving charc. You have to wing down as you are dropping vertically. If you do it right you will be pulled down abruptly and sent for a spin or two before the currents force you up- very similar charcs and conditions to Trash Compactor on the Lower Gauley. The thing to remember here is to not travel back into the eddy underwater if you can help it. There is a rock about 4.5 deep on the eddy line and it can give you a rude whack if you dont give it some space. \r\n\r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\n\r\nPaddlers go by gauge on bridge in Albright.\r\nAlb. Bridge = (1.55 * Alb. PS) + 0.5 \r\n\r\nso go to this page and use the calculator:\r\nhttp://www.keelhauler.org/khcc/cheatalawa.htm\r\n\r\nADMIN NOTE: THE CURRENT FLOW YOU SEE BELOW IS FROM THE ALBRIGHT GAUGE, NOT THE BRIDGE!','','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (94,'Last Mystery','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Albright','Albright','','','','39.5937','-79.7468','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03070260&set_logscale_y=0','','There is a little known mystery spot just above the final riffle going into Jenkinsburg. It is at the bottom left of the rapid above the riffle and is only distinguished by a low lying rock with strong deep currents to the left of it- almost next to the shore. You break out high going right with a steep diving charc and try to link up with a seam about 18 beyond the eddy. If you get it right your head will disappear for a couple seconds. You travel a lot and cant get much support from the eddies so it is very fickle but worth a stop if you have any energy left. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nPaddlers go by gauge on bridge in Albright.\r\nAlb. Bridge = (1.55 * Alb. PS) + 0.5 \r\n\r\nso go to this page and use the calculator:\r\nhttp://www.keelhauler.org/khcc/cheatalawa.htm\r\n\r\nADMIN NOTE: the current flow you see below is from the Albright gauge, not the bridge.\r\n','03070260','ft','13','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (95,'Good Morning Good Morning','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','','','','','38.2849','-80.8420','','','This is an un-named place downstream of Initiation Rapid about 100 yards. A large rock splits the main currents and creates an obvious eddy to try. You break out bearing left and can go regular or backcut. People rarely get decent downtime here though but it is a good place to work out early trip jitters and get tuned to your equipment. Its also a good place for screws- even in a rodeo boat. The best charc is a hard fast drop close to the top of the eddy and you might get a few spins before the currents urge you up. This isnt a bad place to sample but not a wise place to spend a lot of energy and get cold early in the trip. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (96,'Spot Below Pillow','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','','','','','38.2849','-80.8420','','','This is another un-named spot down a bit from- but in sight- of Pillow Rock Rapid. A modest sized rock splits currents obstinately near the river left shore. The small eddy is powerful and dynamic and there is often kayak and raft traffic passing by so you have to be on your toes to get your timing to jive with the traffic. The charc is short sweet and powerful but quite worthwhile. Use some speed to pierce in close to the rock- bearing left. Drop steep and fast with significant winging down in a near vertical mode. Youll get pulled under eagerly but then spit back up after just a turn. Still it is dynamic and smooth and easy on the body. The eddy cant take many paddlers but this spot is always worth a stop on your way by. This is another cool place for big black attacks or light loops.\r\n\r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (97,'Sweet Cheeks WV','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','Belva','2400','2800','3200','38.2039','-80.9310','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03192000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','This is a little understood and used mystery spot which is a favorite of old schoolers. It was named by Eric Lindberg and Whitney Shields back in the ancient days of the sport because substantial mysteries result in a gentle spanking off the bottom of the river. It lies around the corner from Pillow Rock and is a very obscure ripple in the currents below a riffle- pretty much in the center of the now sedated river. The most used charc is a slow dropping backcut. Come out of the attainers right eddy with a lot of speed to cross the 30 of currents you need to. Use this speed to transfer into a lateral dropping charc as you wing down with the left hip to tap into meager currents falling off an underwater ledge. Stay very flat and spin slowly and expect a second push of energy from the significant downstream currents you just crossed. People who get really big DT here (over 7 seconds) then tap into a juicy seam which starts right after the initiation zone and proceeds very far downstream. You can turn slowly or just proceed downstream on a kind of straight mush move like charc. You can also use a regular charc- bearing your bow to the left in the initiation zone- but this is a complicated charc which is really a sophisticated form of mush move bearing left and looking downstream. For this charc leave the eddy and cross the currents and enter the initiation zone a bit more upstream than you otherwise would. This place is definitely worth a good stay as it is plastic repellent and even easy to work around the significant raft traffic. \r\n\r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html','03192000','cfs','12','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (98,'Sherlock','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','','2000','','2500','38.2849','-80.8420','','','This is one of the most powerful and fickle mystery spots on the entire Gauley. It lies just to river right of Postage Due rock below Sweets Falls. It was named by Jim Snyder around 1989 because if you do it right you can Sure Lock into big DT as you solve the mystery. The best levels are 2,000- 2,500 cfs. People rarely do it right. This is firstly difficult because rafts often tie up in the eddy for long lunches and completely block the entrance charc. HAHA! Tough Luck they laugh. If there are no rafts there it is still a difficult approach. There are strong currents encroaching from the right as they exit the Room of Doom. Then you are pressed close to the undercut Postage Due rock - whos steep face often gets in the way of your right blade. because of this it is advisable to enter the approach eddy with some speed so you can coast through the tenuous final feet before you engage the slab. Enter the slab within two feet of the rock. You dont need a steep dive but you would do well to wing down strongly. You will zoom into travel mode quickly and finally encounter support from the eddy about 10-15 downstream. If you have been able to get deep by this point you are in for some real big DT- over 10 seconds. You may travel a bit downstream and chances are you will be at least 4-6 deep. Remember to exit breaking left to re- attain the eddy before you travel too far downstream or getting back will be very difficult. A cool aspect of this arena is that it usually features many hundreds of raft customer spectators who get their first look at mystery moves. This often results in loud rousing cheers from the peanut gallery (uh... if you do well- otherwise its possible to provoke confusion and laughter- so this arena is not without risk). \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (99,'Mastercard/Visa','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','','','','','38.2849','-80.8420','','','This is a very powerful drop zone halfway down the last rapid of the Upper Gauley. It involves a 2 high pourover with a soft shoulder on attainers right. You eddy up behind the hole and break out bearing right. Pierce your bow into the slab and then proceed to quickly engage your left hip into the slab. Wing down and prepare for dynamic but short (3-4 seconds) DT. You will be traveling fast towards rocks immediately downstream so dont lurk or roam. Just blast down and back up and catch your breath because it is pretty exhilarating. This arena is so powerful you can even disappear rodeo boats here. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (100,'Last Chance','Upper Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','Belva','2400','3000','3600','38.2228','-80.9876','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03192000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','(AKA that spot at the takeout for the upper)\r\nThis little obscure un-named spot is actually the home to a lot of fun! In recent years people have been destination boating here by driving into the take out at Panther Creek. It lies at the river right bottom of the last rapid of the Upper Gauley. It is a small low rock on attainers left bordering some modest currents with a delicious shape. Come out high and drop your bow deeply but also count on significant winging down with your left hip. Turn quickly underwater back into the eddy you left for some support but then proceed to turn slowly without traveling too far to attain fines DTs of 5 seconds or more. This place proves its the shape and not size of the currents which dictate how well you can drop. People often enjoy spending a half hour or more here-no matter how tired they are- because it is real easy on the body. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html\r\n\r\nDirections to Last Chance and the Upper Gauley Takeout:\r\n\r\n1. From the put-in head west on Hwy. 129.\r\n2. In Poe, at the white church, turn left onto Backus Branch Road.\r\n3. At a Y at a run-down trailer, turn right (unpaved, steep, winding). On Google map, from the Y the left road is County Road # 22/1 (Vinton Road) and the right road is Panther Mtn Road, or Poe Vinton, or County Road # 11/1\r\n4. Go over a large hill on County Road # 11/1 and drop down the other side.\r\n5. At the T intersection (with COunty Road #22), turn left. When you see a field on the left after about 100 yards, turn in and park.\r\n6. Heres a link to a Google map of the field. You can back-track from there.\r\n\r\nhttp://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&source=s_q&hl=en&geocode=&q=poe,+wv&sll=37.0625,-95.677068&sspn=50.777825,78.837891&ie=UTF8&ll=38.226428,-80.992584&spn=0.003102,0.004812&t=h&z=18','03192000','cfs','15','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (101,'Trash Compactor','Lower Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','Belva','700','700-3400','3400','38.2397','-81.0389','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03192000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','This is a special spot at the way bottom right of Junkyard Rapid. It was named by Dale Adams around 1993 (?). Its against the river right shore and plunges deeply off the side of an small underwater rock. You come in with speed but coast your final charc (good technique anywhere). Come in very close to the rock- almost scraping it and dive steep and fast with a plunging charc while you wing down hard in a vertical mode. You will soon gain support of the eddy which powers up the slabs ability to drive you deep. Good riders can easily go very deep for over 7 seconds. There is a bit of travel involved but its not like youre roaming. You can also do powered up exits because the squeeze here is sooo dynamic. Timid or inexperienced boaters usually get lesser results here. Keep your charc clean and simple because this place is so powered up that it can torque your body if you are waffling around. Dont fight it- find your way to the center of the earth here. If you put too much into it- it will bite back and you might even end up getting dogged around or doing an ignoble roll in front of your friends. So be careful- but enjoy! Its one of the best spots on the river. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html\r\n\r\nThere is another Mystery realm just 30 feet downstream from Trash Compactor. In fact, it is possible to come up from a Mystery at Trash Compactor and then drop right into another seam for an even better ride.\r\n\r\nWhile Trash Compactor itself is best at higher flows (3000-3400 cfs), the lower seam is better at lower flows (700-2400).\r\n\r\nAbout 30 feet downstream from Trash Compactor the main flow collides at a right angle with a series of jet currents that are all parallel. This forms a long seam. You can approach the seam from any angle, but the best angle seems to be from the jet currents.\r\n-Harry','03192000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (102,'Twisted Sister','Lower Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','Belva','2400','2800','3200','38.2230','-81.0568','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03192000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','This is the most famous and accommodating mystery spot in West Virginia. Which isnt to say its not fickle. Even homeboys often sample the Sister for an hour before she yields the good stuff. It is about 2 miles into the Lower Gauley near some play waves which are usually littered with plastic- above Upper Mash Rapid. It is a mere wrinkle at the way bottom left of the rapid. It features an underwater ledge- where you get your down force, a large supporting eddy- which maintains excellent downtime, and a couple noteworthy rocks- which it behooves you to work around. It is successfully worked with regular and backcut charcs. Big downtime here is over 20 seconds and involves a lot of travel- but that is the Schnelle Zone. Most paddlers tap into 3-7 second drops with excellent sweet aesthetics. It was named by Eric Lindberg and Whitney Shields around 1990 and has remained a favored haunt of shadow riders since then. It was named that because they liked the name- not because of anything going down easy or juicy seams or anything like that. The regular charc usually yields the best downtime but is often hard to cypher out- especially for beginners here. The trick is to leave the eddy consistently- about15-18 inches away from the upstream rock. Travel with some speed across the approach currents hitting you from the right and generate some lateral speed which will feed you into the maw of the abyss. Look for the farthest right corner of the mini-wave there and approach that spot with your bow sunk about 1 but sitting up centered over your wing. The idea is to engage your hip fully and smoothly in the upstream slab which is plummeting quietly over the invisible ledge. If you do it right you bow will clear over the ledge with only inches to spare- even though the ledge is about 15 under the surface and hard to see. Use a single sustained stroke to smooth and guide the impact with the slab. Once you hit- drop fast with a smooth wingdown and turn back sharply into the eddy. This is not a good time to travel. Once youve re-established contact with the eddy you can keep spinning at a nice pace and prolong your downtime. There are special concerns about traveling too far here also- which I will mention later. Another good option is to drop fast to about 4 deep and then do a full loop (barrel roll) on your way back to the surface. This is where loops were first developed by Jim Snyder in the fall of 1996. You can also wait until you are nearly breaking the surface and do a Retarded Loop or wait until your head breaks the surface and do a Light Loop. You can also do stunning and awesome mobiusequences here to really show your stuff- although homeboys almost never do because they are saving their energy and feet for downtime. The backcut charc is also very effective here. Approach the same way but a bit more downstream like you are trying to catch a surf on the mini-wave. Then deeply engage your bow in the furthest right tiniest corner of the mini-wave and use a powerful sustained up-directed backstroke on the right to jam your left hip into the slab. You dont need to wingdown much here because you are going down big time no matter what if youve done the approach right. The best thing to do next is to stall or use some magic force to sustain spins against the whirlpool energies. No one knows exactly how this works- but it sure does here! Its also fun and effective to stop your spin and reverse it. The one thing its not a good idea to do is to travel fast backwards along the ledge in this mode. There are 2 underwater rocks of concern here. Both are about 4.5 deep and a ways away from the drop zone but still quite accessible. They are called the Pinning Rock and the Rock That Waits. The Pinning Rock is out in the center of the river and is usually encountered by mystery riders traveling backwards along the ledge from a backcut approach. You will get there in about 3 seconds from a very deep drop and will have a half second of turbulence to warn you that a hard crash is imminent. This is your one chance to hit the up button. Often people who drop deep and travel here see shadows of neighboring rocks pass by above them on their way. If you hit the rock- which has been done too often- quickly turn vertical and try to splat your way off the face. People who impact this rock often get deep scars on their hulls and report that the hull crushed on them- a very bad sign. But no one has ever been pinned seriously and most people just live by the discipline of not roaming into the neighborhood. The Rock That Waits gets a lot of visitors. It is down in the eddy- just on the eddy side of the eddy line about 25 downstream of the drop zone. It takes a deep drop and about 3.5 turns to find yourself parked there. You have to stay deep the whole way to really visit. When Jeff Schnelle gets his big downtime here he has to navigate past this rock underwater. Im not sure its well marked at all, but there is distinct turbulence for a full second before you get there. A good way to guarantee that you will never park on the rock is to keep your boat only 4 deep in this area. This way you will pass over the rock for sure. Five feet deep is asking for it though- so be precise. It helps to open your eyes and keep a reading on the surface so you know how deep you are if you venture down that way. There have been a large number of pins and whacks on this rock and no one has been crushed badly on it- although Knuckle Down Guthrie got his moniker by mauling his innocent hand between the rock and his boat once. Its pretty benign though and theres a chance that Dans choice of coffee had something to do with the incident. The beauty of this spot is that it is easy on the body and yields very consistent good results for practiced players here. It is a high point of the year for mystery artists and there are sublime gatherings which occur in the fall season. Its a classic Mecca that should be on every squirt boaters list of places to visit. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nCheck to see if there is a dam release at the US Army Corps:\r\nhttp://www.lrh-wc.usace.army.mil/wc/wwsched.html\r\n\r\nDirections to Twisted:\r\n\r\n1. Take the road to this bridge via the rail-to-trail tunnel:\r\n\r\nhttp://maps.google.com/maps?hl=en&ie=UTF8&ll=38.22371,-81.046132&spn=0.005951,0.009624&t=h&z=17\r\n\r\nYou cannot drive across this bridge. Park at roads end just as you exit the tunnel at the SOUTHEAST end of the bridge.\r\n2. Descend the hill and putin just downstream from the bridge.\r\n3. Paddle class II+ water down to Twisted Sister.\r\n4. To return, paddle across the river to the river right bank across from Twisted Sister.\r\n5. Hike up the hillside to the railroad track\r\n6. Hike upstream along the ACTIVE railroad track to your car','03192000','cfs','15','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (103,'Halls of Karma','New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Fayette','Thurmond','1200','1900','2700','38.0393','-81.0311','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03185400&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=hinw2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1&toggles=10,7,8,2,9,15,6&type=0','This classic arena was properly named by Jim Snyder after a Black Oak Arkansas song about being torn between God and the Devil. It was named around 1979- before squirt boating began- when river guides used to amuse themselves by swimming the whirlpools after being shown how by Tim Kanannen. It is one of the first arenas where squirt boaters sought out big DT. It is exceedingly fickle and yet serves up major downtime to true devotees. The best levels are when it is pretty low and stable- from 0 to -2. A major portion of the river is slamming off a huge rock at the way bottom left of Lower Keeney Rapid. The river is quite deep here, even at low levels, although the bottom has been touched a very few times by people who dive deeply into the hearts of big whirlpools. The charc involves breaking out from behind the rock bearing left. For the best DT you need to turn sharply underwater before you travel too far and tap back into the eddy for support. This requires engaging the slab very close to the rock- within about a foot of it- and winging down hard right away semi-vertically. Many people waste hours here by making the mistake of dropping too slowly and trying to link up with an obvious seam about 3 out which is derived from the pillow formed by the rock. You can link up with the seam but you rarely get any good downtime at all because you travel fast without spinning and lose any support from the eddy. Some people, like Jeff Schnelle, get huge DT here and do travel to get it- about 50-80 in 20-25 seconds. But it is all based off an initial deep drop and using support from the river left eddy. Sometimes you can get a good ride by traveling across the currents underwater and downstream a bit and tapping into the river right eddy. But this is very dynamic travel and usually peoples up buttons get greasy from all the action and they have premature evacuations. At any rate, this is a superb place to play for many hours and you have to pace yourself, bring drinks, snacks and rest periodically to get the best of the arena. \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nLook at this conversion page to get the current flow:\r\nhttp://www.wvwa.net/cgi-bin/nrg.pl\r\n\r\nThe Halls of Karma is located at the bottom of Lower Keeney Rapid on the New River Gorge.\r\n \r\nFrom the town of Winona high on the river-right plateau, drive down Keeney Creek on a winding dirt road. This road eventually turns to pavement. After you cross Keeney Creek for the fourth time, look for the eighth (8th) turnout on the right. It is about 0.85 miles from the fourth bridge (or about 0.25 miles from the end of the paved road). You can generally park about 4 to 6 cars at this turnout.\r\n \r\nDirectly across from the turnout is a guard rail. Look for the trail that drops into the woods below. Youll likely see a campsite in the clearing below, next to a large boulder. Follow the trail down past the fire ring and boulder to the railroad tracks.\r\n \r\nOnce at the railroad tracks, turn left and walk about 30 feet past a telephone pole. Youll find another well-worn trail leading down through the boulders to the New River. Lots of poison ivy here!\r\n \r\nThe putin is at the bottom of a large amphitheater of terraced rock slabs. The trail should take you right down to it. Paddle upstream 100 yards in a large pool. Halls of Karma is on attainers right.\r\n\r\nCamping in the New River Gorge is free up to 14 days. Regulations are 100 ft from water sources, cliff tops etc. There is one spot right at the park and play put in. Also several spots just upstream in the Keeneys Creek pool.\r\n\r\n9/3/14 updated the prediction url','03185400','cfs','12','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (104,'Thread the Needle','New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Fayette','Thurmond','2700','3500?','4300','38.0598','-81.0714','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03185400&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=hinw2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1&toggles=10,7,8,2,9,15,6&type=0','This is just upstream from Fayette Station about a quarter mile where two huge rocks sit in the middle of the river. The mystery eddy is on attainers right below the rocks and near shore. It is only about a two boat eddy with a vague looking eddy line. It is good at most levels but best at lower levels. You leave the eddy very high near a micro wave and use a flat slow drop to tap into a distant seam in the currents. You have to travel 5-8 feet to find the seam and by then your head should be disappearing. You can usually have your head gone for 2-3 seconds and this is an excellent arena for explosive black attacks or light loops. Its easy to get consistent results here at lower levels if you have any energy left \r\nBy Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nLook at this conversion page to get the current flow:\r\nhttp://www.wvwa.net/cgi-bin/nrg.pl','03185400','cfs','12','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (105,'Red Hole','Passage Creek','','US','US Eastern','VA','Front Royal','Bukton','5.6','','7.6','38.9410','-78.3064','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=03_00065&format=img_default&site_no=01635500&set_logscale_y=0','','Here’s some info on a great, little-known mystery spot on Passage Creek near Front Royal, VA. \r\n\r\nThe AWA Link will give you some more Info. (http://www.americanwhitewater.org/rivers/id/1981/)\r\n\r\nThe spot is called Red Hole, and it’s about 2/3s of the way down the run through Passage Creek Gorge. It is road side and can be easily located just above the nice rapid with a rock retaining wall against the road on the river left side. The actual spot is on the river left side, and it is a seam/eddyline that comes off of a small six inch ledge. The ledge is angled from left to right going downstream. The prime entry point is about two feet in from the end of the ledge/seam, and is best attacked with a regular charc going left, and shallow hip angle. If you hit it in the right place, the drop is effortless and instantaneous, and a steep forceful entry is not necessary. The hydrodynamics of the ledge is similar to Last Chance at the takeout of the Upper G, but going left instead of right and the ledge is angled downstream a bit more. Once you get the hang of Red Hole, you can roam easily even without an entry stroke. At the prime levels, even a novice mystery mover will sink out of sight with ease. Many times you will bounce smoothly along the sandy/gravel bottom for 8-10 seconds before emerging ten or fifteen yards downstream. In my experience, I have yet to find any spot that dishes out such high success with minimal effort. Below the spot is a thirty yard pool before the river runs into the next rapid, and the eddy on river left at the spot is plenty big. One major drawback is trout fishermen. In season, the stream is choked with fisherman and Red Hole is definitely a favorite fishing spot. It is also a favorite summer swimming hole for locals, but usually the creek is far too low in the summer months. \r\n\r\nAnything above one foot on the painted route 55 gage will work, with prime levels between 1.5 – 3 feet. As for directions, I believe they are posted in the AWA link above.\r\n\r\nBy, Joel D. Meadows\r\n\r\nDirections Below from--Chris Fewster\r\n\r\nRed Hole, Passage Creek, Strasburg, VA:\r\n\r\nLocated off Rt. 55 east of\r\nStrasburg just upstream of the state fish hatchery and downstream of\r\nElizabeth Furnace. Look for an angled ledge on river right with a deep\r\npool. There is some rock art and a sign that marks the spot. Extremely hard\r\nto catch with water.\r\n','01635500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (106,'Bubbler 1 & 2','Upper New','','US','US Eastern','VA','Blacksburg','Radford','2.2','3.0 -3.2','3.3','37.2515','-80.6120','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=05_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03171000&set_logscale_y=0','','Bubbler  One 2.2\r\n\r\nBubbler One & Two3.0 -3.2\r\n\r\nThe Bubbler Posted by Ricky Showalter \r\n\r\nThis realatively new mystery spot is really cool! Locals have been getting rides from 8 - 17 seconds pretty consistent and it is very gentle with lots of bubbles for the view. Drop similar to Last Chance on the Gauley, but smoother rides. \r\nCamping available in the Jefferson National Forest (Norris Run Road toward Pandapas Pond... primitive in the forest 10 min. & great Mountain Biking Area)you can reserve Boley Field from the Jefferson National Forest but you must register in advance and pick up the key, Claytor Lake State Park 30 min. off Interstate 81 near Dublin, White Rocks Campground pay spots in the National Forest near Ripplemeade off Route 460 turn on Route 635 near 460 bridge that crosses over the New River and go 17 miles up the mountain about 45 minutes from the mystery spot & plenty of hotels in Blacksburg where Virginia Tech is located. \r\n\r\nDIRECTIONS: \r\nFrom D.C., Richmond, & Charlotte or South: take I-81 to exit 118 in Christiansburg which is the Blacksburg VaTech exit. Take rt. 460 West towards Blacksburg for approximately 10 minutes to the 2nd Prices Fork Road exit. This is rt. 685 towards Prices Fork--away from Blacksburg \r\n\r\nFrom Beckley, Charleston (W.Va.), Ohio, Kentucky: take I-77 to the Princeton exit. Take rt. 460 East for approximately 45 minutes to the 1st Prices Fork Road exit, this is Prices Fork exit -away from Blacksburg. \r\n\r\nOnce on rt. 685 towards Prices Fork, turn right onto MCCoy Road(across from Snuffys Market) and follow to stop sign (several miles). Turn right at stop sign (Big Falls Road)and go about 2 miles on left. You will first see Big Falls Rapid which is the home of the old New River Rodeo, Down Under and The Squeeze is located in this rapid.. just down stream 1/4 mile will be a pull off on the left (just before you cross over the RR tracks the second time)this is the parking for the Bubbler.  Paddle to the other side of the river and on the top ledge you will find Bubbler 1 is river left of the rock pourover and Bubbler 2 is river right!  \r\n\r\nHave fun and dont forget to let the locals know you will be in town so they can join you by posting on the Angst board.\r\n\r\nPhone gauge is 540-639-3425 and push #7 to back the recording up in 30 min. intervals - the gauge is 6.5 hours of water travel to the Bubbler.','03171000','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (107,'Mellow Ledge','New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Fayetteville','Thurmond','4300','6000','9500','38.0568','-81.0698','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03185400&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=hinw2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1&toggles=10,7,8,2,9,15,6&type=0','INTRODUCTION\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge is a wonderful (and really under-appreciated) Mystery realm located about 1/2 mile upstream of the New River Gorge Bridge near Fayetteville, West Virginia. The rides at Mellow Ledge are deep, long, smooth and, of course, mellow!\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge has the distinction of being in range more days per year than any other Mystery realm in West Virginia. Mellow Ledge runs all winter but it is usually too cold squirt. In March-April the temperatures become tolerable and Mellow Ledge stays in range all the way until summer. This is the best time to catch Mellow Ledge.\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge is located between Millers Folly (Undercut) and Thread the Needle on the New River Gorge. The local squirting boating pro calls the spot Millers Folly instead of Mellow Ledge.\r\n\r\nI remember the first time I saw Mellow Ledge... Carl Gittings and I ran the New River gorge in squirt boats one freezing, rainy December afternoon. We mushed into the eddy line at Mellow Ledge on our way down river. The bubbles rising calmly to the surface gave me the impression that this was a very deep and special Mystery realm. We were too cold to stop and explore as our session at the Halls of Karma had put us on the verge of hypothermia. My butt was frozen and we had to get off the river. We would have to sample Mellow Ledge another day.\r\n\r\nDIRECTIONS\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge is on river left, directly across from the confluence of Fern Creek. To get there, park at the takeout below the bridge (WHAT BRIDGE?) and walk up the railroad tracks 1/2-mile on river left. Past the first gentle bend in the tracks, you will see a 10-foot boulder up ahead, left of the tracks. About 20 yards upstream of this boulder there is a telephone pole. Another 10 yards upstream of this pole you will find a steep trail that leads directly down to Mellow Ledge. Early in the season look through the bare trees for Fern Creek on the other side of the river.\r\n\r\nHYDRODYNAMICS\r\n\r\nThe eddy line at Mellow Ledge is formed by currents that spiral off the sloping edge of a very large, rectangular boulder that lays almost flat in the water. Regular lefty charcs are the norm at Mellow Ledge. (Back cuts have not been very fruitful here.) You will notice a large pillow on the upstream side of the boulder. Slice in at the interface between this pillow and the currents passing downstream.\r\n\r\nThe initial drop will take you spinning down the sloping face of the boulder. You may grind your stern on the way down if you are too close to the rock on the entry. When you drop off the edge of the boulder (2 to 3 spins) you will drop again and go deep (the double suck). \r\n\r\nIn the middle of your long and gentle ride, you may find yourself bumping into an underwater pillow that suddenly drives you to the surface. You can screw down behind this pillow (the triple suck) into a really long and deep ride. This pillow is formed a large sloping boulder (Kind Rock) but no one has ever hit it.\r\n\r\nGAUGE\r\n\r\nThe gauge for Mellow Ledge is the Thurmond USGS gauge:\r\nhttp://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/Gauge2/detail/id/43472/\r\n\r\nThe Hinton gauge is about 12 hours upstream and helps with predicting levels due to dam release.\r\n\r\nLOW WATER\r\n\r\nThe bare minimum flow for rides at Mellow Ledge is just under 4500 cfs. Hand paddles are best at low flow because you really have to screw down to catch the double-suck. Long, deep rides are still possible but not consistently obtained.\r\n\r\nIDEAL LEVELS\r\n\r\nThe ideal levels are between 5800 to 7400 cfs. The rides are fantastically deep and very easy on the body. How good is it? I can spend a whole day at Mellow Ledge at this level and not miss a single ride. What does that tell you? Some who have sampled this spot at ideal levels have argued that Mellow Ledge is better than Halls of Karma. Yeah, you read that correctly. Better than Halls of Karma.\r\n\r\nThe only problem with the ideal levels is that you will go so deep and so long that you will surface in the 2nd or 3rd eddy.\r\n\r\nA ride into the 2nd eddy is not a big deal, but you will have to attain back up into the 1st eddy. Attaining can be a real PITA for hand paddlers at these higher levels. Fortunately a sneak opens up through the boulders at about 7400 cfs, which allows you to pull or push yourself up and over some rocks back into the 1st eddy. I like to go through the sneak backwards so that I am pushing myself over the rocks, not pulling myself.\r\n\r\nA ride into the 3rd eddy, while fantastically long, necessitates getting out of your boat and carrying over the boulders back to Mellow Ledge. The first ride into the 3rd eddy: THAT WAS TOTALLY AWESOME! Second time: Oh, that was cool. Third time: I am NOT doing that again.\r\n\r\nHIGH WATER\r\n\r\nAt 9300 cfs the rock is underwater and Mellow Ledge is just a large, sticky hole. The eddy is almost gone. You can still get mysteries, but it is a ton of work battling the current. The charc is essentially the same as at lower levels. You will surface in the 3rd eddy.\r\n\r\nI heard rumors that the old-school Projet crowd likes Mellow Ledge in the 9300 to 9800 cfs range. That makes sense. Projets have the speed to stay in the fast-moving eddy and the hole is powerful enough to sink a large-volume boat like a Project.\r\n\r\nBETA FOR TRAVELERS\r\n\r\nOne old-timer reported that he will not travel 3 hours to Mellow Ledge unless the level is at least 3 feet (5800 cfs). That is not bad advice if you are heading in from out of town. Check the prediction URL above to see what Hinton is doing or going to do (12 hours upstream).\r\n\r\nPARKING\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge does not handle crowds very well. The eddy can handle 4 boats max. Finding a place to get out of your boat is always a problem. The river bank is a jumble of large boulders and you will be able to find only one docking station at any given level.\r\n\r\nAt low levels there is a sloping ledge where you can get out of your boat. This ledge is at the upstream corner of the rock that forms Mellow Ledge. It is immediately upstream of a big undercut that keeps the ferry interesting.\r\n\r\nAt high levels there is a protected harbor near the bottom of the first eddy. Even if you cannot find a place to dock, at least you can do a wet exit in shallow water.\r\n\r\nAESTHETICS\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge is in the sun until late in the day. However, the rocks on shore go into the shade quite a bit earlier. It is not the best place to be on a cold day. Dress warmly. Early in the season gloves and hoods are a good idea.\r\n\r\nALTERNATIVE PLAYGROUNDS\r\n\r\nOn your way down river back to the takeout, stop at Thread the Needle for a few dips. Its fun place.\r\n\r\nIf the water is too low for Mellow Ledge, then check out Thread the Needle (best at 2500 to 4500 cfs). If the water is even lower than that, then check out Halls of Karma (1200 to 2700 cfs). If the water is too high for Mellow Ledge, then see what is running on the the Gauley.\r\n\r\nMellow Ledge is a groovy place, baby.\r\n-Harry','03185400','cfs','13','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (108,'Danger Whirlpool','Appomattox','','US','US Eastern','VA','Petersburg','','','','','0','0','','','I noticed a Danger Whirlpool sign. I got to talking to a fisherman and he said that at higher flows a dangerous undercurrent from where the channel narrows and where an underwater ledge is located A BIG Whirlpool forms . All of this occurs under the aluminum bridge (highway 36). Has anyone squirted here? \r\n\r\nI got my first mystery at this spot. In short at high water (4 ft +), stay away!! This thing gets ugly fast. Since that time Ive spent many a day squirting from the Pipeline down to the whirlpool and had a blast in the deep currents. Best levels seem to be somewhere in the 8 to 3 range. Each level has a preferred spot to play, and it is well worth the effort to stop. \r\n\r\nThe Gages\r\n\r\nOld RC gage at matoaca bridge. about 3- on the USGs matoaca gage is around 0. On RC gage. Somewhere around 18.- On RC (4.5 on USGS) seemed to be the funnest level. Take a look below for a warning!!! \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDangerous whirlpool below the route 36 bridge near the takeout at Virginia State University. I recommend taking off the river before this hole that roams around a twenty by thirty foot area. Also, the eddy on right side has very fast upstream current. A tall dam with keeper hydraulics is 200 yards downriver. The entire Appomattox runs through this tiny granite notch. It is over forty-five feet deep underneath the bridge according to some SCUBA divers I ran into when the river was a lot lower!\r\n\r\nTake off the river just after Target rock rapid if you want to avoid this monster whirlpool. The whirlpool forms underneath the bridge at Virginia State University at higher water. If you can see the bridge think about getting off the river. You can scout this easily when you set up your shuttle before getting on the river. There is a dam 200 yards down river of this whirlpool which adds to the danger. Ive seen debris enter this hole and come back up about seventy-five feet down river. If you hear that the Appomattox is flooding its fun just to watch this hole. It is really awesome. Just dont fall off of the rocks!','','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (109,'Fish Bowl','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Great Falls','near wash dc, little falls pump station','2.7','3.1','3.3','38.9969','-77.2527','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=01646500&set_logscale_y=0','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1','FishBowl, also known as The Shoe: best at levels between 2.7 to 3.2 feet.\r\n\r\nThe FishBowl is formed by the convergence of the Horseshoe slab with the Streamers slab. Its a short hike up over the O-Deck peninsula to get to the bowl. We put in at a rocky cove and ferry across the Horseshoe current to an eddy below the Streamers on river right. When this spot is above 3.3 feet it is difficult to get back in the staging eddy on river right. The strong current usually forces you to eddy out in the eddy below the Flake/Spout. An accomplished squirter can easily wing down at this interface in either direction, a regular mystery charc will be to the right spinning with the current and backcut mystery charc will be to the left against the current. At any level in order to have success, you need to sink early, before you get to the current coming from the Horseshoe. Theres a little curler that forms at the seam, you need to have your boat already under when you get to the curler. The FishBowl isnt torquey except at the higher levels above 3.2. Its actually very safe compared to Bermuda or Simple Pleasures, or most spots on the Potomac for that matter. I know of no one whos touched bottom or encountered submerged rocks. This is one of the Potomacs premier spots for roaming under water. A roaming mystery is where you travel some distance underwater. The key to a roaming mystery move at Fishbowl is to sink early and wing down to the subsurface Horseshoe current. This charc will push you towards the middle of the river, so when you resurface, focus immediately on getting back in the eddy. This is my favorite mystery spot on the Potomac, because it doesnt usually boss me around (except at higher levels) and the scenery is spectacular, perfect for a Mystery Circle.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAt lower levels, the wave/hole above the seam becomes better for surfing so you must defend the staging area or surface kayakers will cut right over the seam to get back in line. If it gets too busy, just head on down to Bermuda, because thats where the best downtime will be. Downtime is slang squirters use for time spent in the mystery move. Harris Haynie, Dave Collins, and I would often do these aerobic mystery sessions. This is how it works: After dipping in the first time, attain up to the top of the seam instead of paddling back into the eddy, and dip over and over until you need to rest. Wed often dip 8 to 10 times, occasionally dipping simultaneously one at the upstream part of the seam while the other is on the downstream portion of the seam. We first began going up to The FishBowl while looking for new places to play below 3.3 feet after the Fishladder waves in Portage were no longer good for surfing after the twin floods of 1995. We first started calling this spot The Shoe as an abbreviation on Horseshoe, the spectacular last drop of Great Falls on the Maryland side. The FishBowl seems more appropriate, cause the overlooks on both sides of the river can get quite crowded with tourist eager to check out the kayakers playing the river. \r\n\r\nAccess to the Potomac spots in my guide to Mather Gorge is from Great Fall National Park in Virginia, Great Falls and C&O Canal National Historic Park in Maryland, or Anglers Inn in Maryland.\r\nAccess Points:\r\n\r\nMaryland: Rt 189 to Macarther Blvb\r\n\r\n- Sandy Beach. Park at Great Falls National Park (fee area), reached via MacAuthur Blvd. in Montgomery County, MD. Carry 1/4 mile south along the C & O Canal towpath, take trail on the right that leads to Sandy Beach putin.\r\n\r\n- Anglers Inn. Reach via MacAuthur Blvd. Park in one of three gravel or dirt lots across from the Anglers Inn, a fine restaurant. Carry across the canal, then 100 feet south on the towpath, then right down to the shore. From the river, the beach is easily seen on river left.\r\n\r\nVirginia:\r\n\r\n- Fishermans Eddy. Park at Great Falls National Park Virginia (fee area). From lower lot, carry across picnic area upstream toward steep trail that leads to Fishermans Eddy.\r\n\r\n- Rocky Island. From Great Falls, Virginia, walk south on trail from picnic area to a small footbridge and walk left down the rocky gully access Rocky Island surfing waves.\r\n\r\nBy, stro','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (110,'Bermuda Triangle','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','near wash dc, little falls pump station','2.6','2.9','3.05','38.9949','-77.2499','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00065&format=img_default&site_no=01646500&set_logscale_y=0','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1','Bermuda Triangle: best at 2.6 - 3.0 feet\r\n\r\nBermuda Triangle is formed by the convergence of the Fishladder slab with the Potomacs main slab. Look for a good-sized eddy in front of the rock that forms the point at the mouth of the Fishladder current on river left. Peel out of the staging eddy and head toward the upstream-most point of the convergence, theres a small curler at the optimum spot. As the river levels drop, the sweet spot moves downstream. Mysteries can be achieved either regular or back-cut, but the back-cut seems to work best. Often during the best mysteries youll travel underwater upstream a little when you use the back cut charc. On those really long mysteries, youll probably pop up just in time to make the eddy. At many levels, we often ferry across the river after re-entry to avoid being swept below the staging eddy and this also allows you to practice your mush moves. A little water pours out of the back of the eddy at higher levels. If you get flushed downstream, an amphibian over rock attainment is used to get back up to the staging eddy. The upstream fringes of Bermuda are toyed with at many higher levels, but beware and keep your up button ready to fire. I dont commit to a serious mystery charc until the levels are at or below 2.9. Extremely long and dangerous downtime can occur above 3.0 feet, there are many stories of scary downtime at and above this level. We havent permanently lost any boaters here, but remember it is Bermuda Triangle.\r\nWhitney named Bermuda, he called me after a session of mind bending DT to describe what he had tapped into, I can still hear the excitement and passion in his voice. Its called roaming now, we just cruised deep, always tryin to get the charc that sent you up stream for the easy return to the eddy.    mre.\r\nAccess can be gained equally from left or right side of the fishladder flow. As a matter of fact the right side of fishladder flow is the preferred at higher levels.\r\n\r\nAccess to the Potomac spots in my guide to Mather Gorge is from Great Fall National Park in Virginia, Great Falls and C&O Canal National Historic Park in Maryland, or Anglers Inn in Maryland.\r\nAccess Points:\r\n\r\nMaryland: Rt 189 to Macarther Blvb\r\n\r\n- Sandy Beach. Park at Great Falls National Park (fee area), reached via MacAuthur Blvd. in Montgomery County, MD. Carry 1/4 mile south along the C & O Canal towpath, take trail on the right that leads to Sandy Beach putin.\r\n\r\n- Anglers Inn. Reach via MacAuthur Blvd. Park in one of three gravel or dirt lots across from the Anglers Inn, a fine restaurant. Carry across the canal, then 100 feet south on the towpath, then right down to the shore. From the river, the beach is easily seen on river left.\r\n\r\nVirginia:\r\n\r\n- Fishermans Eddy. Park at Great Falls National Park Virginia (fee area). From lower lot, carry across picnic area upstream toward steep trail that leads to Fishermans Eddy.\r\n\r\n- Rocky Island. From Great Falls, Virginia, walk south on trail from picnic area to a small footbridge and walk left down the rocky gully to access Rocky Island surfing waves.\r\n\r\nBy, stro','01646500','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (111,'Moose Creek Flats','Gallatin','','US','US Mountain','MT','Big Sky','Gallatin River near Gallatin Gateway MT','700','850','1350','45.354749','-111.173399','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/mt/nwis/uv?06043500','','This spot is on the Gallatin River between Bozeman and Big Sky at the Moose Creek Flats Campground along Highway 191 (aka Gallatin Road).\r\nThe Campground is on the west side of the road. At the south end of the campground there is a little beach area just down river of an island. You want to hit the convergance from the surfers left side (nice beach side eddy).\r\nUber safe spot. Its a bit of a pooldrop with a gravel bottom. Maybe 7-8 feet deep at its deepest and slopes up to being only 2-3 feet deep at its far end.\r\nThe eddy gets blown out just above the max flow.\r\nUsually sinkable for a couple of weeks in late June, early July. As the river comes up earlier in the spring it blows through the min to max flows in a couple of days.','06043500','cfs','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (112,'Three Forks','Snoqualmie','','US','US Pacific','WA','Snoqualmie','Near Snoqualmie Falls','300','','','47.5203','-121.7745','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00060&format=img_default&site_no=12142000&set_logscale_y=1','','Park in the parking lot of Three Forks Park, off of Reinig St.  Then you hike south down a trail for 1/10mile to the river... there is a convergence where the North Fork and the Middle Fork come together...\r\n\r\nseems like the limiting factor is when the north fork is running... so thats why i have that gage hooked into this spot. but you need to look at the middle fork gage too, to be sure the convergence is good... look at journal entries (put both gage readings in them) for beta to dial in a promising level.\r\n\r\nmiddle fork gage:\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=12141300\r\n\r\nnorth fork gage:\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=12142000\r\n\r\nCamping:\r\nA. unexplored stealth site: South east of North bend, get onto 436th ave which will go under rt90...it will turn into Cedar Falls Road SE... this will eventually get to some Forest service roads(left onto FS 50) that go by some lakes... kinda confusing, you just need to look at at map, cause its hard to describe.\r\n\r\nB. unexplored stealth site: off of SE reing, turn LEFT onto 438th ave, away from north bend...this road will turn into North Fork Road SE, and then it will turn into NFD 2700 rd which might have a gate, but has 3 left hand turns off of it that may have camping.\r\n\r\nC.  ive crashed in my car off of rt18 in the parking lot of Tiger State Forest... but its not that sweet. Too close to the highway..gate closed to park in winter.','12142000','cfs','13','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (113,'Magic Bus','Payette','','US','US Mountain','ID','','','','','','43.9423','-116.1962','','','Going north on hwy 55 out of Horseshoe bend, it is just downstream of a left hand bend(drivers perspective)\r\nabout .25 mile before the Amish quilt and Glock store. (yes, Glock, not clock. welcome to Idaho...) There is a big turnout on the left side of the road with a 4wd acces road to the gravel bar beach. The Bus is a river left eddy with nice folding whirlpools. Catch the folding surge at the top of the eddy as the current pushes in perpendicular to the current line and spin left and down and down and down.... There is a big rock right where you start to drop, but it is clear and very deep after that.\r\n\r\nIt is about 2-3 miles downstream of Beehive Bend on the Main. ','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (115,'Simple Pleasures','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','2.6','2.9','3.1','38.9942','-77.2496','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1','Simple Pleasures: best at 2.6 - 3.1 feet\r\n*****\r\nSimple Pleasures is at the downstream corner on the Maryland side (river left) of S-Turn. This spot has a very quirky entry move, which must be performed approximately one boat width or so off the rock. The move most of the locals use is a backcut mystery charc. This charc involves paddling hard out of the eddy with your bow up. Once youve reach the spot next to and about boat width away from the rock, do a sudden forward weight throw to catch the bow under water. Then do fast rear pry on the right side, once your head is under, youll need to start spinning immediately or the currents will have their way with you. Extremely long, dark, and deep mysteries are possible here. Beware! This spot will draw you down quite deep very quickly. Ive experienced my longest and deepest mysteries here, many on the order of thirty seconds or more with depths over 10 feet deep. Ive heard of folks tapping rocks only occasionally. At the higher levels, water pours thru a slot next to the wall, this will affect your entrance charc. I prefer the lower levels of 2.7, when the slot is dry, because its an easier entrance charc and its also less turbulent once you get under.\r\n\r\nThis is another spot found in a Projet, I named it Simple Pleasures because the full potential was so difficult to achieve, yet so simple when you hit it. My preferred entry took more effort but gave consistent results - mush move not a true Mystery. As I recall there is a long seam leading into the sweet spot Stro describes, the key on the Mush is to enter the current high near the rock (that by now must have a name, named below I see) bow up high, as you enter the seam smash the bow down and about chest deep you should be near where a back cut charc would put you. After you drop a foot or so reverse the spin and enjoy the simple pleasures of life.\r\nOne of my favorite entrances to Simple Pleasures is without a boat. With a life jacket on leave the eddy, dip the up stream shoulder, catch the water on your back and sink. The wild thing here is that this will take you to the bottom - small boulder garden somewhat deep, plan on popping your ears on the way down - and keep you there, true roaming. The down draft is so strong that swimming with a life jacket you still have to push off to return to normal life.                                                                              mre.\r\n\r\nMost of the good mystery spots on the Potomac are on the river right, so most Potomac squirters are stronger at spinning underwater to the right. After a visit to the Ottawa Jimmicup, I vowed to practice my lefty moves. This venue is probably perfect for a regular lefty mystery charc, but our weakness probably led to the predominately used backcut charc.\r\n\r\n``For plastic boaters and intrepid (or unaware squirt boaters as has happened to yours truly as you can attest) watch out for this spot at 5 - 6 feet as the whirlpool will suck you way down and rattle your nerves and possibly try to drown you. I was sucked down, flipped over, rolled up and was still on my way down deep. Surfaced at the wall under your boat (whack).                  Greg Steiger\r\n\r\nI remember that day, Greg was seriously spooked. Ive had a few sessions that ended quickly after too much success with depth and time spent deep. Ive also had many a session where I was skunked and could barely get my head under. This spot is perfectly suited to perform some roaming and mystery circles.\r\n\r\nHow about the pourover at the top of the S-Turn above Simple Pleasures you ferry over to attain the S-Turn. At the right level its great vertical blow blastin and as you are smiling downstream allow your boat to work over to your right (VA) and then you and your boat will get sucked down, flatten out and come up down stream. It is really the way to get out of the blast. I think there is a name for this rock forming the pourover (Molly Hatchet).                                                                  Greg Steiger','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (116,'Rocky Island','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.0','4.2','5.0','38.99233376096277','-77.24847793579101','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Rocky Island - best at 3.8 - 5.? Feet\r\n\r\nRocky Island offers awesome downtime possibilities on the eddyline or wave train. The eddyline charc can be difficult while crowded with surfers waiting in the eddy. A little polite explanation and a shout of eddyline usually works. Regular or back cuts work here and its very suitable for roaming, but the entry can be fickle. Watch out upon re-entry, as others may be oblivious to your departure. Its a difficult staging area to defend. I remember one day at Rocky, Whitney was there in his new T-Bird working on his mysteries and I asked him why he wasnt surfin much. Realizing it now, he was under the spell of the mystery trance, but he mumbled something about squirtin up on the Ottawa River recently and that Rocky Wave couldnt compare. Plus getting downtime was too much fun. \r\n\r\nLittle Sweet Cheeks aka Rickys Cheeks best at 3.0 - 3.8 Feet\r\n\r\nThis spot is very similar to Sweet Cheeks on the Gauley. Its at the seam next to the first wave at Rocky Island Rapid. Enter the seam on a steep right-breaking charc next to the submerged rock. Wing down quickly and wait for the double suck. The spot to look for at lower levels is just behind the first wave, where the double suck happens at higher levels. Respectable and safe downtime can be expected. Ricky Rodriguez showed me this spot, he hated the name [Rickys Cheeks], but he hasnt come up with another one [other than Little Sweet Cheeks] so its stuck so far.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (117,'Top Secret','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.6','4.0','4.0','38.9904','-77.2476','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Top Secret - best at 3.6 - 4.0 feet\r\n\r\nTop Secret is located just downstream from Rocky Island. Its a pourover hole in the middle of the river. Id tell you more, but protocol called for me to only show folks this spot, you cant tell them exactly where it is. The move is a regular charc breaking right. Surf across the wave/hole and align with the current, you should wave move to wing down quickly and roam maybe 10 feet before exiting. Theres a pourover downstream that looms, however everybody Ive seen pop up before reaching the rock. Suitable for a mystery circle, Ricky Rodriguez showed me this spot in the height of the Potomac squirt craze. He was quite secretive about the location of its pleasures hence the name, not to mention the joking attempt to hide this spot from the CIA squirters. \r\n','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (118,'Terrapin Station','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','6.0','6.5?','8','38.9947','-77.2469','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Terrapin Station - best at 7.2 feet\r\n\r\nThis spot is located across and slightly downstream river right from the Sandy Beach put-in below Great Falls, MD. Use a regular charc breaking right to achieve truly powerful mysteries. Whitney named this one shortly after seeing a particularly good Dead show. This spot is suitable for slalom and rodeo boat mysteries. When Terrapin is going off, Tims Wave (old school Daves Wave? Most excellent wave moves! Stro, Im confused here, as I see it Daves wave is across from sandy beach, Terrapin Station is down stream and then Tims wave would be the fist wave encountered when attaining the channel) down in the Maryland channel should be good for surfing as well as a myriad of spots downstream like Dead Cow, Corner Hole, and Skull Island. \r\n\r\nI suspect we rode Terripin at higher levels, things were pumpin. The power was intense, the favorite move was a cross bow draw that would set the boat at about 60 degrees, this would help the river form a whorl pool and instantly suck you down, deep for a long roam into a black attack. Whitney called it a Torque Screw. Terripin was the only place you could get a Projet to perform like that, wild, deep and fast                                                                                         mre\r\n\r\nI saw Whitney, god bless his soul, disappear into the grasp of this eddy line and wrote him off for gone. We watched and watched and no Whitney. Still no Whitney, still no Whitney. Fuck, where is he, we wondered a bit spooked. Suddenly he burst to the surface in a radical exit charc, face beet-red, eyes wide shut, and speaking in tongues. The water was real brown and muddy and cold. Usually when this spot is up the river is brown and cold and strong so if you fully commit to the mystery when the level is prime, not a half-assed attempt but a full-pledged committed attempt with a perfect knee to hip transition when the surge is right, you are a really brave submarine captain. Get ready Captain Nemo. Good place for O2 tanks or a good set of lungs. Plan on being able to hold your breath for a while in cold water, dont pass out.                                                                                   Greg Steiger','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (119,'Smoothie','Ottawa','','CA','','ON','Beachburg','OWL','-5','0-3','?','45.7509','-76.7832','http://www.owl-mkc.ca/owl_gauge.htm','','At the top of McKoy’s (above Sattler’s Hole against the river left shore) lies what is perhaps the friendliest and most accessible DT spot on the entire river at levels between 2 and –2 on the OWL gauge. Deep and unobstructed, it is a clean and fairly innocuous-looking eddyline that bulges out from the shore into the current, which is accelerating downstream into the heart of the rapid.  The bottom of the eddy is defined by a large shelf of rock which captures water flowing downstream and feeds it back up to the top, creating a consistent and very supportive eddy/current structure which can yield smooth, controllable and very deep rides of over 20 seconds to serious and skilled riders. Aptly named “Smoothie” by Carl Gittings in August of 1999, the spot has been frequented by local squirt boaters for years and has just recently begun to attract the attention of squirtists from further abroad.\r\n\r\nThere are several ways to access the lower realms of Smoothie, but by far the best rides occur when the rider goes in “standard” – with the whirlpool energies.  The most popular entry seems to be to cross the eddyline just above the squeeze at about a 45 degree angle to the currents, and initiate your bow with a high-angle smash that snares the bow deep into the downstream currents close to the eddyline. Good timing is required, for as the boat spins with the momentum of the move and drifts down into the squeeze, you must simultaneously slam the stern down in and level the boat out, placing you about neck-deep and in perfect position to continue winging down, spinning along the seam and accessing ever-deepening realms.  This move is effective and flashy, and is an excellent way to get deep fast, avoiding the turbulence caused by the shallow water at the very top of the eddy.\r\n\r\nAnother common method is to approach the squeeze with your bow buried about a foot deep or so.  As you approach, you will notice a tiny curling wave that forms and disappears just above and to the eddy side of the squeeze – the trick is to penetrate the currents just above this little wave and wing down hard with a decisive impact from your right hip (crossdraws work well here).  Be sure and get back into the eddy immediately, as the downstream currents will want to pull you out into the main flow.  Once you spin back in, it’s easy to continue winging down using the support of the eddy – the experience is sublime, like floating down through thick layers of molasses.  There’s little sense of motion, even though your eyes are registering that the boat is spinning, the sensation of doing so is almost completely absent.\r\n\r\nThis spot can also be accessed using a backcut entry – the drop is fast, and the downtime can be just as big as going regular.  There are those who have managed to make it work very well, with consistent huge rides in the 20-second-or-longer range. Approach the squeeze running very close to the eddyline, and watch for that same little curling wave.  The aim is to cut back perpendicular to the seam, effecting a big left-hip impact as you pass under that wave.  The drop is immediate if you’ve positioned yourself properly…the trick now is to maintain your spin going against the whirlpool energies, not always an easy task.\r\n\r\nmore info:\r\nhttp://ottawajimicup.sinkspots.org/','','ft','14','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (120,'Rincon','Arkansas','','US','US Mountain','CO','Salida','PARKDALE','500','650','3500','38.472891','-105.867235','http://www.dwr.state.co.us/surfacewater/data/detail_graph.aspx?ID=ARKWELCO','','Pretty easy to get to, really - drive from Salida towards Canyon City.  About ten miles outside of Salida you\\ll see the Rincon parking area off to your left.  Park there, the seam is just upstream.  If you want to save a couple of bucks on parking, turn left at the Wellsville bridge, then downriver (right) as soon as you can.','07094500','cfs','17','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (121,'Holtwood-Wunderland','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Holtwood','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','8','9','9.5 ?','39.818903','-76.333437','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','Wunderland is a pourover which forms its own eddy just upstream of Playspot II, near the Right shore of the main channel at Holtwood. (see Susquehanna Surf Guide: http://www.chasingrain.com/surfguide/index.html)\r\n\r\nThere are multiple put-in and take-out locations available, but if you just want to get to Wunderland, the best put-in is on McCalls Ferry Road(River Rd on some maps), at the second creek which you cross over as you drive north from PA 372.  Hike down the creek bed to the river and ferry out to the pourovers.\r\n\r\nThe best spot is the river-left most eddyline.  Regular cut to the right or back-cut works, but you have to miss the ledge, to drop into the deep pool(very fast, but very smooth).  Once down, duration is up to you, and how well you can maintain your spin and balance.\r\n\r\nThe pourovers are also great for vertical blasting.\r\n\r\nThe eddy is not close to shore, and can be a little pushy, so you dont get too much rest between drops.  When youre pooped, go downstream to Playspot II and then takeout at the next access point along the road.  You can do multiple laps if you need to. \r\n\r\nThe levels are only suggestions, since the flow is dependent on how water is being distributed from the dam, which changes sporadically.\r\n\r\nby Dan Mayer','01570500','ft','15','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (122,'Mystery Machine','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Harrisburg','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','5.3','6','7','40.356462','-76.932975','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','Mystery Machine is 5 minutes from Downtown Harrisburg on a stretch of the Susquehanna known as the Dauphin Narrows.  There is a 25 ft replica of the statue of liberty atop a crumbling stone bridge pier in the middle of the river (visible from 322).  Apparently, Paul Schreiner helped in the construction of the original statue, which was replaced after a flood or something.\r\n\r\nYou can see the spot from route 11/15 which is on River Right (West Shore).  Head north out of Marysville and pull off just before the road narrows and the stone guard wall begins.  Look about 50 yards off the shore for a tell-tale pourover curling off a sloped rock with a huge eddy behind it.  Unfortunately, you cant put in there because youre separated from the river by a 100 ft near-vertical embankment, and a 6-lane rail-bed, which gets a lot of traffic.\r\n\r\nThe best access is from downstream in Marysville.  Find the tunnel which goes under the railroad tracks to the river.  Turn left as you exit the tunnel, and drive to the end of the road.  There is a small pull-off to the right where you can park.  \r\nYou can paddle up from here but its much easier to hike (about a quarter mile) along the tracks.  Bring sturdy shoes or booties for the hike.  The shore is a poison ivy plantation, so wear pants and long sleeves.  Put in high, above almost all of the rapids, and drift down to the spot.\r\n\r\nThe seam is a pourover on River Left side of the rock.  It tends to take you straight down very quickly to a depth where things mellow out and you can begin spinning.  Its pretty shallow, and youre likely to tap some rocks - nothing hazardous though. The eddy is big enough for multiple boats, but its 50 yds from shore, so taking a break can be a challenge.\r\n\r\nThe spot is formed by a pourover slipping a layer of water under a large, overhanging slab of eddy current.  You can feel the eddy slab as you slam into it, or slip under it.  When you slam into it, you typically will start surfacing in a bubbly layer.  If you get under it, youll be in darker greenwater and two things can happen.  You travel under and pop up on the other side of the eddy, in the main slab.  Or you stall under the eddy slab and get pasted to the bottom.  You will come up, but its very slow, and it feels like youre under tremendous weight.\r\n\r\nThe ease of entry and variety of rides you can get here make this spot really fun.\r\n\r\nBy Dan Mayer','01570500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (210,'Toilet Bowl?','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Dauphin','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','3.9','4.0','4.6','40.359775','-76.925528','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','Im adding this spot based on hearsay.\r\nSeveral locals have mentioned sinking here back-in-the-day, but I havent sampled it yet.  \r\n\r\nIts located at the last - or one of the last- features in the narrows on extreme river left.  Im told its a pourover feature that gives up short rides and is more mellow than Mystery Machine.  Im also told that it only works at 4.0 ft.  Ill definitely find it this summer and report more. - Dan Mayer','01570500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (125,'Chicken Shack','Little River Canyon','','US','Dirty South','AL','Fort Pyne','Little River nr Blue Pond, AL [ AL ]','1300','1800','?','0','0','http://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River_detail_id_69_','','Seam is at the bottom of the Falls on the Little River. Dalton says its great at 9 to 12 inches.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (126,'Hawaii sur Rhone','Rhone','','FR','','Rhône-Alpes','Lyons','','','Low summer levels ','','45.795432','4.878058','http://www.rdbrmc.com/hydroreel2/station.php?codestation=43','','Squirt spot above the wave in Lyon aka Hawaii sur Rhone. The seam works at low/medium levels, in highwater will wash out. If your feeling brave surf the wave, the eddy line below the wave is full of rubish and is no good for squirting.','','cfs','14','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (130,'Flower Pots','Exe','','GB','','DEVON','Exeter','eathorvertonwebcam','0 ','3 and 3 quarters on the EA gauge ','4 on the EA Gauge ','50.7224','-3.5399','http://eathorvertonwebcam.org.uk/index2.html','','Flowerpots seam provides a great learning curve for squirtboaters of all skills. The seam will start running during the low summer water levels and couldnt be better situated than slap bang in the middle of Exeter, right next to The Mill On The Exe Pub. Park nsink dosent get much better than this!\r\n\r\nThe seam can be found half way down Flowerpots weir in a big pool of flat water, the weir forms two jets of water that meet to form the seam, in high water the jets no longer meet and the weir becomes ugly, apart from a kicking playhole/wave and in very extreme flood conditions you get a monster river wide wave. Hawii-sur-rhone eat your heart out!\r\n\r\nDirections\r\n\r\nYou can park on the road next to the river or use the pub car park (next to the weir).\r\nPlease note we have a good understanding with the pub, they have asked us not to use it during their busy periods i.e lunch and dinner times and to change discretely. Thank you.','4 on the ea Gauge','ft','15','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (131,'Singing Eddy','Back river (tidal)','','US','US Eastern','ME','Georgetown','n/a (tidal)','n/a (tidal)','n/a (tidal)','n/a (tidal)','43.8515','-69.7721','http://www.maineboats.com/tide-charts/southcoast','','***Summer 09 Update: Singing Eddy is offline for the forseeable future due to bridge reconstruction. Ask Ryan Linehan on the Angst Board for status updates. Construction should be done toward the end of the summer.***\r\n\r\nDESCRIPTION (from http://www.singingeddy.blogspot.com/):\r\nHere is a shot of singing eddy from the bridge at about the sweet side of the tide. You can see the convergence as the water falls over the submerged ledge off the tip of the island. The squeeze is about 25 ft deep at low tide. This is an incoming tide sink spot. Hit it 3 hours before Portland high tide. Its importnt to go by the Portland tides, not local tides for Singing Eddy area. Check tides here: http://www.maineboats.com/tide-charts/southcoast. Definitely check the charts before driving up to make sure the its running at a reasonable time of day.\r\n\r\nDIRECTIONS:\r\nTake Route 1 north through Bath and over the Kennebec river bridge. Immediately after reaching the East shore, take a right onto 127, just before the Dairy Queen, following signs to Georgetown and Arrowsic Islands. Soon after that right, youll go over another bridge. Youll be on Arrowsic Island. Keep following 127 for 5 or so (maybe a few more) miles until you come to another bridge. This is the bridge connecting Arrowsic Island to Georgetown Island. The Singing Eddy is right below you coming off the tip of the island. Park either before or after the bridge and pick your way down to shore. The seam is obvious and Ryan always seems to backcut it with great success.\r\n\r\nmap of the area:\r\nhttp://www.bobfenton.com/georgetown.maine.area.htm\r\n\r\npay camping on georgetown island:\r\nhttp://www.sagbaycamping.com/location.html','n/a(tidal)','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (143,'Borobus','Ketagawa','','JP','','Shizuoka Prefecture','Hamamatsu City','','','','','34.94827','137.865176','http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ja&u=http://sakurazaka.cocolog-nifty.com/squirt/2006/03/post_afa9.html&sa=X&oi=translate&resnum=2&ct=result&prev=/search%3Fq%3Dsquirtist%26hl%3Den%26lr%3D%26client%3Dfirefox-a%26rls%3Dorg.mozilla:en-US:official%26hs%3DZbl','','Its in south central Honshu- a couple hours below Nagoya.\r\n\r\nThis site is in japanese:\r\nhttp://blog.drecom.jp/squirtogether/ \r\n\r\nstros pictures:\r\nhttp://www.putfile.com/pic.php?img=3424513','','cfs','12','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (144,'88s  (88 Dodgers)','French Broad','','US','Dirty South','NC','Asheville','French Broad River at Asheville, NC','1200','2000','4000','35.6821','-82.6160','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03451500','','I-26 North of Asheville (US Highways 19, 23, 25, 70) Take the Newbridge Exit and head south towards Asheville on Merrimon Ave. At the top of the Hill turn right on Old Marshal Highway and follow until eventually merging with NC Highway 251. Eventually the river will appear on the left and after an additional mile you will see a turnout on the left. Pull in here or continue on for another 1/4 mile to the parking area and river park. 88s is a lefty cartwheel ledge just downstream of the pullout in the middle of the river. It is not very deep but it is a flat rock bottom so you just sit into the pourover and it will drop you down and you can skim across the bottom about 3-4feet under for about 5-8 seconds.','03451500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (150,'Wicked Wanda','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','5.99','6.05','6.09','38.9818','-77.2411','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Wicked Wanda: best at 6.?\r\n\r\nWanda is about two eddies down from the big bend of the river in Mather Gorge on the Maryland side (river left). Use a left breaking charc and watch out for the double suck.\r\n\r\n``There is nothing like a big wet kiss on the lips by Wicked Wanda. Whitney showed me Wicked Wanda and we loved this spot. It forms when Daves Wave is cookin and is formed by water coming over a rock ledge on river left I think two eddies down from the left turn of the river below the Mather Gorge at the Jumps. It will give you a true double suck, taking you down once like at madder and madder, then as you begin to rise to the surface if you keep spinning it will suck you down again. Never seemed lethal or scary like Terrapin, looked that way to more timid onlookers but Wanda does not want to hurt those that give her a kiss on the lips.                                                                              Greg Steiger','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (146,'Devils Dip','Tuckasegee','','US','Dirty South','NC','Bryson City','Tuckasegee River at Bryson City, NC','800','1600','5000','35.4306','-83.4428','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03513000','','I-40 between Asheville and Knoxville, take exit to follow US Highway 74 West. About 45 minutes later you will take exit 67, Bryson City. Go down the hill about 1/2 mile and take a right at the light (Main Street). After a quarter mile take a left at the light (Everett Street). After another quarter mile take a right at the light (Bryson Street) and follow until you dead end at a pedestrian bridge. Park on the left and cross the bridge to the island. The lower spot is at the point of the island, the upper about half way up.','03513000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (182,'Swirlies','North Santiam','','US','US Pacific','OR','Mehama','','','','','44.7521','-122.3811','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14183000&set_logscale_y=1','','These are just dyanamic whirlpools that pulse down the eddy line. Kinda fun but not a great mystery spot for controled and quality mysteryies. Fun to get verical in the whirlpools and let it push you around..\r\n\r\nPut in at Packsaddle Park..you can take out at the first bridge, so thats about a 2mile section. swirlies is about at 1.5miles into it.  If you want to do a longer section, continue downstream 1 mile to Spencers Hole. You can take out there too..or go another 2miles further down to the Mill City park. This is a fun downriver squirt run, class II-III, 6miles total if you do the whole run.\r\n\r\nSwirlies pretty much alot like the browns hole spot on the mckenzie.\r\n\r\nIm hoping both of these spots will be better at lower summer flows..','14183000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (147,'Dunkin Stronuts','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.0','','3.6','38.9950','-77.2513','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Dunkin Stronuts aka Running Errands best at 2.8 to 3.6\r\n\r\nThis great little eddyline is above Portage/Fishladder on the river right. Its at the top to the small islands just little below the wall at O-Deck. I was playing at this unnamed spot with Gree Herring, Amy Gibson, and Dave Collins one day May 2000, I commented that it didnt have a name and Gree pipes in How about Dunkin Stronuts.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (148,'Fishermans Eddy','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.4','','3.9','38.9956','-77.2527','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Fishermans Eddy         fickle at all levels best at 3.4 to 3.9\r\n**\r\nThis is the eddy directly below the Observation Deck 2 & 3 on river right. This is great warm-up eddyline at any level. Downtime can be achieved by tapping into a wave move charc in the wave train or by screwing down at the wall. Beware of squirting too close to the wall, its not a good spot to be vertical as its not very deep. The wall mystery charc is safest at 3.4 to 3.9 feet. The next eddy down was the scene of the Whitney Shields pinning mentioned by Eric Lindberg in a Jim Synder interview for the book ``Squirt Boating and Beyond.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (149,'Madder and Madder','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.6','4.0','4.3','38.99263395622427','-77.24871665239334','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Madder and Madder - 3.6 - 4.3 feet (<12000 cfs) best at 4.0\r\n\r\nIts off the Virginia Shore (river right) just 50 yards above Rocky Island Waves. Begin with a regular charc to the right and a shallow entry directly next to the rock. Only do three turns underwater at the most and dont work on the vertical plane or chances are youll meet a shallow rock that waits ten feet downstream. I was checking this spot recently at O-Deck level 3.67 and was successful, and I wasnt whacking any rocks in my shorter Asylum while working vertically at normal levels. Eric Lindburg and Whitney Shields first showed me this spot. Eric would say, I better get going cause Barb is gonna get madder & madder the longer I stay here.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (151,'Center Chute','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','5.3','6','6.7','38.9777','-77.2358','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Center Chute at Difficult Run - best at 5.0 - 6.7 feet\r\n\r\nUsing the top wave, initiate a wave move charc toward the Maryland shore. At higher levels, (6.5 - 6.7), the main hole can give good downtime using a normal mystery charc. Be aware of the rock that forms the Center Chute hole, use a shallow entry charc!\r\nI remember that you need big cahunas to get in that hole below 5.2 or so cause it is sticky and shallow. You can actually also charc to the right. To look really in control, surf the sweet little wave next to the island (does it have a name) while everyone is so concerned and lined up for the big wave. Good place to warm up, then do a wave move to the left, mystery, exit on a screw-up, surf over to the center wave, do a few spins into a few back blasts when the wave breaks, then spin around into a wave move and mystery, again exit on a screw up and do a few cartwheels to show you been watching Snyder videos. \r\n\r\nDIRECTIONS:\r\nYou park on the Maryland side instead of the Virginia side. From the Beltway (interstate 495), while youre still in Maryland, immediately before the bridge over the Potomac take the Clara Barton Parkway exit. Theres only one exit and it only goes in one direction (itll say Carderock). (Dont take the Cabin John Parkway exit which is about a mile before the Clara Barton). Follow the parkway to where it ends at MacArthur Blvd. Take a left on MacArthur. Youll go through one intersection with a stop sign and then about 1/4 - 1/2 mile later youll see LOTS of cars parked along the road and some dirt parking lots full of cars on the left. Those are the lots for where you want to park for the put in. Theres a restaurant called Old Anglers Inn directly across the street from the parking for the put in. Once youre there its easy to find the put in. Then you just paddle upstream to get to Center Chute. There will be lots of boats headed to and from Center Chute so itll be hard to miss!','01646500','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (152,'Maryland Chute','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.1','3','','38.9787','-77.2357','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Maryland Chute at Difficult Run - best at 3.1 - 3.9 feet\r\n\r\nMaryland Chute is a wave/hole at these levels and mysteries are achieved using the regular mystery charc towards the Maryland shore (surfer right). At 3.2 feet and below, only do three turns underwater at most and dont work on the vertical plane unless you do it immediately or you might whack a shallow rock that waits ten feet downstream.\r\n\r\nDon Qs   \r\n*\r\nThis spot is located in the Maryland Chute downstream from where the traditional hole forms. The rock that used to stretch and dump water at lower levels is now a pourover. Use a right breaking charc for a quick mystery move. Don Qs is a real tough attainment.\r\nI was thinking about your list of mystery spots and alas I think we forgot Don Qs at the MD Channel that you found when the river is up. I cant remember exactly what the level was but it must be around Center Chute level.                                                          Greg Steiger','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (153,'Pecker Point','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','4.5','5','5.0','38.9785','-77.2343','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Pecker Point     best at 4.5 to 5.0\r\n\r\nThe eddyline on the way up to the Chutes at Difficult Run before you attempt the ferry to the big eddy behind the island. It is a cool little eddyline w/ swirlpools. Backcut and regular mystery charc work at this spot.\r\n\r\n\r\n','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (154,'Shakedown Street','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','5.7','','6.9','38.9789','-77.2367','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Shakedown Street -best at 5.7 to 6.9\r\n\r\nSomewhere above the Difficult Run Chutes, this spot comes into play when the Center Chute Hole at Difficult Run is prime, and gets even better as it rises to Scull Island Waves & Dead Cow Hole. Its just downstream from the waterfall that drains from the C&O Canal. I recall Whitney Shields and Cory Marshall raving about the mush moves theyd just done while we were playing below.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (155,'Amys Secret','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Little Falls','3.3','','3.56','38.9784','-77.2366','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv?01646500','','Amys Secret - best at 3.3 to 3.6 feet\r\n\r\nAmys Secret is just upstream of the Difficult Run Chutes on the Maryland side. Its on the attainers right side of the rock about 30 feet off the MD shore. Use a regular charc breaking right, but the backcut move will also work. Squirt Chicks dig this spot, its perfectly suited for controlled head deep mysteries. I also highly recommend this spot for working on light loops and other tricks. This spot is named for Amy Lueders, who is Greg Steigers wife and squirt boater supreme.\r\nI thought I was Amys secret, but hey this eddy line is a good spot in the summer when the river is low and you want to practice your treadin. Leave your paddle on a rock and go for it.                                                 Greg Steiger','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (156,'Four-Pines','Exe','','GB','','DEVON','Exeter','eathorvertonwebcam','4  and a half on the gauge ','5 on the gauge','5 and a quarter on the gauge ','50.756034','-3.529744','http://eathorvertonwebcam.org.uk/index2.html','','Four-Pines (50.755654, -3.535495) is a weir upstream of Flowerpots on the outskirts of Exeter. The main seam is on river right where a jet of water from a sluice meets the main flow from the weir face.\r\n\r\nThis seam when tapped into will give you long dark mysterys, which will keep you coming back for more, time and time again.\r\n\r\nThe only other downtime spot of note is a horizontal seam to the main weir face just to the left of the main seam. This seam will take you down to neck height and then locks you in.\r\nYou can then impress your mates as all they can see is your head spinning endlessly around in circles as you roam this spot in till you get bored or your boat fills up with water and sinks!\r\n\r\nDirections\r\n\r\nTravel from Exeter to Tiverton on A396, you will see the river on your left, just after you see the weir look for a turning into a farmers feild. Park next to the river just before railway bridge, have marked this point on the map. Get changed here, put on the river and paddle short distance down to the weir (50.755654, -3.535495), when finished hike back up to your car.','','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (157,'Breatherlizer','Dart','','GB','','DEVON','Dartmoor National Park','Dartcom weather station','10mm of rain in a 24hrs period','20+mm of rain in a 24hrs period','The more rain the better!','50.532924','-3.808941','http://www.dartcom.co.uk/index.php?pageID=6','','The river Dart is a paddlers paradise from grade 1 to 5+, situated in the beautiful Dartmoor national park this river can make your dreams come true, squirtboating is no exception.\r\n\r\nFor the avid squirtboater the Dart has so much to offer, from running chunky rapids to droping into the endless depth of the green room. This is one of those truly amazing places that send a shiver down your spine just thinking of it.\r\n\r\nThe Breatherlizer seam, will leave you breathless, one set of lungs just isnt sufficient. This seem is very deep, long, smooth and powerfull, you will run out of air long before the seam is bored of you. Get ready to polish off those greasy up buttons, your going to need it!\r\nYou can find Breatherlizer on the middle section of the Dart where the Webburn joins the Dart the two flow converge and create the seam. You can park nsink or run the meat to get to this spot, the choice is yours.\r\n\r\nThere is no gauge as such for the Dart, there is a metal pole just upstream of the seem I use as a gauge.\r\n\r\nZero water on the pole, seam is likely to be rubbish\r\nQuarter of the pole covered, seam is OK\r\nHalf covered, seam is GOOD\r\nThree quarters covered, seam is EXCELLENT\r\nTotaly covered, hold on to your hats, your going down!\r\n\r\nTo get an idea of waterlevels before you get there we use local weather charts to gauge how much rain has fallen. 20+mm of rain in a 24hrs period should get the rivers going nicely, the more the better. We also use the local kayak shop ASwatersports for up todate info.\r\n\r\nhttp://aswatersports.co.uk/ \r\nhttp://www.dartcom.co.uk/index.php?pageID=6\r\nhttp://www.metcheck.com/V40/UK/FREE/today.asp?zipcode=devon\r\n\r\nDirections\r\nDrive along the A38 and turn off at Ashburton and follow sign to Newbridge. Newbridge carpark (50.523390, -3.819601) is the get on for the middle dart and the get out is Holne bridge (50.521030, -3.792570). If you want to park nsink carry down small road on river left to here (50.532722, -3.809739).','','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (158,'Bideford Tidal Spot','Bideford Estuary','','GB','','DEVON','Bideford','Local surf reports','','2 - 3hrs before and after high tide','','51.016436','-4.203193','http://www.surfstation.co.uk/acatalog/Surf_Report.html','','North Devon main attraction is it surf beaches, if however you find your luck is out and the waves have deserted you then fear not, Bideford might have an answer to your squirtboating needs.\r\n\r\nIn the middle of Bideford is an old arched bridge that spans the water, you cant miss it.\r\nSupposedly all the arches provide good seams when the tide is flowing. Best time to be there 2-3hrs before and after high tide??? I have yet to test this sight but if true could prove amusing if all else fails. However if the surf is going off my sdvice would be to go big in the waves. \r\n\r\nDirection\r\nDrive to Bideford, park nsink.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (159,'Holme Pierrepont National Water Sports Centre','Trent','','GB','','Nottingham','Colwick','HP','','','','52.945250','-1.091766','','','HP is a man made white water slalom course, you can find many of GB top athletes training here from time to time. \r\n\r\nThe course has everything a budding squirtboater could want for, waves, holes, seams and big flat pools to try out your flat water moves or watch the world go bye. There are four main squirt spots where you will find the glitter gathering in the eddys like so much drift wood.\r\n\r\nTop Wave is the first feature on the course and is a walled in wave/stopper, loved by the playboating whipper snappers. If you can fight you way onto it you can practise your paddle twirls and shudder rudders intill the cows come home! When you get board of that load the front of your boat and visit the green room as you sub out the back of the wave to cheers from the crowds.\r\n\r\nCarry on down stream to the pyramid block, tuck into the eddy behind the pyramid block then paddle full tilt into the pourover created by the block and hold on. The locals have a number of different charcs for this spot see if you can work them out.\r\n\r\nThe looping pool is just below a wooden bridge and is a beast of a drop, they change this drop quite a lot from a hole to a wave and so on. When its working at it best hold on for massive down time, this is a very powerful spot and quite intimidating to look at, expect a few unintentional loops whilst under! A good use of the up button is need at times.\r\n\r\nFinally the cherry on the cake has to be the Magic Roundabout, the water here goes around and around and can creat upto three seams, the best seam is where a side channel meets the main flow and gives outstanding down time if you can hold on wait for the double suck! \r\n\r\nDirections\r\nHead to Nottingnam then follow road signs to West Bridgford and Holme Pierrepont National Water Sports Centre\r\n\r\nFor more info on British Squirtspot check out the Downtime Squirtforum\r\nhttp://www.downtimekayaks.com/forum\r\nor\r\nhttp://mushmove.co.uk/','01159824717','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (160,'Wish you where here','Lune','','GB','','YORK','Near Kirkby Longsdale','','','','','54.301778','-2.569783','','','Wish you where here is set in the wonderful Yorkshire Dales, set in a serene valley surround by feilds and woods you will find the River Lune and Rawthey confluence.\r\n\r\nThe seam is created where the two river flows meet, just upstream of the seam on the Lune is a small surf wave. The seam can be a little difficult to tap into at first and will take practice to nail every time. When you figure your charc out you will hit a seam with awsome potential, if you roam just right you will hit the locker room. The locker room is a perfectly still pool of water which will hold you down as long as your lungs can hold out, perfect for looping or just sit there and enjoy the views.\r\n\r\nDirections\r\nTake the M6 and then head for sedberg and then onto A683 towards Kirkby Longsdale. Just after you cross over the Rawthey park in small laybye\r\n(54.301778, -2.569783). Get changed then cross the road and cross farmers feild to Lune, Rawthey confluence.\r\n','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (161,'Lledr spot','Lledr','','GB','','North Wales','','','','','','53.065267','-3.818479','','','','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (162,'Bitches','Pembrokeshire coastline','','GB','','South Wales','St Davids','','','Spring tides, the bigger the better! ','','51.864779','-5.329742','','','The Bitches is a tidal race between Ramsey Island and the main land of South Wales, spring tides really bring this spot into its elements.\r\n\r\nThe Bitches is all about soul surfing, big glass waves, whirl pools, holes and seams you name it, its got it. The best way to experience this spot is to hirer a jetboat for the day! With out one your going to find it a very hard and scary days mission, swimming is not an option!\r\n\r\nDirection\r\nDrive to St Davids city in the south of wales, follow small lane down to lifeboat centre and park. Get changed, take boat or start paddling to the Bitches, best to be at the bitches 1-2hrs before high tide.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (165,'Severn Bore','Severn','','GB','','Gloucestershire','Gloucester','Severn Bore','','Spring Tides ','','51.836450','-2.357750','http://www.severn-bore.co.uk/2008.htm','','The Severn Bore is one of Britains few truly spectacular natural phenomena. It is a large surge wave that can be seen in the estuary of the River Severn, where the tidal range is the 2nd highest in the world, being as much as 50 feet (approx. 15.4m).\r\n\r\nThe Severn Bore is a soul surfers paradise and as such you will find surfers and kayakers etc all fighting to ride the way up the River Severn.\r\n\r\nFor Directions and Info check out this website.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.severn-bore.co.uk/\r\n\r\nThe Severn Bore Inn (51.836450, -2.357750) is a good place to start catching the bore, paddle down stream and then surf the bore back to your car.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (168,'Tanic Compression','West Branch Penobscot','','US','US Eastern','ME','','','','','','0','0','','','from: http://www.singingeddy.blogspot.com/\r\n\r\nTanic compression is up on the West branch of the Penobscot at a place named little eddy you can see where the flow converges at the end of this island very deep here, mellow and endless rides. Here is the angle from the downstream end of the island right in the convergence\r\n','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (167,'Pallaresa seam','Noguera Pallasera','','ES','','Sort','Sort','','','Low summer levels ','','42.449238','1.150678','','','Have no real info on this spot apart from it runs at low levels and can be feisty! I hope to be going here in May will report back after.\r\nCheck out the youtube video in media. ','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (169,'Catacomb','Piscataquog','','US','US Eastern','NH','Goffstown','','4','5.5','6','43.0132','-71.5443','','','This is on the Piscataquog in Goffstown. exploratory spot...\r\n\r\nThe put-in would be at the bridge on Henry Bridge Road, off Rt 114. There is a big bend in the river a bit below this bridge and the squirt spot is on the outside of this bend, just below some houses on Emerald Circle, I think.\r\n\r\nThe river was at 5.5 feet on Saturday during the first explore mission, probably a good medium level for this play spot.\r\n\r\nI was thinking to call it Catacomb because it is on the P-Cat and looks to be deep and dark. ','','ft','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (170,'Blue Hole','Snoqualmie','','US','US Pacific','WA','North Bend','middle fork snoqualmie','','','','47.4974','-121.7638','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=12141300','','never been here or seen it... but it would probably be worth the effort if you are going to Three Forks, to do a little run down the middle fork also. \r\n\r\nThis is total exploration, never done this run before... put in at 114st and go down the middle fork to Three Forks park... 2.5mile run, approximately.\r\n\r\nafter i got back from Three Forks recently(which is incredible btw), i saw on the angst board what sam wrote about this:\r\n\r\nIf you look upstream of Three Forks Park on the Middle Fork on that sat image, youll see a large sandy island directly across from the end of SE 114th street. The pool and convergence below that island is the Blue Hole apparently a popular local swimming hole. It, too, didnt look like much at low flows, but with a bit more water it could be promising, me thinks..\r\n\r\nLook on the sat image from mapquest.com ...its better quality than the google maps one... \r\n\r\nHere is what google maps says for directions from blue hole to three forks park: ie. the shuttle route... 2.4 mi (about 8 mins)\r\n\r\n1.Head northeast on 432nd Ave SE toward SE 112th St	0.1 mi\r\n2.432nd Ave SE turns left and becomes SE 112th St	0.3 mi\r\n3.Turn right at 428th Ave SE/Pickett Ave NE Continue to follow 428th Ave SE                                            1.7 mi\r\n4.Turn left at SE Reinig Rd	                        0.3 mi','12141300','cfs','13','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (171,'Tubes, The','Chattahoochee','','US','Dirty South','GA','Atlanta--Buford Dam','CHATTAHOOCHEE RIVER AT BUFORD DAM, NEAR BUFORD, GA','500','500-10000','10000','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ga/nwis/uv/?site_no=02334430&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062','','This spot is below Buford dam on the hooch north east of metro atlanta.  Look for the bridge on Hwy 20 over the hooch.  You can see the spot from the bridge about 200yds upstream.  Park and either hike up the river right side or just paddle up.  The spot is a large rock ledge leading into a deep pool that has two separate flowpaths.  Basically during normal periods (ie not the worst drought on record) they have a water release from the dam that goes from 500-10000 cfs in about an hour and a half.  During that time there are many cool spots that open up, the best being when there is about 2 ft of the big rock left sticking out of the water and large whirlpools develope on the middle left of the river.  It is like halls of karma but stronger and much smoother.  At the top of the release the spot kind of blows out and by that time you will be tired anyway.  Call the dam number and try and be at the spot by 1 hour after they start releasing for best results.','02334430','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (172,'Squeeze, The','Upper New','','US','US Eastern','VA','Blacksburg','Radford','2.2','2.5 to 2.7','3.0','37.2440','-80.6071','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=05_00065&format=img_default&site_no=03171000&set_logscale_y=0','','Added by Ricky Showalter\r\nThis spot is just upstream 1/4 mile from the Bubbbler and is located to the left of the Big rock on river left and in the rapid Big Falls.  See Directions to the Bubbler to find location,camping suggestions and phone gauge.  A very sweet spot with lots of possibilites for different charcs.  With some patience this spot can be very rewarding.  For the past several years the water has been dialed in for some perfect water levels prior to the Bubbler comp. during the New River Squirt Gathering of Friends in May.  Runs often during the springtime and early summer.','03171000','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (173,'White Horse','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','WV','Harper Ferry','Potomac at Harper Ferry, WV','1.0','','8.0','39.3223','-77.7207','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01620000','','Hey Harpers Ferry crew.\r\n\r\nGive us your beta!\r\n\r\nplease\r\n\r\nPosted by hero on 19:29:15 18/01/08\r\n\r\nIn Reply to: Harpers Ferry posted by Missin WV\r\n\r\nbd - funny that youll be kickin in my old grounds! at the top of whitehorse theres a little dip move on play right into main channell. but definitely do some explorin there are a lot of little options that should get your head wet.\r\n\r\nIts not going to be as sweet as below Great Falls, but some folks sink in a rapid called White Horse on the Potomac river just downstream from Harpers Ferry. There are several ways to get there. You can run from the 340 bridge over the doah to the 340 bridge of the Potomac. Another option run the needles section of the Potomac that begins at a lock on the C&O canal (river right). The last option is to park on the side of the river on 340 on the Virginia side of the river and paddle across. White Horse is the last rapid on the river right side of the Potomac. Dont know the levels, but Im sure if you explored,there are other fun spots out there. ','01620000','ft','15','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (174,'Squirtland','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','WV ','Harpers Ferry ','Harpers Ferry  confluence','5.0','','8.5','39.3229','-77.7203','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01620000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','','Squirtland is a rock ledge about 150 yds down stream from the confluence.  On the right there is a well defined channel, very good squirts to be had however there are rocks nearby. Water levels should be 5.0 up to around 8.5.  In the middle of the river at higher levels is a very nice blasting hole.\r\n\r\nNot to be missed at even higher water levels is the Maui surfing wave directly below the confluence. Level should be 11 on up to 20+.  The lower levels have a wave and a h\r\nole and the higher levels are all wave.  Bring your fast hull for this one, the sweet spot is huge and yours truely has had two hour surf sessions.  Be on the watch for debreis coming down the main flow.  Kowabunga!!','01620000','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (179,'Chertsey Weir','Thames','','GB','','Surrey','Chertsey','','','','','51.3921','-0.4871','','','Thames Weir squirting\r\nPourover runs all summer long, nice and deep for mysteries and seam for playing. \r\n\r\nWinter levels left hand side of weir when the gates are open a fantastic wave with a re-circulating eddie that just brings you back for more.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (178,'Darley Abbey','Derwent','','GB','','Derbyshire','Darley Abbey','','','5 to 6 on the gauge  ','','52.943140','-1.475511','','','Darley Abbey is a very beautiful and rustic English Village tucked away in the deepest depths of Derbyshire. \r\n\r\nThis spot has a lot in common with Flowerpots, both spots are generated by a man made weir, but even more importantly they are both next to really good pubs. :-)\r\n\r\nIf you are fed up with the might ditch that is Nottingham HP, then the Abbey is the place to go for a refreshing change of scene.\r\n\r\nThere are 3 seams to be had at Darley Abbey but the main one that comes directly of the weir is best for long smooth down time.\r\n\r\nThe lower seam, river right of the big island below the river left weir, works in most levels to varying degrees.','','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (176,'Sawyers Rapid','North Umpqua','','US','US Pacific','OR','Drain','Winchester','','','','43.6628','-123.3152','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14319500&set_logscale_y=1','','Lots of fun wave trains, and mush moves on this 2.3 mile run. Put in at the gravel turn off 2.3 miles upstream from the take out: Scott Creek River Access, Boat Ramp..  There is a spot half way down on this run, on far river left, that reminded me of Twisted Sister... didnt get down here yet, but it definetly is worth checking out some more..','14319500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (180,'Shepperton Weir','Thames','','GB','','Surrey','Shepperton','','','','','51.3808','-0.4581','','','Shepperton weir offers interesting squirt action. Make sure you use the main weir by the slalom club as the new back weir is looking dangerous. \r\n\r\nShepperton weir varies dramatically, you have the weir pool itself what can go from flushy to boily grade 5 eddies do not go near the side gates if they are open. Other than that you have lots of interesting seams to explore from the main flow but also the river converges 4 points from the backweir, wey canal and wey flood tribrutry creating a huge eddie to explore. \r\n\r\nFun to be had, but not for the faint hearted.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (181,'Browns Hole','Mckenzie','','US','US Pacific','OR','Vida','','0.0','2.0','3.0','44.1289','-122.5405','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=01_00065&format=img_default&site_no=14162500&set_logscale_y=0','','Exploratory...\r\n\r\nStrong eddy line just downstream of browns hole. Been here at 2.5-3.0 ft and it is very dynamic with lots of power.. surging whirlpools. Probably more controlable and chill at a lower level like below 2ft.\r\n\r\nCross the mckenzie at the covered bridge, and follow the road till it turns to dirt..go another couple of minutes.. one of the last pulloffs will be what your looking for. You can see the rock outcropping on the river left as you are driving down the road. \r\n\r\nSweet river side car camping is available right there! This is public land so technically speaking you are not breaking the law by camping there. Fire ring and camping spots are all over the place and a 50ft walk from the eddy line.  The only downside is that you are not out in the middle of no-where: there are houses across the river from the spot, but they are out of view from the camping area.. so safety meetings should probably take place around the campfire, and before you get in the water.','14162500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (183,'Dream Seam','Snake','','US','US Mountain','WY','Alpine','Alpine','4000','5000','7500','43.19970','-110.86337','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=13022500','','For direct access, find Dream Seam parking at mile marker 127 (Last I was there, the mile marker was gone, but you can extrapolate from the ones that are still in place.) It is just a dirt pulloff on the left side of the road as you drive downstream (from Jackson toward Alpine.)  Walk downstream about 200 feet and find the trail (steep!) that takes you to the river.  Or run the usual whitewater section from West Table to Sheep Gulch - lots of good squirt play the whole the way (8 miles) with deep water and few hazards.  Youll come to Dream Seam about 3 miles downstream from the West Table boat ramp.  Or for maximum squirt fun per feet of river, put in at Taco Hole and take out at Dream Seam.  Shuttle is 0.8 miles.  :-)\r\n\r\nDream Seam is a river left eddy where the river widens dramatically after a sharp right hand bend & constriction.  The pool is VERY deep and no hazards have been detected, other than the possibility of going too deep & too long, especially at higher flows. At medium flows it is a powerful squirt arena, where the possibilties have not yet been fully tapped.\r\n\r\nby kelly','13022500','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (186,'Wenatchee Run','Wenatchee','','US','US Pacific','WA','Cashmere','PESHASTIN','2000','','15000','47.5206','-120.4690','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=12459000','','There is probably some downtime on this river.. but i havent found the goods yet..\r\n\r\nits a fun class 3 downriver squirt boat run..\r\nanywhere from 2500-10,000+cfs is probably good.. \r\n\r\nthere is a festival June 14-15.. see the gatherings page for more info or this link\r\nhttp://www.wenatcheeriver.com/\r\n\r\n-weaver','12459000','cfs','12','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (188,'Dizzyland','Yakima','','US','US Pacific','WA','Cle Elum','YAKIMA RIVER AT UMTANUM, WA','2650','4000','4400','47.1845','-120.9199','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wa/nwis/uv/?site_no=12484500&PARAmeter_cd=00060,00065','','Take 1-90 East out of Seattle and go to Cle Elum exit. Follow the exit and road past the Safeway (cheapest gas around too) go to the second traffic light and turn Right. Follow this road across I-90. At what might seem to be the end of the road (only a block or two past I-90 overpass) turn left towards Hansen Pond. This will dead end into a county park with a pond on one side of the parking lot and the Yakima river on the other side. Drive to the end of the parking lot and park. Walk 40 feet to the river edge and the line(s) are apparent. It is obvious and the conveyor belt that feeds right into the seam makes this spot seem like an amusement park ride. There are two lines the upper eddy line is the best. Weve been there when the Yakima (at Umtatum) is running at 4100 cfs and it is sinfully delicious but might be a bit nerve racking upon first apperance. It no longer has the downward pull below 2600cfs. Not sure how high it goes.\r\n\r\nadmin note: exit dumps you onto 1st street. second light is oaks ave which goes over RR tracks then over I-90.. then you make a left on Hanson Pond Rd. This hanson pond road is not on the map.. but follow it to the promise land. The map on the explore tab points to the approximate location of the spot.','12484500','cfs','14','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (190,'Deschutes-EXP3','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','North Junction','','','','','44.9760','-121.0735','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','totally exploratory...never been there.  Looks interesting on the sattelite images if you switch to the terrain layer...\r\n\r\nthere is an islands here of interest..   might be a good convergence.. another island is very close, just upstream, and worth looking at while you are here...\r\n\r\nFrom Maupin, take the BLM road upstream 21.2 mi.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (191,'Deschutes-EXP1','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','','','','','45.2847','-121.0253','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','totally exploratory.. never been here. \r\n\r\nPre-emptively calling this spot \r\nLopado­temakhjjjfjfdjsfdskkljgfdshsdfhrereiurytipwpopzsismlxkcjjknvgkdsjlklkaeyrhtblhfblsjbflhjbsvlj-dfgthsljh-hlgahjgsdjhgfjhdgsjo­selakho­galeo­kranio­leipsano­drim­hypo­trimmato­silphio­karabo­melito­katakekhy­meno­kikhl­epi­kossypho­phatto­perister­alektryon­opto­kephallio­kigklo­peleio­lag&#333,io­siraio­baph&#275,­tragano­pterýg&#333,ne  \r\n... meaning name of a dish compounded of all kinds of dainties, fish, flesh, fowl, and sauces.\r\n\r\nMight be a convergence after that island.. \r\n\r\nGo to where 216 crosses the deschutes and head downstream 2.4miles\r\n\r\nIf this is bunk, there is another island futher downstream...  im calling that spot exploration2','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (192,'Deschutes-EXP2','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','','','','','45.3305','-120.9394','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','This is 8miles futher downstream from exploration2... so that is about 10.4 miles from 216 on the BLM road. \r\n\r\ntotally exploratory, never been here.  \r\n\r\nsattelite image looks like there may be a convergence below that island.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (196,'Deschutes-EXP5','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','','','','','45.3078','-121.0017','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','island convergence..','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (193,'Deschutes-EXP4','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','North Junction','','','','','44.9670','-121.0835','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','totally exploratory...never been there.  Looks interesting on the sattelite images if you switch to the terrain layer...\r\n\r\nthere is an islands here of interest..   might be a good convergence.. another island is very close, just downstream, and worth looking at while you are here...\r\n\r\nFrom Maupin, take the BLM road upstream 21.2 mi.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (194,'Deschutes Mouth - Columbia','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','','','','','','45.6334','-120.9124','','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','totally exploratory, never been here...\r\n\r\nThis might not be good because i fear there wont be enough flow/force coming down the deschutes as it gets to the columbia...but who knows. it might be awesome... and totally convenient since its right off rt84.\r\n\r\nworth a drive by to get a visual..\r\nlook at the satellite image.. there is an island right before the deschutes meets the columbia, that might have a gentle convergence after it.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (195,'Twin Springs','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','','2000','','5000','45.3072','-121.0151','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=14103000&set_logscale_y=1','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','about a half mile upstream of Twin Springs Campground.\r\n10+sec moves possible for sure...\r\n\r\nFires not permited untill after Oct 15th since this is a High Desert prone to wild fire. fires only in designated fire containers in campgrounds.\r\n\r\nYou are required to have a $3 boater pass, that you can get here:\r\nhttp://boaterpass.com/\r\nor at the corner market in maupin. BLM officers patrol the dirt road and can ask you for yours.. ive gotten questions 2 out of the 4 times ive been there... so you might want to be SAFE and get one.\r\n\r\nYou are required to camp in designated campsites, of which there are several on the 18mile dead ending dirt road, but i slept in my rig parked on a pullout right above the spot with no problems.. dont see why this wouldnt be ok as long as you are low key about it, expecially during the off season like fall/winter. its a mad house out here in the summer, so you may get hassled then.\r\n\r\nfrom shears falls, head downstream several miles until you get to Twin Springs Campground. Then turn around and go back about half a mile to the small island you see toward river right. there will be two small pulloffs right there. This dirt road is notorious for flat tires.. i got one, it was awesome... and during the summer the cops will bust you for speeding..its 20 most of the way. you couldnt drive much faster than that anyway because the road is so shitty.\r\n\r\nCharc that was working for me:  \r\nyou start on the river right shore, and ferry over to this island in the middle of the river. i was using this as a staging area before going for a mystery, but you could totally go right into the move on the initial ferry.\r\n\r\nso from there, i was going lefty or righty, both worked.. but the part of the charc i think i figured out was that i needed to be more in the river left current that was more gentle, and then sorta float and screw into the river right current. if you got too involved in the river right current, you would start to travel fast and get blown downstream.\r\n-weaver','14103000','cfs','18','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (197,'Spitchwick','Dart','','GB','','DEVON','Ashburton','Dartcom','','Throw the Third arch at Newbridge.','','50.529399','-3.815102','http://www.dartcom.co.uk/index.php?pageID=6','','This spot is on par, if not better than the Breatherlizer seam! \r\n\r\nSpitchwick seam has a massive eddy service which is really deep and slowly feeds you back into the seam perfect for throwing shapes or chilling out in whilst you wait your turn and watch the world go bye.\r\n\r\nThe seam it self runs along side a fast flowing wave train, with small whirlpools forming down the eddy fence. The best spot for plugging into this seam is at the point where the diagonal starts to form, that feeds in to the first wave of the wave train. Back cut here and your charc will send you spiraling down into oblivion underneath the wave train, I found hand paddles work best, less chance of getting beaten by the wave train and whirlpools! Once your under hold on for a long and dark experience, this pool is deep and long, happy hunting mystery lovers.\r\n\r\nThis spot work really well with lots of water may have possible potential in medium to low water but dont quote me on that, just yet! Best way to gauge if their is plenty of water is to use Dartcom, weather station. If their has been 30ml plus of rain on Dartmoor in a 24hr period then youre probably good to go.\r\n\r\nDirection\r\n\r\nJust upstream of Breatherlizer Spot, either get on at Newbridge and float down, or take a short walk to Spitchwick.','','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (198,'Corner Pocket','Saikawa','','JP','','unknown_state','','','','','','36.348781','137.914655','','','This arena was found 100 yards downstream of another spot where the 2004 gathering was to occur, but that spot had disappeared.  Tim Hollar found this spot, the gathering was moved here, and good downtime was had by all.  The local squirtists report the spot was gone the next year.\r\n\r\nlat/lng provided by Hiro.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (200,'Elwha-EXP1','Elwha','','US','US Pacific','WA','Elwha','Elwha','500','','2000','48.0284','-123.5936','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wa/nwis/uv/?site_no=12045500','','Total Exploratory... camping across from this spot at Elwha Campgrounds.   there is a convergence in walking distance from the campground, with potential other spots in this whole lower section.\r\n\r\nSite of TurkeyFest2008 gathering.\r\nhttp://sinkspots.com/TurkeyFest2008/TurkeyFest2008.php  \r\n\r\noff of 101, turn left onto Olympic Hotsprings Road before you get to the town of Elwha... go about 5miles south into the park and you will see the Elwha pay campground on your left.\r\n\r\ncurrent min/max flows are recommended from american white water for a playboat run.','12045500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
