    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (204,'Out Of The Blue','Waikato','','NZ','','','Taupo','','','120 cumecs','','0','0','','','Found by Greg Nicks \r\n\r\n\r\nplease add some beta!\r\ncheck out the vid...on you tube\r\n\r\nHi Guys, Greg here. Just stumbled on this site and saw that someone had added my spot on here! Cool!!I found this spot about 5 years ago and called it out of the blue because of the blue crystal clear water and the fact that it came......\\out of the blue\\\r\n\r\nHere is the beta:\r\nI am the only squirt boater in NZ so if anyone ever wants to come to this spot it would absolutely blow  me away to have someone else to sink with. I know this is a soul sport but this is ridiculous!! If anyone ever wants to squirt here then come stay at my place in Taupo and I\\ll see you right.\r\n\r\nBasically it goes on 90-120 cumecs, you get up to 10 secs  head under in crystal clear water. It is 7 minutes drive from my house which is good because the flow is quite hard to predict, I check the mighty river power website and if the flow is good then i Go.The  Water is warmer in summer and thats when I generally go.I ts just a regular eddyline with a small whirly.It is right outside the very expensive Huka lodge which is where the Queen stays when she visits NZ so I make sure I always urinate on the Island in the middle of the river in full view.\r\n\r\nI emigrated here 6 years and there is like no squirt scene :(, but some cool other paddlin and folk so thats ok:). Are there any other squiters out there?\r\n\r\nAny way just stoked to be still doing some squirtin,cheersGreg \r\n\r\nSeriously If any one wants to come to NZ to go squirtin then please please look me up....you\\ll find me just ask for the only squirt boater in NZ,)','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (205,'Two fat hoes sitting off in a room!','','','US','US Mountain','CO','','','','','','38.5711','-106.3230','','','Need to get your head straightened?  Rancho Relaxo has several head squaring techniques.  Contact Weaver for the 411.','','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (206,'tarmonbarry','river shannon','','IE','','','','','unknown','11 gates','unknown','0','0','','','situated in the Irish midlands,tarmonbarry is a recently discovered play and squirt spot.Downstream of the towns bridge there is a weir with sluice gates on river left.when the shannon is at a high level these gates are opened and a wave forms downriver of the gates.to surfers right of the wave there is one of the most powerful eddy lines in Ireland.\r\nwarning:dont try to get down time too close to the weir as there is a concrete apron downriver of the weir','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (207,'randolphs leap','Findhorn','','GB','','Scotland','','','','','','0','0','http://www.sepa.org.uk/water/river_levels/river_level_data.aspx?id=234306','','Findhorn gorge, Low water. There is a large island just down from Randolphs leap as the two pieces of water re-join they practically slam into each other. \r\nCourse you then either have to paddle the gorge or you can walk out on river right. \r\n-Chris Jones','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (208,'S-Bend','Skagit','','US','US Pacific','WA','Skagit','','1500','','8000','48.6014','-121.3583','','','Here is the basic info on the area:\r\nhttp://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River_detail_id_2206_\r\n\r\nWe typically look for the Sbend rapid and scramble down to the river just above the rapid. Not much to do in the rapid, but it is fun to run for the sake of running a mellow class II+/III- rapid. We take out either at the take out listed here, or we take out after the old bridge abutments (there is some decent play to be had just downstream of them at a rock on river left). If you take out after the old bridge abutments, it is a scramble up the bank and through the woods back to Hwy 11.\r\n\r\nWe’ve explored this whole stretch at varying flows. The best spot is just below the S-bend rapids at the rock below the old bridge abutments. But we have found intermittent spots along the way. Sometimes they are in, other times not so much.\r\n\r\nBridge abutment is just downstream from S-bend rapid. Where the road comes back to be parallel and right next to the river. There is a pull out on west side of the road that accesses power lines. Park there. Cross the street. Walk upstream a few hundred yards and then to the river. You can see the abutments from the river, but they are hard to spot from the road.\r\n\r\nLook for the parking area/powerline access. (you can see it on the map).\r\n~Info Gleened from Dale K. \r\n\r\nNOAA hotline for gauge: 206-526-8530\r\nthe usgs gage 12181000 is at the take out..at copper creek.','12181000','cfs','12','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (209,'Feyrer Park','Molalla','','US','US Pacific','OR','Molalla','Canby','500','','4000','45.1381','-122.5334','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=14200000','','90* convergence around a island.\r\n2300cfs at canby looked epic here.. \r\n..although unexplored.\r\n\r\nyou can see it from the bridge. park and play from boat launch at\r\nFeyrer Park. \r\n\r\nFrom molalla on rt211, make a right following signs to Feyrer Park...then the road quickly bears to the left. youll drive through the small park and youll pass a right turn into the park boat launch. you may miss the boat launch turn, and if you did, youll cross the bridge in about 5 seconds later. look to your right off the bridge to see the convergence below.  posted 6am to 6pm hours at boat launch. you can see the spot from the end of the boat launch as well.','14200000','cfs','18','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (211,'Jacks or Better...','Green','','US','Dirty South','NC','','','jacks -','? -','trips -','35.2795599','-82.3467837','','','unconfirmed, and likely to stay that way','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (213,'Tuck Hole','Tuckaseegee','','US','Dirty South','NC','Dillsboro','','dusty -','not sure -','refrigerator doors -','35.3783572','-83.2653547','','','Small/tight drop spot just behind the infamous Tuck Hole.  Very satisfying in the hot summer months.  Primarily developed by Crazy Jim MacArthur and T. Davis.  Upstream and around the corner from BKs Tiki Bar.  Oh, you can cartwheel here too, lots of people have.  If you want to use the bamboo tube, just dig around the obvious cracks at the base of the viewing podium.','','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (229,'Sky','Skykomish','','US','US Pacific','WA','Index','SKYKOMISH RIVER NEAR GOLD BAR, WA','1500','3000','4000','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wa/nwis/uv/?site_no=12134500&PARAmeter_cd=00060,00065','','Squirted main Sky river from Confluence of SF and NF through Boulder rapid. Take out at Splilt Rock. 3 hours of generous play time.\r\n\r\nRan at low flows, but the river is channeled with plenty of great eddy lines to mush in and a few to sink in. Of note were two places - more can be found with more exploration (and more water).\r\n\r\n1) River Right JUST below Boulder Drop. You can portage the rapid and put in below the rapid on River Left, them ferry to river right. Seam is coming off of the river right side of bottom ledge. Try it, youll like it. (if you are up to it, you can also run the rapid) then play at the bottom while you wait for the rest of your group to portage. :>)\r\n\r\n2) Center of the river at bottom of Lunch Hole. Nice beach on river right and you can access this spot from the road on River left. Parking may be a challenge though, so you may have to walk from an appropriate pull out. Ill get mileage marker info next time I am there.\r\nSpot is formed off of the back of the last hole which at this level was more of a pourover. Trust the downstream thrust and you will avoid the rocks that form the ledge. Ride the slab down - DEEP. I was in a full float PFD and my bigfoot and was able to completely disappear for a couple of seconds each time. Would be really fun to roam without PFD! Super deep pool behind the line with other eddy lines to explore.\r\n\r\nNOTE: Just guessing on the max - min - ideal flow levels. It was fun when we were there at 1600 cfs.','12134500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (216,'Three Mile Island','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Falmouth','Harrisburg','8','?','10','40.133056','-76.724722','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','I checked this spot out after reading this in the account of a local boater named Pat Reilly:\r\n...at 8 feet on the Harrisburg gauge... ...at the dam’s upper end is a big circular eddy with whirlpools spinning off the eddyline that are great for mystery moves in low volume boats... \r\nsee the whole article here: http://www.bluemountainoutfitters.net/Rvrtales/pat_06.htm\r\n\r\nThus far Ive only seen this spot at low levels, but the structure of a nice mystery spot is there.  This part of the dam is like a long concrete slide.  An eddy forms at the river left shoulder of the dam.  The eddy current curls around and collects against the bottom edge of the dry portion of the dam, which feeds current back into the slab at right angles to the main flow, creating a strong looking squeeze.  I dont, however, see a drop in the river bottom to create the down-draft.\r\n\r\nAccess to this spot is terrible, and involves either a long upstream paddle, a short trespass on a nuclear energy facility, or a long flatwater lake crossing followed by a short trespass on the power companys dam.  Choose your own adventure.\r\n\r\n5.30.09:  This spot is no good up to 6 ft.  Maybe its good at 7 or 8 ft.  I dunno.\r\n\r\nby Dan Mayer.','01570500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (269,'Weldon','Roanoke','','US','Dirty South','NC','Weldon','Roanoke Rapids / Halifax','7,470','8,270','~8,500?','36.4278','-77.591717','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nc/nwis/uv?dd_cd=04&format=gif&period=7&site_no=02080500','http://www.dom.com/about/stations/hydro/roanoke-rapids/projected-flow-releases.jsp','Weldon, NC. Its just off I-95 (exit 173) ~8 miles South of the NC/VA boarder. Right where US-301 / US-158 cross the river. Its park & play w/ a city park & boat ramp right there. Just upstream of the boat ramp is a grassy, sandy or muddy cove (depending on water level).  This is much easier on boats than the ramp.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/1116/ is the AW page for it, but theyve only listed info from surface boaters at low water. Disregard everything they say about a lake downstream, there isnt one. \r\n\r\nThe ideal level seems to be 8,270cfs on the Roanoke Rapids gauge: http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nc/nwis/uv?dd_cd=04&format=gif&period=7&site_no=02080500 \r\n& 26.33 on the Halifax gauge: http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nc/nwis/uv?dd_cd=01&dd_cd=02&format=gif&period=7&site_no=0208062765 \r\nTheres another spot on river right that is good around 28.76 on the Halifax gauge. \r\n\r\nThe best time to catch it seems to be in the spring when flows are regulated for the stripers. The rest of the year they are up & down w/ the flow, sometimes twice a day.','02080500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (217,'Falmouth','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Falmouth','Harrisburg','4.4','4.6','4.7','40.122','-76.718','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=ctp&gage=harp1&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','Falmouth is the name of the town on the East (river left) shore.  The area is also known as York Haven, the name of the town on the West shore, and the name of the dam and power station.  On topo maps, its called Conewago Falls, since Conewago Creek enters from the East at this point.\r\n\r\nThe fun spots are clustered near river right, under the upstream-most set of high voltage wires that cross the river.  There is a convergence on river right, where a slab of current joins the main flow after a long trip around an island and over some ledges.  The last ledge forms a fun but shallow hole, where you can catch a surf before heading down the slab into the seam.  This spot only works from 4.5-4.7 ft.  3-4 second helmet mysteries thus far.\r\n\r\n50 yards to river left is a dunking rock with a sloping edge that will give up a short helmet deep dunk with a light stern tap.  Best at 4.7.  \r\n\r\nAbout 50 yards upstream from there is a funky three-way convergence I call the Tripod.  It looks like nothing, but will serve a 4 second, no-travel dunk with your head about 1 foot under.  This spot is fickle and only works at 4.5 ft.\r\n\r\nThere are some creeking lines through the bouldery islands at the base of the dam.  Good from 4.5-6 ft.  Watch for some sieves in the boulders.\r\n\r\nAs the river rises to 6 feet and above, the middle of the river turns into a mess of waves and swells, which are really fun to paddle through.  No big holes or nasty rocks, just fun.\r\n\r\nThere is reportedly a huge glassy surfing wave that comes in at 8 ft.  Its called Hawaii 5-0 and is said to be suitable for long-boats only and has no eddy service.  Ive also seen this section at high water (12 feet) and there are massive Grand Canyon-style wavetrains exploding down the middle of the river.\r\n\r\nAt levels below 4.5 ft, most of the river is directed to the York Haven power station, and this whole section of the river is reduced to a trickle.\r\n\r\nBy Dan Mayer','01570500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (221,'Arcadia','James River','','US','US Eastern','VA','Arcadia','James River at Buchanan','2000','2200-3000','5000','37.5451','-79.6333','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02019500','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=bnnv2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','The layout: \r\nSpot is downstream of the red pin on sinkspots, in between the two islands. The flow splits around the top island, and when it comes back together it forms a big squeeze Ill tentatively call Bermuda South. The river left channel is pinched by some 45 degree rock layers that extend from the left shore, forming a new river gorge-ish wave train that runs about 100 feet. On the river left side of this train is a huge eddy the size of a baseball infield with counterclockwise return service back to the top of the wave train. This swirl takes you along the top of the lower island. The lower end of the upper island has a nice place to empty the boat and take breaks/stash packs/safety break, or just do it from the cobble-y beach by the tracks.  \r\n\r\nCharcs: \r\nI knew I had found the goods when my very first drop gave up a 3 second helmet under ride even with my life jacket on... \r\nYou can tap the RR side of the wave train for a good dunk anywhere from the root at the top of the eddy to 20 feet down the eddy line. The eddy here had some good upstream momentum along with small whirlpools and big boils. The RL side of the wave train also has many entry charcs to try. Going under at the first wave you will clip a rock, 2nd wave on down is deep and clean.  3rd and 4th waves are worth attempting too, at 3000 cfs they seemed to form the strongest squeezes on this side. As your wave train ride plays out you can either take the conveyer belt left and back to the top or move back to river right and mush into Bermuda South, hopefully getting a no travel ride. The squeeze here extends below the point of no return dropping into the next rapid and past the safety of the big eddy back to river left. Helmet under rides are possible at all 3 spots. \r\nI also got a couple good neck deep with PFD rides below the bottom island but the convergence is not nearly as strong. There is a small eddy to get back up but its not nearly as effortless or grandiose as the top arena. \r\n\r\nAccess: \r\nFrom Exit 168 on I-81 head east on route 614 then go @ 3 miles. When you cross the bridge over the James park at a public access point on your right. There is a very tempting ATV trail near the river that goes up the river right bank, but on the way home I talked to a local that lives up the road and he said the unfriendly landowner usually carries a shotgun on his ATV... Besides by the time the ATV trail is even with the 2 islands you are in sight of a house AND have to bushwack a tenth of a mile through poisin ivy and stinging nettles. That leaves the railroad track on river left, which is a good 30-40 feet below the bridge, didnt scout out a descent. Its much easier to spot the islands from this side of the river. The next putin upstream is only about 4 miles away at Buchanan, maybe theres more goods along the way? \r\n\r\nExtras: \r\nAt this level the train has 2 surfable waves at the top, didnt do much for me in my ninja but kept my buddy in plastic entertained (wave was ideal for a 7-9 foot boat, 6 ft spuds so-so). Most of yall with cruiser bottoms can mix it up with a little surfing up top, maybe some clues? \r\nThe top island had several flat spots that would be ideal for camping, but Id take a machete to clear out some PI and SN... Hard to bring a canoe on a long road trip out of towners but you could make a comfy home for a few days... \r\nThe huge deep eddy is allegedly a prime fishing spot if you have a sig. other or buddy whos into that... \r\nIts only a HALF MILE upstream of the bridge and 3 MILES from the interstate! \r\n\r\nLinks: \r\nhttp://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/5075/ \r\n\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02019500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062\r\n\r\nAHPS also has a 2 day forecast for this gauge here:\r\nhttp://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=bnnv2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','02019500','cfs','19','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (222,'No Name','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Rowlesburg','Albright','1800','2500','6000','39.3805','-79.7054','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv?03070260','','No name is the spot on the Narrows section upstream from Fascination Alley.  Its by the only house/cabin on this stretch of road.  Not really sure the best, min, or max levels just made up those number.\r\n\r\nIts a righty charc out of the river right eddy.  Read it and weep lefties.  Not sure about backcuts.   GPS ADDRESS:  6361 River Road, Tunnelton WV 26444.','03070260','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (223,'Trick Saddle','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Harrisburg','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','5.7','6.1','6.2','40.356936','-76.934488','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','This spot is on the Dauphin Narrows, about 100 yards upstream from the Mystery Machine but closer to shore.  Its formed by a saddle-shaped ledge, which slopes to river left.  You basically ride a sheet of water that drops off the ledge and slips under the stagnant patch of water in the eddy.  If you swim the eddy, you can feel it - your whole body is in still water but there is fast current around your ankles.  Its only 5-6 ft deep here.\r\n\r\nLefty backcut is best approach cuz it tends to keep you engaged in the smooth eddy current.  With a regular entry, you tend to peel out underwater, and hit turbulent water at the eddy wall -often rocketing you back to the surface.  The spot is shallow, and you will tap rocks until you work out your charc.  Once you figure out the sweet spot, you can get smooth rides with little or no rock tapping.','01570500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (225,'Slammer','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Harrisburg','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','4.5','4.8','5.0','40.355996','-76.931516','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','I almost forgot about this spot.  Its probably the least desirable downtime in the Narrows, but when its the only game in town, its worth a visit.  Its formed by a shallow ledge pourover, and will give up a 5 second ride in water that cant be more than 5 feet deep.  The drop is very fast, and often results in your hull bouncing off the bottom - hence the name.','01570500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (226,'Yough Exploratory','Youghiogheny','','US','US Eastern','PA','Connellsville','Youghiogheny River at Ohiopyle, PA','1.8','??','9','39.982939','-79.588334','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?03081500','','Jim Snyder reports that Jeff has identified a potential DT spot on the Yough - near Connellsville.  Said to be similar to Mellow Ledge!  Location Ive provided is just a guess based on aerial photos.  Exploration pending...   ...7/9/09 - Dan Mayer\r\n\r\nIm pasting in the threads from Angst Board that discusses all the DT available on the Lower Yough.. ...5/5/10 - Dan Mayer:\r\n\r\nI walked about a mile up onto the Middle before doing a Lower run. For both the middle and lower there was nothing epic but there may be somewhere between 3 and 4 feet--I would go back for this. There were loads of mouth deep spots and I got my head wet in several. There was one spot in Maze where I was able to roam with my head several inches below the water for two to three spins. There was also a pretty neat spot on river right at the bottom of Cucumber--I was able to get my head wet there as well. - Steve Graybill\r\n\r\nWatch out in the maze, a friend of mine pinned his Milennium Falcon there years ago deep underwater in a V shaped notch. Had to blow out his cockpit and most of his deck to get out - Benny\r\n\r\nyears ago, remely, stahlman, driver and i used to get a couple second head under rides at a spot toward the end of the lower yough run...after swimmers rapid somewhere on river right... not sure if this is the same spot.. hey amish kids, you remember were that spot was? - Weaver\r\n\r\nTheres an obscure spot near the end that Ive seen some good sampling of- its just above the last significant drop before Stewarton- the river runs toward the right and theres some low rocks in the current. Ive seen zombies entranced there and getting consistent 3-5 seconds. \r\n\r\nAnd bro Jeff says hes spotted a super nice spot- way down by Connellsville- park and play. Ive got to go check that out soon- he says it looks great- like mellow ledge. - Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nturns out Jeffs idea of park and play aint the same as mine- so- the best I can figure is you can get within a couple miles by road... Ill try to scout it out on my bike soon. Thats the best I can do. Ill take a camera. - Jim Snyder\r\n\r\nAt summer lows, like around 2 ft or below, that eddyline below cucumber has gots lots of rocks. I have clipped them stern squirting that line. \r\n\r\nTheres a convergence in piddley (right below cucumber) that is a pretty good mush move at the very bottom of the big eddy in the middle \r\n\r\nI always had fun below schoolhouse rock. The eddyline coming off the RR side of the rock is real deep and strong, then theres a pinch in the river right below that had tons of bubbles, I always figured that would serve up something. Ive always just cruized the run in my long boat, never squirted below the loop.  When I taught on the yough, we would let kids jump off this rock in the pinch and the current would pull you way deep and downstream, like I said lots of bubbles - Ru Tang\r\n\r\n7/18/11 Dan Mayer:  Looking at some birdseye photos, I think I may have located this mellow ledge that Jeff Snyder mentioned.  The river splits around an island, and on left side of left channel is a huge sloping rock with juicy looking seam arcing off it.  Roughly 1 mile up rail-trail from the end of Riverside Rd.  Updated map coordinates.','03081500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (227,'Chinon','Vienne','','FR','','Loire Valley','Chinon','','','','','47.1649','0.2382','','','pierre says this is a world class spot at higher water..\r\n\r\nThe river splits up stream and then comes back together just below the bridge in the town . The water is warm and brown ish just like sweet hp.It was offering me a quick dunk or two but nothing special, higher water would deff be good.\r\n says downtime dave after checking it out.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (228,'Appletini','Warfe','','GB','','North Yorkshire','Appletreewick','','','','','54.0355','-1.9289','','','Situated at Appletreewick on the River Wharfe this is spot offers soft smooth rides on a righty seem half way down the falls and goes in super low and normal low levels.\r\n\r\nsee claireo on pics and vids page...','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (277,'Bathtub','Susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Port Trevorton','Susquehanna at Sunbury','5.7','7.7','7.9','40.660066','-76.917056','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/pa/nwis/uv/?site_no=01554000','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=ctp&gage=sbyp1','Named The Bathtub because the spot only comes in during the summer and the Susquehanna is 80+ degrees when its that low.\r\n\r\nLocation is below the 4th small rock on the upper set of ledges at Mckees Half Falls rest stop off of pa rt 11 & 15.  You will see a small curler wave about 60 ft behind the main rock this is the entry point standard Lefty.  you should also see a second ledge behind the curler wave this is the main suck zone but you must enter at the wave to get the suck.  I focus about 3 inches above the tip of the wave which moves slightly up and down river Then drop my right edge while spinning slowly to the left and down you go.  Rides are in the 6-11 second range but might go longer with more time spent here.  there is a rock I gently tap on my way down but other are missing it.  happy sinking.\r\n\r\n7/7/11.  Dan Mayer:  I have been comparing gauges and I think the Sunbury gauge might be a better metric for this spot.  Harrisburg is 36 lazy miles downstream and there are some major tributaries in between.  Sunbury is 14 miles upstream.\r\n\r\n7/11/11.  Dan Mayer:  Officially switching to Sunbury gauge.  Range based on documented sessions.  Low end is 4-second head-under dry-knuckle dips.  High end is 12+ seconds, smooth and 6 ft deep.  I suspect it may be good as high as 7.9 or 8.0','01554000','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (232,'Fishing with Gandhi','Middle/West Prong of Little River','','US','Dirty South','TN','Townsend','','3.0','4.0-4.5','6.0','35.6573','-83.7100','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?03497300','','The confluence of the Middle Prong (Tremont) and the West Prong of the Little River, Fishing with Gandhi, was pioneered during the spring of 2009 by Jeremy McCreary and named after a low-budget comedy with the same name.  Look for rain in the forecast if you want to hit this fishing hole, as the Little River gage near Townsend should read at least 3.0 feet.  Parking is available on the left before the bridge.  With great eddy service, multiple charcs, no hazards, and a setting that can only be found in the Great Smokey Mountains National Park Fishing with Gandhi is truly a special place.  Once you have had your fill at the fishing hole either float or drive downstream to the Y.  Make sure you save a little for the Y, because if Gandhi is in then the Y is going to offer up some big downtime too. If you are still hungry for downtime after a day at these two spots then try scuba diving.','03497300','ft','18','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (233,'Barking Dog','South Fork American','','US','US Pacific','CA','Coloma','','1000','2000','4000?','38.809117','-120.921059','http://www.dreamflows.com/graphs/day.075.php','','I had seen a few people squirting here this past fall, but they were playing the upper of the 2 squeezes--which is also fun, but doesnt compare to the lower one :)\r\n\r\nNoah joined me yesterday to explore the lower squeeze (20 feet below the wave on the right convergence). We had a BLAST. This seam is truly world-class, offering us up LOTS of 10-20 second rides with a TON of variety in the realm. Its a small channel that reconnects to the main flow on river right below the wave--we generally entered the small channel from the downstream side just above the convergence spinning clockwise (front cut). Wed often be head-down before hitting the main squeeze, but 1/2 the time, the seam would push us upstream into a calm zone above the squeeze with little support. 1/2 the time itd push us out into the main current where it gets deep and great. Sometimes it would do one, then the other--way fun!\r\n\r\nAnyway, the water is clear and just warm enough to avoid brain freezes and its often warm and sunny there.  This place is definitely worth playing any time--Its right up there with Halls and Smoothie. \r\n-StephenWright\r\n\r\nPS if you park at Lotus Campground to park and play, you cant have a dog in your car...the manager lady there freaked-out on us and I may have been permanently banned from that access....doh!','','cfs','17','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (234,'Skook','Skookumchuck Narrows','','CA','','BC','','','12 knots','','15 knots','49.737317','-123.896428','http://tbone.biol.sc.edu/tide/tideshow.cgi?site=Sechelt+Rapids%2C+British+Columbia+Current+(use+with+caution)','','The Skook. Paddlers travel from all over the world to experience this phenomena. The Skookumchuck Tidal Rapid forms when the tide rises in the ocean, and accelerates as it is constricted through the channel leading into a large fjord area. During the tides, approximately 200 billion gallons of water jets through the narrow channel at speeds of 10-17 knots during flood tides. It is an amazing site to see, even if you werent going to kayak. Skookumchuck means Strong Water, and this area will not disappoint. \r\n\r\nBesides the wave that is sick to surf in a old Rave or other long glass boat... there are giant ass whirlpools that i would be afraid to get into, perhaps dishing out terminal/oblivian mysteries. Not suggesting you drop in them in your slinky destination boat at max flood tide! BUT, i would guess at the correct (smaller side) levels, you could get quality and controlled world class mysteries, just like Singing Eddy or some other tidal spot..\r\n\r\nTo get to the Skook is quite an ordeal. First, you must get into Canada, easier for some than others. Usually the Canadians are cool, but are suspicious of kayakers, so most of the time you get stopped and inspected at the Border. Once in Canada, you need to get to Highway 1, and to Horseshoe Bay Ferry Terminal, about 20 minutes outside of Vancouver, BC. The ferry to get on is the one to Langdale, and it runs roughly every two hours (BC Ferries Schedule). The ferry is quite nice, but quite expensive, so planning ahead and carpooling up is essential (BC Ferries Fare Schedule). Keep in mind that your car will probably be charged Overheight because of the kayaks, nearly doubling the cost of crossing. Note though, that you dont need to pay for the ferry on the way back. \r\n\r\nferry schedule: http://www.bcferries.bc.ca/schedules/mainland/vasc-current.html\r\n\r\nferry fares: http://www.bcferries.bc.ca/schedules/mainland/vasc-current.html\r\n\r\nOnce on the Ferry, its a smooth 45 minutes to Langdale. From Langdale, its another 1:20 to the tiny town of Egmont, the small town that is only known for its access to Skook. From the town, you can either put in at the Marina and paddle in, or hike in on the popular trail. More than 60,000 people per year hike the 2.5km in to see the tidal rapid.\r\n\r\n If you look at a tide chart or calculator, there are a few things to look for to understand the rapid, and when it will be flowing. On the chart, there is a max flood, max ebb, and slack. The max flood is the fastest the rapid will run during a tide, and is what is important. Optimal surfing flows occur between 12-14 knots. The other thing that is important to remember is that the flow begins two hours before max flood, and lasts two hours after. A max flood at 9pm is great, except the last 2 hours will be in the dark. You also need to figure in a 45 minute hike/ paddle out.\r\n\r\ntide calculator: http://tbone.biol.sc.edu/tide/tideshow.cgi?site=Sechelt+Rapids%2C+British+Columbia+Current+(use+with+caution)','','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (235,'Fishermans Bend','North Santiam','','US','US Pacific','OR','Mill City','','','','','44.7625','-122.5201','','','This is totally exploratory... just downstream from fishermans bend. check this out next time your at the weasel!\r\n\r\nIts a 3.6 mi run down to the weasel.\r\n\r\nCamping is just upstream from this spot at Fishermans Bend Rec Site.. a BLM site. First come first serve.\r\nhttp://www.blm.gov/or/resources/recreation/files/brochures/Fishermen%20Bend%20Recreation%20Site.pdf','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (236,'Bar 72','Clark Fork','','US','US Mountain','MT','Alberton','Clark Fork below Missoula','2000','??','3700','47.0101','-114.5445','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?dd_cd=02_00060&format=img_default&site_no=12353000&set_logscale_y=1','','This spot is worth mentioning because of its proximity to the Alberton Gorge and I-90. Perhaps just a spot to get your head wet, but worth a looksy. The set up is created by a convergence off of a gravel bar island that is sure to shift and change. I have spent hours here over the last several days probing all kinds of charcs. Entering high from the boily eddy on river L., getting a back cut going and screwing down seems to be the most gentle, consistent ride. Nothing great but consistent 3-5 sec. rides are the norm. At 3700 cfs keeping it in the eddy takes awareness, any higher and it could be a hassle.\r\n\r\nThe spot is off of a gravel bar at mile post 72 on I-90. The seam is visible from the highway just before the exit. You can only access the parking area from the East bound lanes. So if you are headed from Missoula, go to the Cyr Bridge exit (exit 70) and pull a U-turn and head back a few miles. The parking area is on a bluff above the river, there is an old thrashy trashy play spot called superhole from way back in the day, the seam is about a hundred yards downstream of it. Theres a nice sandy beach and a cool rock formation to play on too.','12353000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (237,'Aber Glaslyn Gorge','Glaslyn','','GB','','North Wales','Prenteg','','','','','52.9512','-4.0949','','','Downtime Dave Reports:\r\n[quote]there is a sink spot at the very bottom of the\r\nAber Glaslyn gorge in north Wales. i was there the same day i floated Pete Woods boat. The spot is on river left under the bridge.\r\n\r\nThe flow comes off the bridge up right, i was able to get a couple secs head unders on a very low flow. basicly there was no rain in north wales for three days and it was working all be it very mellow spot but peaceful and crystal Clear Water.[-quote]\r\n\r\nGeneral info about the section:\r\nThe Aberglaslyn gorge is one of the best short sections of Whitewater in Wales. With normal/low water it is a technical series of pool-drops Class III/IV, but with heavy rain it can become awesome continuous grade 4+. The gorge section is only 500m long. Inspection is easy (walking down the road) and recommended. With excellent road access, and large pools between the drops, it is safe way to be introduced to this class of whitewater. There is one drop which is larger than the others (the breaker), followed by a pleasant pool, and the possibility of a take-out. Otherwise you can continue on down. Keep your wits about you for this final 100m, as there are some more drops. Take out before the road bridge. After the bridge the river is flat, down to the sea (boring).','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (238,'Rebech Wildwater Stadium','Ariege','','FR','','Ariege Department','Fiox','','','','','42.9682','1.6066','','','Maverick says: \r\n[quote]...made it back to the race course at Foix, for some more sinking action, the top seam which I was playing in last year had a load of slalom poles stuck in it so couldnt play their. But their was a good sinking spot at the get out just above the club house. Big boulder in the middle of the river with a very funky eddy service to say the least was giving out good slam dunk mysteries. [-quote]\r\n\r\nRebech wildwater stadium info:\r\nhttp://www.foixcanoe2010.com/en/?p=6','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (239,'Main Event, The','Trent','','GB','','Nottingham','Beeston','','','','','52.9118','-1.2041','','','Found by Orlando and Chris Jones, Located At the Beeston Marina.\r\n\r\nsays orlandinio:\r\ni can report that on undramactic water levels theres a quiet little line river right ( chris named the main event) which got a couple of heads under . we decided it needed a second visit at higher or lower levels as theres otjher bits river right that would clean up and the main event would benefit fro a little extra volume.\r\n\r\nNotes that go with the picture of the spot:(see images page)\r\n1. Is the Main event. At regular type water levels this was giving almost unlimited chin depth mysteries with no travel and occasionally it had enough power to suck me under for a second or two. More water on this is, I think, really promising and I will definately be heading that way next time the rain comes.\r\n\r\n2. Is a little seam caused by the flows rejoining after going round a laddery type thing in the middle of the weir. Occasional chin deep but I think this may become a bit cleaner as the level drops a bit.\r\n\r\n3. Is a great little seam for beginners made at the top of a big eddy. Easy paddle back into the circle but was only offering up shoulder deep for a couple of seconds.\r\n\r\nThe whole site is great, easy access and plenty of places to jump out and stretch your legs. Easy parking and it has a pub - sells Carling so I am happy, and a Cafe. Plus there are acres of land to walk the dog! (Little Ceri take note!)','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (240,'EXP1 - Trent','Trent','','GB','','Nottingham','Bleasby','','','','','53.037485','-0.908787','','','total exploratory... Chris Jones and orlando mentioned it..','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (241,'EXP1 - Eden','Eden','','GB','','Yorkshire','Cumbria','','','','','54.8167','-2.7622','','','exploratory...\r\n\r\nnot sure if the map is pointed at the correct spot.\r\n\r\nInfo:\r\nThe seam is created by the main flow down the rapid meeting a flow that comes down the shingle bank river right. Levels on Sunday were about 3 above the bottom step at the get on in Lazonby so quite low but not scrapy.\r\n\r\nSeam was very strong with a lot of suck when tailying my float boat, regular whirlies forming all the way down the line and a secondary flow coming in about 15 yards downstream on river right from behind an island. Depth of feature currently unknown but more than 2M+.\r\n\r\nThere are some issues, access may be an issue as the Eden agreement is not the best and the spot is right in the middle of the lazonby estates, there is a track alongside the river but this is used for fishing access. A ghillie was trying to keep us moving down part of the river by following us (we had river tickets for the day). On the plus side there is no fishing track at the feature riverside and there is a footpath up that side of the river from Armathwaite, we had no hassle while playing on this spot. Lazonby estates may be more amenable to access outside fishing season or let a river ticket booking stand for a sinking session. Paddling down from the Lazonby get on in a squirt boat would be a long old trek.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (242,'Thun','Aare','','CH','','Berne','Thun','','','','','46.7579','7.6299','','','This is the home of the squirt event for the Worlds Freestyle 2009 in Switzerland... but, people say its not much of a downtime venue.\r\nhttp://www.icf-thun2009.ch/\r\n\r\nbut there is beta of another old school spot nearby:\r\njames reeves says:[quote]I spoke to Jason (Valley) yesterday and he reckoned the seam was off an eddy river left 5 mintues walk downstream from the wave next to a small sluice that came into the river, not off the bridge. He said they are getting upto 20 seconds mysteries. [-quote]','','cfs','4','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (243,'Radium Bridge upstream of BLM Boat Launch','Colorado','','US','US Mountain','CO','Radium','CO @ Kremmling','900?','1100 was good for 10 sec rides','????','39.9525','-106.5571','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?site_no=09058000','','This one was passed through the grapevine as \\I saw this spot rafting with the family/ or I was in the wrong boat...\\  With Arkanas levels too low for Rincon to flow the hunt was on.  When I first search I hit downstream of Rancho del Rio - State Bridge I found a few good eddylines and one mystery spot 1/4 upstream of the State Bridge on river left.  It drops you quick and then sends you right into a huge boulder on river left.  Danger stay away, unless you\\re going to State Bridge to see a concert and it\\s perfect for getting wet.\r\n\r\nThe goods was found on my way back upstream heading to Denver tracing the river up stream.  Past Rancho del Rio is the turn off BLM Camping at Radium go there.  If you go too far, Or coming from Silverthorn/ Kremmling/I-70 you will see the turn-offs for BLM Camping at the Pumphouse Boat Ramp and 10 miles up the put-in for Gore Canyon V.\r\n\r\nCamping is easy and cheap $3 a day and you walk or drive to the bridge 50 yards away from the camp grounds.  Look for the seam just upstream of the bridge eddy service is best on the left.\r\n\r\nHere\\s some video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FFAgOmgdEaE','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (244,'Dalai Lama','Lhasa','','CN','','Nepal','Lhasa','','','','','29.6143','91.0170','','','Lhasa literally means \"place of the gods\".  It is is located at the foot of Mount Gephel. Traditionally, the city is the seat of the Dalai Lama and the capital of Tibet, and is one of the highest capitals in the world. It is home of the Jokhang Temple.\r\n\r\nexploratory convergence just outside of the city. Next time your traveling in Nepal, dont forget your squirt boat... you may attain enlightenment here.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (245,'The meetings','Avonmore/Avonbeg','','IE','','Co Wicklow','','','Medium fflow','Medium-high','As above','52.886722','6.231822','http://irishwhitewater.com/gauge/index.php','http://www.annamoe.net/weekly.htm','The spot is a confluence between the avonmore and avonbeg rivers. Around the spot is pretty shallow but the actual seam seems deep enough. Noone has hit the bottom in the seam so far anyway. \r\nThe seam looks like it could have potential, however so far it has only been explored at medium-low levels offering up decent chest high mysteries but no more yet.\r\nThe spot can be slightly awkward due to the nature of the confluence, when you finish your mystery you have to ferry back across the flow of the avonbeg to go again as there is no eddyline to go back up next to the confluence. \r\nFurther exploration proves that the spot works best on the higher end of medium flows. Higher than this there is no way to reattain the feature, lower than this there is only enough power to get chest deep mysteries. However the rain has to be pretty widespread as if there is a large difference in flow rates between the 2 rivers the seam becomes very turbulent, preventing a decent charc in. \r\nThe guage is on the avonmore several miles upstream (Currently out of action).\r\nPrediction URL shows rainfall readings for the Avonmore, there is no equivalent for the avonbeg. \r\nBe aware of thieves in the Car park, there has been numerous breakins, so park in the Pub car park on the far side of the road as there is CCTV there.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (248,'Marys Magical Hole','Schuylkill','','US','US Eastern','PA','Belmont','Fairmount Dam','','1720','','40.0347','-75.2412','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?01474500','http://www.phillyrivercast.org/','This mystery spot is just above the better known Philadelphia area paddlers play spot, Marys Hole on the Schuylkill River, ergo Marys Magical Hole.   Down times are short, 3 seconds and most times they are not that deep so there is a tendency to exaggerate how well you are doing. Plus the Schuylkill has the unfortunate reputation as a nasty place for swimming, but according to Phillyrivercast.org the river is fine most of the time.  Check their website for water conditions, youll see.   Nevertheless this mystery spot sees its share of action by the downtimers from the area.  If either of the two of them are not there, the locals will help you find the spot but they think it is called a mystery spot because it is a mystery why anyone would go there.  Otherwise go to where Marywatersford Rd hairpins with Flat Rock Rd in Belmont, PA.  Park on road. Walk toward the railroad tracks and then turn right and look for a stream.  Follow the stream through a tunnel that goes under the Schuylkill Expressway.  Take sturdy shoes, it gets dark in there.  Before you get to the river follow the path up river on your left.  Keep walking,but watch for Stinging Nettle.  Eventually you will come to a beautiful beach.  Keep going, its not that beautiful.  There are some pretty high boulders in the river here.  Walk past them and put in at the pebble beach. Out in the middle of the river is a small drop with a fold in it.  You know what to do.\r\n\r\nadmin note:\r\nplease confirm the coordinates... this is in the middle east and for some reason is not a valid coordinate anyway.\r\nlat: 40.0310\r\nlng: 75.2402','01474500','cfs','11','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (249,'Naruto whirlpools','Naruto Strait','','JP','','Hyogo','Naruto','','','','','34.238333','134.651389','','','The Naruto whirlpools (&#40180,&#38272,&#12398,&#28198,&#28526,, Naruto no Uzushio?) are tidal whirlpools in the Naruto Strait, a channel between Naruto in Tokushima and Awaji Island in Hy&#333,go, Japan.\r\n\r\nThe strait between Naruto and Awaji island has a width of about 1.3 km. The strait is one of the connections between the Pacific Ocean and the Inland Sea, a body of water separating Honsh&#363, and Shikoku, two of the main islands of Japan. The tide moves large amounts of water into the Inland Sea twice per day, and also removes large amounts of water twice a day. With a range of up to 1.7 m, the tide creates a difference in the water level of up to 1.5 m between the Inland Sea and the Pacific. Due to the narrowness of the strait, the water rushes through the Naruto channel at a speed of about 13-15 km/h four times per day, twice flowing in and twice flowing out. During a spring tide, the speed of the water may reach 20 km/h, creating vortices up to 20 m in diameter.\r\n\r\nThe current in the strait is the fastest in Japan and the fourth fastest in the world after the Saltstraumen outside Bodø in Norway, which reaches speeds of 37 km/h, the Moskstraumen off the Lofoten islands in Norway (the original maelstrom), which reaches speeds of 27.8 km/h, and the Old Sow whirlpool in New Brunswick, Canada, which has been measured with a speed of up to 27.6 km/h.\r\n\r\nThe whirlpools can be observed from ships, or from the Naruto Bridge spanning the strait. The suspension bridge has a total length of 1629 m, with the center span over the strait having a length of 876 m and a height of 41 m above sea level. A good view is also possible from the shore on Awaji island.','','cfs','14','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (250,'Quicks','Delaware','','US','US Eastern','NJ','Montague','Delaware River at Montague NJ','1700','1850 - 3000','3500','41.3265','-74.7664','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nj/nwis/uv/?site_no=01438500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=bgm&gage=MTGN4','Quicks is easily accessible from the NJ side of Delaware River off River RD in the Delaware  River National Recreation Area.  Follow a dirt Rd (directly across from Minisink rd)the dirt road is blocked off, but you can park along road side and walk in about 100 yrds.  Hike down trail to  finger of rock to put in.\r\n\r\nFrom rt 206 in NJ.  head towards Milford PA bridge.  turn right before bridge onto River rd about 2.5 miles.  Minisink rd on the right, dirt rd on left to the river.\r\n\r\nQuicks Rift flows into a deep(15+) hole. the river squeezes together over this hole and causes the DT.  It can be entered from either left or right at the point where the curent narrows, makes a slight bend and surges into small whirlpools.  Depending on levels rides start above or at the bend.  Water is usually clean and clear(no goggles needed). Workable levels are usually present all summer long.\r\n\r\nBest rides are comming from the eddy in the center of the River,  Line up with small curler ripples and the finger of rock on shore.  drive into the convergance till about stomach deep and spin clockwize.  the left side is more shifty but rides do happen.\r\nby:  adam','01438500','cfs','18','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (251,'JB','Tamagawa','','JP','','Tokyo','Ome','','','-2.50','','35.803903','139.196305','http://www.river.go.jp/nrpc0305gDisp.do?mode=&officeCode=21320&obsrvtnPointCode=4&timeAxis=60','','','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (252,'Deception Pass','Pacific Ocean','','US','US Pacific','WA','Oak Harbor','Tidal','','','','48.407677','-122.644578','','','Probable Tidal spot... unexplored. \r\nBe weary.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (253,'Green Zone','Trinity River','','US','US Pacific','CA','Helena','TRINITY R NR BURNT RANCH CA','0','','2000','40.7701','-123.1270','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?11527000','','Found by Noah Fraser\r\n\r\nsuper clear and cold, great for summer in Cali.  The spot was only about 6-8 feet deep but was super powered up, it was very similair to Borobus in Japan. The rides were easy to get and fun to just screw down into the seam with about six spins before it took you.  I think a little more or less water would make this spot really really good, but who knows????\r\n\r\nmore info at:\r\nhttp://worldkayakblogs.com/noahsplash/2009/08/04/the-green-zone-ca/','11527000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (254,'The Very Seldom Seam','Dolores','','US','US Mountain','CO','Dove Creek','','','1000','','37.8082','-108.8676','','','Squirt Alert - theres an awesome squirty section of the of the Dolo!  About four miles below snaggletooth, once the river has left the road and the canyon starts to pen up a bit (I think it might be three mile rapid) is a two mile section filled with seams, folds, and convergences.  Found one spot that yielded consistent and deep, with superb eddy service.  This was all at about 1000 cfs, although I suspect most levels would work. The downsides: its about thirteen miles into a twenty six mile run, the Dolroes season is seldom more than two weeks long (dam release for hay farmers), and the releases are relatively unpredictable.  the upsides: you can run the whole section (pumphouse to slickrock) in a squirt, the two miles of seams have beautiful, abundant camping right there, and youre in the dolo canyon, truly spectacular scenery.  So if you can get some raft support, and catch the release, bring some glass! You wont be sorry.','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
