    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (258,'Surfing wave','Cartecay','','US','Dirty South','GA','Ellijay','Cartecay near Ellijay','1.9','2.5','3.5','34.637269','-84.428719','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?02379500','','Upstream from the take out of the regular cartecay run that you take out at blackberry mountain. It is located in the second big rapid on the run. Back cut and regular entries both work great. You can go deep here easy, the higher the better. Also when it is higher it holds you down better. Even when it is low you can still get 5 seconds pretty easy.','02379500','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (259,'Hideaway','','','JP','','','','','','','','35.620437','136.947944','','','lat/lng provided by Hiro','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (260,'Nishimasu','','','JP','','','','','','','','36.345852','137.913823','','','Nishimasu\r\n36.345852,137.913823\r\n\r\nlat/lng provided by Hiro','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (261,'Triple Vortex','susquehanna','','US','US Eastern','PA','Mckees Half Falls','Susquehanna at Harrisburg','2.7','3.38','4.8','40.6603','-76.9166','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?01570500','','This spot is off Rt. 15 at the McKeeï¿½s Half Falls rest stop.  You are free to park there until sundown.  There are a few picnic tables for lunch and a restroom.  There are two sets of ledges here and we are still working on finding out info on what is available at different levels.\r\n\r\nThe Triple Vortex was named because of the three distinct whirlpools that form along the seam.  It can be located by putting in at the upriver set of ledges and paddling one third of the way across the river.  The spot is on the river left side of the rock.  Eddy service is good, its large and easy to catch and can hold multiple boats.  Taking a break is difficult though, there is one spot on a nearby rock that can hold one boat at a time. There are some other rocks around but you have to paddle to them, and paddle back.   \r\n\r\nEntrance move thus far has been a standard righty, you need to enter the oncoming water somewhat slowly to avoid hitting the rock.  If you miss the move the boat will most likely go vertical and spin in the first whirlpool, try to flatten it out quickly to avoid hitting a rock in the bottom of the river with your bow.  Other than that your own your own, I will add information as I learn more about the location as this is the closest spot to me. \r\nEnjoy Jared\r\n\r\nAt 4.2 the back cut works well as well as the righty some three and four second rides no travel and very little spin. The three whirlpools become two at this level.','01570500','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (262,'Afternoon Delight','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Potomac','Potomac River at Little Falls','5.0?','5.3','5.6','38.9792','-77.2363','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','http://newweb.erh.noaa.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','I saw this spot today March 7, 2010, while getting an attaining workout in the afternoon, hence the Afternoon Delight name.  Hopefully it will be just that!  The spot is a convergence at the top of the back channel just upstream of the Anglers put-in--75 feet above Dead Cow.  There is a rock island at the top right where you get back to the Potomac proper and it is very reminiscent of Bermuda. If levels hold above 5.0 until this Thursday I am going to give her a go!  Look for a journal entry soon!!','01646500','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (263,'Going Postal','Maury','','US','US Eastern','VA','Rockbridge Baths','Maury River at Rockbridge Baths','700','1000-1500','2000','37.9018','-79.4116','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02021500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062','','This spot is about 500 yards upstream of the Post Office in Rockbridge Baths, VA on route 39.  It is a few miles downstream of the popular Goshen Pass run.  From the swinging pedestrian bridge you can look upstream and see a large round rock splitting the current.  Park at the post office, walk across the swinging bridge, walk up the river right shore above the last rapid, then paddle up the pool.  Try to be quick and discreet, have not talked to the people that own the 2 houses right next to the river here.  Both sides of rock have obvious seams to try.','02021500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (264,'Twin Fan','Collawash','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','three lynx on the upper clack','2000','','','44.9853','-122.0651','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?14209500','','Twin Fan Campground at convergence. \r\nTwo campsites with park and play access. \r\n6 Miles from Bagby Hotsprings.\r\nThe convergence is at the Hot Springs Fork of the Collawash, where it meets the Middle Section of the Collawash.\r\n\r\nMiddle section is briefly described here, take out at Hot Springs Fork Bridge where the sink spot is:\r\nhttp://americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2713/\r\n\r\nUpper Section has detailed description here:\r\nhttp://www.oregonkayaking.net/rivers/collowash/collowash.html\r\n\r\nUnexplored as of yet...\r\nbut everything looks right: huge recovery pool, convergence of two flows at the bottom of a island and convergence of a third bigger flow from the hot springs fork of the collawash, the third flow is actually flowing at an angle upstream when it hits the other flow so it probably provides a lot of support to just hover and spin,\r\n\r\nDirections:\r\nGo to estacada, head to the upper clackamas on rt 224. Keep going, past Bobs Hole, Fish Creek, Three Lynx... at Ripplebrook turn off of RT224, and turn right onto NFS 46. Follow the signs to Bagby Hotsprings which you see every once and a while. Make your next major right turn after a couple miles onto NFS 63 to follow the Collawash River drainage. When you get to where Bagby Road (NFS 70) turns right off of Collawash River Road(NFS 63), keep going another 0.1 miles on Collawash River Road and youll see Twin Fan Campground just before you cross a bridge. This bridge is what people call the Hot Springs Fork Bridge. \r\n\r\nThere is not a gage for this spot/river. Closest is the Three Lynx gage on the Upper Clackamas, so the spot is set to look at that gage.','14209500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (265,'Collawash (Two Rivers)','Collawash','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','Three Lynx on the clack','500','2000','','45.0323','-122.0606','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?14209500','','Confluence of the Collawash and the Upper Clackamas. Two Rivers Picnic Area gives you riverside park and play access to the spot.  From here we are 15 minutes upstream from Three Lynx. \r\n\r\nThis spot is at the takeout for the June Creek section of the Upper Clack described here:\r\nhttp://www.oregonkayaking.net/floodstage/clack_high.html\r\n\r\nGage is at Three Lynx,  USGS 14209500 on the Clackamas. The Collawash has no gage.\r\n\r\n4 Miles upstream from here on the Collawash is Twin Fan.\r\n\r\nLooks good to me, unexplored as far as i know.  The entry window big, like 2-3 boat lengths long, reminiscent of the seam at squirt ranch. You can screw down into it in a similar way..with no travel. The staging eddy is on the collawash side.\r\n-weaver','14209500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (266,'Ithiel Falls','Lamoille','','US','US Eastern','VT','Johnson','Lamoille River at Johnson','500','1500','2500','44.652378','-72.73147','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?04292000','','Saw this during the annual creeking trip to Vermont.  A textbook convergence of currents at the downstream end of a group of islands.  Havent boated it yet.  Will definitely probe next year.\r\nThis section of river is posted on AW - Slide Falls to Jeffersonville.\r\nWhen I saw it the level was around 1100 cfs - it looked like it would work, but could use a little more juice.  maybe 1500-2000 would be ideal?  Check out the pics. - Dan Mayer','04292000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (267,'Right There','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John','near wash dc, little falls pump station','???','5.1','5.4???','38.9787','-77.2276','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1','Today is April 23, 2010.  Three weeks ago this Sunday John Bell and I headed out for an exploratory of some stuff down below Anglers with the level around 5.1.  Our primary goal was some whirlpools above Yellow Falls.  We pushed off from shore with some skepticism as to what we would find.  Low and behold we get 200 feet downstream and find the only bonafide lefty spot on the Po!!.  This spot is good for 5 to 7 second rides with 3 or 4 spins possible--at least that is what John and I were able to pull off with our short session.  Anyway to get there, go to the Anglers put in and it is Right There!','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (268,'Po Dunk and Roam','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John','near wash dc, little falls pump station','3.2','3.45','3.8','38.971975','-77.219858','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1','So this is the Whirlpool section that John and I wanted to checkout when we discovered Right There with the level right around 5.1.  Stro is the one who told me about this spot.  He told me that back in the day, him and some other old-schoolers would hit this spot up at times with respectable downtime in the whirlpools.  After, being pleasantly surprised at Right There John and I headed on down to see what this spot would give down.  We were not disappointed!  Using a backcut charc we were getting consistent head under rides.  I also had 3 rides in the 15 to 20 second range with close to 100 feet of travel.  It was bordering on epic for a short span, but then things just went dry.  We only had about an hour here before John and I headed back.  After this I headed up to check out Afternoon Delight at this lower level, while John Headed to Brookmont Dam for some surfing.  Afternoon Delight was surprisingly OK at this lower level, but I was really anxious to give Po Dunk another shot.  I paddled down and was just about completely skunked.  The water had dropped a little bit which may have been the reason for no downtime or I was just worn out.  Anyway, the jury is still out on this spot, but the potential is there for a great new Realm!  \r\n\r\nThe Verdict is in: This spot is awesome!!\r\n\r\nDirections:  You can just paddle down to this spot from Anglers.  However, the best access is from the hike in from Marsden Track.  There is a pull off about 200 feet upstream from the Stop sign at Brickyard Road on MacArthur Blvd.  Park and hike to the river from here.  During your hike will come to a bridge at the Canal.  Go over the bridge and make a right onto the towpath and then an immediate left back onto the path.  The path leads down to a T. There is a good launch spot right here--make a left at the T go ten feet and there is a path down to the river.  Once here you will see an island directly across from you and another island farther out.  You can attain up the channel between these two islands without much difficulty--once at the top of the channel ferry across to river right--get high enough to make it around the far island.  Actually, we have found the attainment easier on the back side of the second island.\r\n\r\nYou will see a rock that forms a large eddy in the middle of the channel.  The flow that comes off the river left side this rock is forms the squeeze.  You can pretty much enter anyway with regular righties--the rock does stick out quite a ways so I have been getting a foot away from the rock before initiating, however for a good drop you want to be as close to the rock as possible without hitting it.  The flow on the left side of the rock also gives up respectable downtime above 3.45.  Finally, the flow coming into the channel from the island is also fun to play with--I am still wondering if you can link up a ride from this top flow into squeeze off the eddy rock.  There is not much traffic at this Realm. I would say it is a great place to practice Safety\r\n\r\nHappy Roaming!\r\n\r\n6/16/12\r\nI  took the ? mark off the min and max reading so that it would report as in when its in.\r\nStro','01646500','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (270,'Matthews','River Shannon','','IE','','','Limerick','','','','','0','0','','','Urban squirting.6 seams form below a bridge along with a fun wave train','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (271,'Wye','Little River','','US','Dirty South','TN','Townsend','Little River above Townsend','2.7','3.3','???','35.659807','-83.797709','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?03497300','','Outside Townsend, inside the Great Smokey Mountains National Park is the â€œYâ€.  On the Little River, the â€œYâ€ is formed at the confluence of the Little River and the Middle Prong (Tremont).  A classic hangout for locals and tourists alike, the â€œYâ€ may have some spectators and if you are lucky to catch it on a warm day, then plenty of tubers will be sure to float above your head.  \r\n\r\nLook for the Little River to be 2.8 feet or higher on the Townsend gage, with over 3 feet if there is significant travel involved.  When the â€œYâ€ is in there are plenty of creeks running, from Class II, to all that you want.  So, if that tickles your fancy then bring your creek boat too.   The gage is the last long pull-off on the left before you enter the park, look for the small wooden shack.  \r\n\r\nIf you are keen on a little more privacy, then walk about two hundred yards upstream Tremont, to Roy and Gillâ€™s favorite little fishing hole, Fishing with Gandhi.  After a day at these two sink spots if you still want more downtime, thenâ€¦','03497300','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (272,'Offutts Realm','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John','Potomac River at Little Falls','5.0','?','?','38.9751','-77.2209','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','The spring continues to provide new stuff on the Po! Exploratories, are becoming a lot of fun!  Especially, when they are yielding results.  In previous years I have spent numerous runs on Little Falls with really nothing to show for the effort.  While this year I have spent most exploratories to just downstream of Anglers.  I am willing to bet there are some spots yet to be discovered there.  The Whirlpools where Po Dunk is needs further exploration for sure--looking to hit there around 3.2 to 3.3 this summer.  Today however, two more potential spots are on the horizon.  Look for a Offutts Tease to follow soon.  \r\n\r\nAt the bottom of the Offutt Channel I was looking for something to sink in while Helene was surfing the play wave above. Frankly, I was pretty bored and about ready to leave when I realized that the channel at the bottom on RR actually flows into the channel and is not a runout.  This forms a convergence that was obviously not very powered up today since you had to look close to see that it was not a runout at about 4.8--Honest to God I took no safety breaks : )) \r\n\r\nI did get one 6 second ride though (in 20+ attempts).  I am thinking at 5.5 and higher this spot could yield some epic DT.','01646500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (273,'Offutts Tease','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John','Potomac River at Little Falls','4.8','?','?','38.9754','-77.2234','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00062,00054','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','There was no watch time here but this spot was consistently getting my head wet at 4.8.  More water may make this spot a good 5 to 10 second spot.  Use a regular righty charc coming out of the eddy.  WARNING!!  Dont use a really steep entry charc, as the rock comes far out into the current--I had two really painful pitons trying a steep entry.  This may become less of a factor above 5 feet.  I rated this one as poor--I would not make an entry for anything that is not get going to get my head under and for a moderate rating the spot is going to have to get me 4 feet under--not to be confused with 6 feet under, which is still cool with me as long as we are talking about being 6 feet in the Realm!!  The pitons did not help the rating on this one either--those really sucked : ))\r\n\r\nDeep Thoughts!!!\r\n\r\nSteve G.','01646500','cfs','','poor','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (274,'Statewide','Nolichucky','','US','Dirty South','NC','Burnsville','Nolichucky River at Embreeville, TN','400','1000','1800','36.08328','-82.356182','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03465500','','Statewide is a great low-water option on the Nolichucky to sink. It is located just below On the Rocks in the middle of the river and is formed by the large shelf that the water drops over. The eddy itself resembles the shape of East TN, and although it is upstream of the state line it is where inspiration for the name came from. Different charcs work here righty-regular or lefty-backcut. Nothing sketchy about Statewide, although it is possible to tap a rock on the tail-end of a good ride. After your session continue downstream and surf Jaws for a while before hiking out on the railroad tracks on river left. Be careful crossing the bridge on foot, you dont want to have a Stand By Me incident.\r\n\r\nIn order to access Statewide,  put-in at the standard put-in for the Nolichucky gorge (36.07894,-82.347634). Paddle downstream and you will paddle through Entrance Rapid and On the Rocks, with Statewide in the middle of the river below On the Rocks. Be aware that there is an undercut rock in play in On the Rocks. There are plenty of moves to do on your way downstream (splat the bridge pylon, surf some waves, and sink some mush moves) so keep an eye out.','03465500','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (275,'Cliffside','Nolichucky','','US','Dirty South','NC','Burnsville','Nolichucky River at Embreeville, TN','2500','3500-5500','???','36.077043','-82.369373','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03465500','','About a mile or so below Quarter Mile is Cliffside. It is located on river right below some impressive cliffs with some very smooth rocks and is a great spot to session and eat a snack on your Nolichucky adventure. The regular-righty charc is the way to play at Cliffside. Cliffside offers up some BIG travel rides, and has the eddy service to accommodate. It is a ledge drop that comes out of the giant river right eddy.    \r\n\r\nTo reach Cliffside you are looking at squirting the entire Nolichucky gorge, highly recommended. Use the standard put-in for the Nolichucky (36.07894,-82.347634) and be prepared for a big day. It is probably not wise to squirt the gorge below 2500 cfs (I try to make 3000 cfs my minimum) unless you are a glutton for punishment as the last half of the gorge is rough without the extra water. With plenty of water the Nolichucky gorge is fantastic!','03465500','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (276,'Twin Eddies','Nolichucky','','US','Dirty South','TN','Unicoi','Nolichucky River at Embreeville, TN','1000?','4000-5000?','?','36.084363','-82.423417','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=03465500','','This is a largely unexplored spot partly due to Cowbell being about a mile downstream. Even at low flows, there are big whirlpools in the eddy. From 1300 cfs to 2500 cfs (1700-1800 cfs being optimal) there is a great surf hole for plastic boats. \r\n\r\nI believe the primo level to be either 4000 cfs or 5000 cfs, when a small current stream from river left converges with the main flow (below the hole) to create a perfect drop zone. Odds are you have squirted the Nolichucky gorge to reach Twin Eddies during its ideal flow, but it is possible to hike up the railroad tracks about a mile upstream of Cowbell if your not keen on a downstream trip. When hiking look for a large sandy beach on river right with a massive eddy/pool. Beside the railroad tracks there is a rock formation. Access the river just upstream of the rock jumble.\r\n\r\nAgain there is plenty of exploring to do at Twin Eddies. It is possible that the optimal level is lower and is a level that the river is more often. Definitely BIG downtime at Twin Eddies when everything is right, whenever that may be? Now go out there and git you some.','03465500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (278,'Cornmush','White','','US','US Central','IN','Petersburg','White River at Petersburg, IN','20000','30000','50000','38.546017','-87.241658','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/in/nwis/uv/?site_no=03374000','http://www.dusurf.com/indiana-whitewater','County Roads 300W and 700S will be incredibly slippery after rain. Either road will get you close to the confluence, but theoretically 300W will get you closest. Use the West Fork gauge 03360500 and the East Fork gauge 03373500 to determine if both forks have roughly equal flows, for a distinct seam. This spot might never pan out, I have only seen 10K cfs, and it was weak. Large Asian carp could be a deal breaker.','03374000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (279,'Hindostan Falls','East Fork White','','US','US Central','IN','Shoals','EAST FORK WHITE RIVER AT SHOALS, IN','4000','5500','7000','38.623040','-86.849670','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/in/nwis/uv/?site_no=03373500','http://www.dusurf.com/indiana-whitewater','River left eddy, at the top of the ledge, along shore. Eddy is 5-6 feet deep at 5000 cfs, with a sandy, gravel bottom. Swimming is sweet but posted as not allowed. Lots of blasting holes all the way across the ledge, which is 120 yards wide! The river bed is a very inviting sand and gravel mix along the downstream edge of the ledge, no rules against walking. Very slippery river banks. A few wet yahoos will easily trash the access at the eddy. The trail starts with a lot of glass near the picnic tables. There are other access points that are not as steep and slippery, which are recommended. The worst case shuttle is to put-in near the ramp above the falls, take-out at the ramp below the falls, and walk a half-mile shuttle.','03373500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (280,'Pipeline','James','','US','US Eastern','VA','Richmond','JAMES RIVER NEAR RICHMOND, VA','3.5','3.6-3.9','7.0','37.53269','-77.437068','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02037500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062','','A well known spot to spud boaters, the 3rd drop of Pipeline rapid in downtown richmond, this lefty cartwheel hole will also give up some decent downtime.  Attain up to the foam pile, then hit a lefty charc into the tongue but missing the rock and hang on!  Above 4 feet it is a wild slam dunk drop, but lower summer levels show more promise for longer controlled and stable rides.  \r\n\r\nPark at the boaters parking lot on river left off 14th st, then cross the road and RR tracks, look for steps down to the Pipeline Walkway,  spot is the second ledge up from the bottom.  Water drains half the state of VA, bring head plugs or a solid immunity to river funk.  \r\n\r\nBy josh','02037500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (281,'Fish Ladder at Ashland','James','','US','US Eastern','VA','Richmond','JAMES RIVER NEAR RICHMOND, VA','3.5','3.6-5.7','6.0','37.533405','-77.444568','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02037500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062','','Another spot that you can get your head under, could bear some more exploring.  After Belles Isle and Hollywood Rapid there is a long pool of flatwater.  At the bottom of this on far river left is a break through an old dam.  There is a green sign reading Ashland hanging from a retired railroad bridge, this is the spot.  Try the 2 channels on either side of the sign, in all cases a plug of water falls off the remnant of the dam wall.  River right channel is a righty charc, head deep and only one spin or you pass the eddy and drop into the rapids immediately below.  River left channel has a very promising looking eddyline with whirlpools, havent found the ideal flow yet to tap in everytime.\r\n\r\nPark on river left at the day use lots for Belles Isle, put in near a big rope swing hanging from the active RR tracks.  Getting back to the car is a bit tricky, have to run the rapid below then bushwhack up to Browns Island and walk upstream back to car.  Or just keep going downstream to Pipeline...\r\n\r\nName changed per local knowledge...  Second Break is on river right','02037500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (282,'3,2,1','Watauga River','','US','Dirty South','TN','Elizabethton','Watauga Reservoir','0 generators      ?','between 1 & 2 generators    ?','2 generators      ?','36.335565','-82.264424','http://lakeinfo.tva.gov/htbin/lakeinfo?site=WTH&DataType=All&SUBMIT=View%2Bdata','','3, 2, 1, blast off rocket ship ride into outer space is more like it. Its just two river wide ledges about 50 feet apart. The upstream ledge is broken in two places (you want the furthest one downstream) and water pours through into a fairly deep pool depending on how many generators are on. With 0 generators you might find a few rocks on the bottom if you dont level out in time. At this level its hard work staying down, but... Ive been getting the best rides paddling upstream beside the current on the river left side, then doing a backcut entry. At 2 generators its easy to get down, and the water is quite a bit deeper. The water is cold but really clear. So I recommend long sleeves, goggles, and summer sunshine. The Doe river joins the watauga above this spot so it can effect the level some when its up and make the water cloudy. \r\n\r\nYou can park behind the VFW on hwy 321(2001 West Elk Avenue\r\nElizabethton, TN 37643-3720) and walk down the stairs to the river. The ledge will be about 100 yards downstream. When youre done its an easy walk back up to the VFW.\r\n\r\nor you can park respectfully behind Cline Holder electric supply company. There is a fenced in storage building near the back corner of the parking lot and a trail down to right above the spot. Just make sure you are not blocking the entrance to the storage building and that your vehicle is in the grass. Not on the pavement. The electric supply uses the back parking lot to receive shipments, so a lot of big trucks have to turn around there. I just pull up in front of the fence that is surrounding the storage building as close to the trail as I can get. The owner is cool with that.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nby, columbo','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (288,'Skull Island','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John','Potomac River at Little Falls','5.2?','5.5?','6.0?','38.979549264522674','-77.23207354545593','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62619,62620,00062,00054','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=lwx&gage=brkm2&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1','I have tested this spot several times now and it is worth adding to the everexpanding list here at SinkSpots.  Not real sure of the Min, Max and ideal levels.  I do know that this spot will give you consistent head-under 5 to 10 second rides at around 3 feet of depth.  Occasionally, you can get some depth, maybe 6 or 7 feet and hit like a 15 second ride here.  The Charc I have used is to work your way up the eddy and break right as steep as you can as close to the rock wall as possible without having your stern hit as it swings around--the quicker you can get under here the better your chance of a good ride.  It is a great spot to stop before the Anglers takeout after a gorge run or a Center Chute Session.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (287,'Dunkin Grayballs','Potomac','','US','US Eastern','MD','Cabin John, MD','Potomac River at Little Falls','2.75','2.9','3.1','38.99265063370146','-77.24863082170486','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/md/nwis/uv/?site_no=01646500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62619,62620,00062,00054','','I use to just consider this spot Madder and Madder at lower water, but after showing it to John Bell he suggested that it deserves its own name.  For one, while it is really close to Madder and Madder, it is in a different spot.  Two, it is considerably better than Madder and Madder.  Dunkin Grayballs is located about 10 feet river left of where Madder and Madder forms around 4.  I have had really fun times here lately and it is a good alternative when Bermuda is a little on the scary side.  This spot is better than Moderate but not quite Great--it will yield head under rides almost every ride with good depth on 2 to 3 out of 10.  Occasionally, you can hit rides in the 15 to 20 second range!  At times it can be a pain making the attainment back up for multiple rides but with practice it is not that bad.  I have been using a steep breaking right charc and initiating a little farther away from the rock than what you think will be necessary--missing the rock on entry, which can be a challenge, is key to good rides here.','01646500','ft','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (289,'Kern Convergence','Kern River','','US','US Pacific','CA','Kernville','SF KERN R NR ONYX CA','800','1000','','35.965665','-118.480678','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ca/nwis/uv/?site_no=11189500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','','Home of the Kern River White Water Festival - April 15th.\r\n\r\nhttp://kernfestival.com/\r\n\r\nhttp://www.kernfestival.org/festival.htm\r\n\r\nThere are two spots of interest that sinkers know about: \r\n1. The best spot is just below the brush creek parking lot. If there is enough water going around the island then it should be good, last year I think it was over a thousand.\r\n\r\n2. There is also a spot along a cliff about a mile below the dam near brush creek.\r\n\r\n*** Not sure if the USGS gage is correct for this spot.. locals please adjust if incorrect','11189500','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (290,'Kern Cliff','Kern River','','US','US Pacific','CA','Kernville','','','','','0','0','','','','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (291,'DidgeriDrop','South Branch Raritan','','US','US Eastern','NJ','Flemington','South Branch Raritan River at Stanton NJ','300','750','1000','40.551366','-74.853453','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nj/nwis/uv/?site_no=01397000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=phi&gage=sttn4&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1&toggles=10,7,8,2,9,15,6','Parking is off Rt 31 south just south of the Woodschurch Rd jughandle. Look for the break in the guardrail and a small paved apron leading onto a dirt road. 4 x 4 vehicles can proceed down the road if there is mud. Cars can park on the apron. Alternate parking will be on River Rd. First right after you cross the river on Rt 31. Park on the pull off next to the tracks on the right. Trail to the spot is in the works.\r\nThis spot is the convergance of the river as it wraps around a large island. The seam is just below the small island and can be accessed either from the island or from the eddy on the opposite side of the river. \r\nThis spot has good eddy service on both sides.\r\nThis spot was discovered by Chris\\\\\\\\s Whirld','01397000','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (292,'DidgeriDrop','South Branch Raritan','','US','US Eastern','NJ','Flemington','South Branch Raritan River at Stanton NJ','400','750','1000','40.551366','-74.853453','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nj/nwis/uv/?site_no=01397000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=phi&gage=sttn4&view=1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1&toggles=10,7,8,2,9,15,6','Parking is off Rt 31 south just south of the Woodschurch Rd jughandle. Look for the break in the guardrail and a small paved apron leading onto a dirt road. 4 x 4 vehicles can proceed down the road if there is mud. Cars can park on the apron. Alternate parking will be on River Rd. First right after you cross the river on Rt 31. Park on the pull off next to the tracks on the right. Trail to the spot is in the works.\r\nThis spot is the convergance of the river as it wraps around a large island. The seam is just below the small island and can be accessed either from the island or from the eddy on the opposite side of the river. \r\nThis spot has good eddy service on both sides.\r\nThis spot was discovered by Chris\\s Whirld','01397000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (293,'The Squish','Little River Canyon','','US','Dirty South','AL','Fort Payne','','750','1000','1400(+)','34.364031','-85.650692','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?02399200','','Located in the runoff from Screaming Right Turn on the Upper Two section of the Canyon, the Squish can be found just below two large boulders that channel the runoff into three currents.  The resulting convergence below yields high quality rides that are very smooth with excellent downtime potential. Mainly a righty spot with lefty potential (current seems to work best with right), its a drop and stop ride with picturesque canyon water surrounding you. Beware of the two larger boulders downstream as there is potential for being \\\\squished\\\\ up against the one on river left while still dwelling well beneath the surface. Do not panic if squished, the rock is easy to ride up if your mystery takes you there. One can expect consistently easy 8-10 second rides and can push for the 25+ range on a very regular basis as well.  Very dynamic, smooth, beautiful, and enjoyable spot. Access can be found most practically by hiking down to the spot from the trail following Wolf Creek down from the Canyon Rim Road, takes about 45 minutes to hike down.','02399200','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (294,'Julios Vajulio','Watauga River','','US','Dirty South','TN','Elizabethton','Wilbur Dam','1 generator','between 1 & 2 generators','2 generators','36.341596','-82.256581','http://www.tva.gov/lakes/wth_r.htm','http://www.tva.gov/lakes/wth_r.htm','Having spent all summer at 321 me and Ryan decided to put in higher up at the twins diamond and float down to look for any other good sinkin spots. The water was still low at 3:30pm when we put on. Wilbur Dam was scheduled to begin its release at 1pm. We were skeptical about putting on cause we didnt want to paddle the shoals at low water and risk bustin up the boats. But we decided to put our faith in the TVA and get in anyway. We had paddled to behind the sycamore shoals state park near the end of the parks walking trail where the river forks around an island. The river left fork is the deeper channel and the route we decided to take. I had paddled this section of the river before in a long plastic boat at 0 generators with my girlfriend and remembered this section being really shallow and difficult to navigate. But today at 4pm the channel was obvious and smooth. (The water must be rising!) I aimed river right for an eddy created by the downstream tip of the island and Ryan turned in right behind me. When we spun around to look downstream we knew we had found what we were looking for. Water currents from both sides of the island were colliding with one another in a pleated smash that stretched out for at least 30 feet right in front of us. After I got over the initial shock of having found such potential 10 minutes from where I lived and had spent most of my life I decided to drop in. When I hit the seam it pulled me down hard. Once I got underwater, I was off like a prom dress. Even with my eyes closed I could tell I was moving fast. I just knew I was going to slam into a big rock or log or fish or something. But I never did. I just kept skipping off the river bottom until I ran out of air. I really had to fight to get back up before I got blown past the eddy. When I surfaced I found the eddy, threw up some really hard fist pumps, and then immediately began the ferry back up the river right bank for another ride. We stayed here way too long. Ryan was supposed to meet his inlaws for dinner at 6pm. So at about ten til six we decided to take out early and call his wife from sammons hot dogs to come pick us up.\r\n\r\nBest place to park is at the Sycamore Shoals State Park. Parking is free. Youâ€™ll have to hike from there down the walking trail (which is very well maintained) only a short distance to find one of a number of great spots to put your boat in. Just downstream is where the river forks around Julios private island and the spot is just on the other side. To get back out from the spot paddle just to the downstream river left where there is an obvious take out with a park bench. Youâ€™ll see the walking trail here. Just follow it back up. Youâ€™ll be about 250 yards from the parking lot','42','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (295,'Spin Cycle','Rondout Creek','','US','US Eastern','NY','','','10.5','depends on appetite/','','0','0','','','Spin Cycle is a powerful seam that is formed at the bottom of class 3 rapid on the Rondout Creek in the Shawangunk Mountains, which are part of the Eastern Catskills in NY State.\r\n\r\nThe seam is best from about 11.6 down to 10.5 feet.  Mysteries above 11.6 can get very dynamic, and even from 11 to 11.6, the rides can be loopy even when you\\re in the black compression zone.  I have played around there in the 13\\s but stayed away from the main squeeze.  The highest that locals have tapped in was 12.6 feet, during a river run, with PFDs and paddles, which dished out some nerve-wracking rides.\r\n\r\nSpin Cycle is pretty epic because very deep rides can be had here.  There have been a few over 20 seconds but the up button was pushed.  All of the rides here are different. \r\nThe river constricts here to form the seam, and the result is a strong fold complete with lots of whirlpools.  The whirlpools turn in both directions and go deep.  The current here is also kind surging, so eddy walls form and also go deep where they can smack into you, causing a stall, slide, or a loop or two.  The key is to get under quickly and kung fu your way down through the first few feet of turbulence and level off.  You may need to brace off of those eddy walls and whirlpools once deep.  Sometimes it\\s smooth and easy and sometimes it\\s not.   Spin Cycle may suck out your earplugs or your ride might be super mellow and smooth with great subaquatic visuals.\r\n\r\nAnother reason that this is a pretty epic spot is based on two things:  1) the underwater terrain may be, according to old folklore, scattered with some debris.  I have heard that there are things like bicycles and an old tractor in there.  There definitely is a rock that is about 3 to 4 feet off of the tip of the rock cliff on the river right side, but no one has ever hit it or maybe even come close, and several rides have ended up past the cliff.  As a matter of fact, no one has ever hit anything here and rides have been deep and dark.  Which brings us to 2), when your charc is right, the seam will take you very deep and it gets pitch black.  You roam for several spins and you are lost.  This gets scary, there\\s no doubt about it.  \r\n\r\nYou can park n sink here by parking by the dam and walking 250 to 300 yards down the path to the spot, or you can run a class III/III+ rapid down to the seam, and walk back up.  Or you can just run the whole river, it\\s a great squirt run.\r\nThere is also another epic seam downriver called Tree Hugger, and a few quick mushes and waveholes to ride along the way.\r\nBeer and food at both take out and put in.\r\nGauge Phone # 845.658.8180','','ft','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (305,'Tree Hugger','Rondout Creek','','US','US Eastern','NY','Gunks','','10.9','11.2 to ?','?','0','0','','','Tree Hugger is located about 200 yards above the rapid which contains the infamous Eye Ripper.  There is no park and play here, you have to run some class 2, and then after your session, you will have to run (walk if need be) about a mile of class 3 and 4 afterwards.\r\nTree Hugger is formed by an elbow in the river where there is an eddyline that is formed by the rocks on the bank combined with a drop in the riverbed.  Basically, squirtboaters drop into a trough in the riverbed along the bank.  There have been recent changes to the riverbed here from Hurricane Irene, which gives us a second eddyline that comes from the other riverbank and traverses the main flow to meet up with eddyline #1.\r\nThe rides here can be smooth and very deep with a delay on the up button, judging from years past.  In 2007 or 2008 a flood jammed some trees into the core of the seam and ruined it.  Tree Hugger used to kick down massive downtime, and the recent changes seem to have only improved the power of the eddyline.  \r\nAs of December 2011, we have yet to hit it above 11.2 because the level hasn\\\\t been there when we can go.  But judging on tapping in at lower levels, I can tell that the spot will be as good if not better than it used to be before the hurricane.\r\nI have gotten some rides around 6 or 8 seconds here below 11 feet but the second eddyline tends to smack you into the rock wall which kind of sucks.\r\nThere is a two-stage eddy service here.  The on-deck eddy has plenty of space but the batter-up eddy can fit 2, maybe 3 boats.  The massive tree that used to lay in the heart of the squeeze is in that eddy, and paddlers must hug the tree to keep from getting sucked out by the current.  Good times!','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (296,'The Trestle','Deerfield River, Fife Brook Section','','US','US Eastern','MA','','','800','1000?','','0','0','','','The Trestle is a mystery arena on the Fife Brook Section of the Deerfield River.  It has been written up here on Sinkspots but it was added to the Dryway Section listing, so I decided to post info on it today so squirtists will know there are two major options on the Fife Brook.  Both of these spots are much better than any of the dt on the Dryway Section, and both are park and sink.\r\nThe Trestle gets water about 30 minutes after the release starts on the Fife.   Primarily a righty spot but backcuts into a lefty charc can work as well.  The key is to aggressively get  under and over towards the river left eddy side of the squeeze.  Once you have gotten under the turbulent water, you can work your spin down.  It is possible to get very deep rides over 15 seconds if you hit it just right.  Most rides are in the 5 to 8 seconds, then all of a sudden you nail a big one.  It seems like the higher flows equal better mystery moves.\r\nTap in here for a couple of hours, eat lunch, then drive 3 miles downriver to CJ for some more dt.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (299,'Seboomook Spot','Seboomook','','US','US Eastern','ME','Near Pittson Farms','','','','','0','0','http://www.h2oline.com/235120.asp','','I was there at 1,750 cfs.  There were two great spots. The first was on river left inbetween the two ledge drops above the labrinth. This spot was really chill, easy to get down with backcuts.  The other spot is in the center channel below baby killer, it was a bomb dropper.  Aggressive move into a diagonal foam pile put you on the bottom fast.  Definitely hit some rocks at the second spot, but it was really fun.  We did the run whole run, but you could walk up a trail on river right from teh take-out which I believe ends near the first really good eddyline.','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (300,'Elevator-Sandy Beach','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','14103000','','Summer','','45.14','121.03','http://www.nwrfc.noaa.gov/river/station/flowplot/flowplot.cgi?MODO3','','Favorite spot of mine in the 90\\s - 6.1 miles downstream from Maupin bridge, or 1 mile downstream from the White River confluence. Strong, deep eddy river right with small whirlpools. This eddy is about 300 yards below Elevator and 500 yards above the Sandy Beach takeout, just below where the river narrows and slows.\r\nNot sure about flow info, but, works best at lower summer flows. Caution - make sure the White River is not full of snowmelt as it will wash this spot out.\r\nThere\\s parking and a trail, so you can walk in and walk out if you wish.......','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (301,'Deschutes - Elevator Eddy','Deschutes','','US','US Pacific','OR','Maupin','','','','','45.24','-121.03','','','Favorite spot of mine from the 90\\s. 6.1 mi downstream from Maupin bridge, 1 mile below confluence with White River, 300 yards below Elevator (where the river narrows and slows).\r\nSlow, deep eddy, river right with small whirlpools, not sure about flow levels, but works best at low summer levels - I\\ve spent hours at this spot :)\r\nMake sure the White River is not running full with snow melt as it washes out the eddy.\r\nParking spot and short trail for folks that want to park\\n\\play','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (297,'Frustration Alley','Ocoee','','US','Dirty South','tn','ducktown','','1000','1200','1300','0','0','','','More to come','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (302,'The Gig','Weskeag','','US','US Eastern','ME','South Thomaston','','','','','44.051725','-69.126105','','http://me.usharbors.com/monthly-tides/Maine-Midcoast/Thomaston','This is a tidal location in South Thomaston Maine.  The spot is ideal about 3 hours before high tide and runs for about 1.5 hours.  The spot (river left just after the bridge)is VERY dependent on the tide height and is best on a big (11foot or more) tide.  The whirlpools come and go and every few minutes it changes.  No 30 second epic rides here, I don\\\\\\\\t think I have even hit 10.  It\\\\\\\\s only 10 minutes from my home though, and runs every 12 hours so it is PERFECT for me! \r\nExpect to have some locals stop, jump out of their car, and start waving their arms in fear you are drowning.  It happens often as \\\\Mainers\\\\ have no idea what squirt boating is. \r\nCheers, Ray','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (303,'Powerhouse','Caney Fork','','US','Dirty South','TN','Rock Island','TVA Great Falls','4,000','5,000-6,000','7,500?','0','0','http://www.tva.gov/lakes/gfh_r.htm','','This is the seam created at Rock Island where the water from the pumphouse slams into the current from the falls/sieve city rapid.  At ideal levels it\\\\s world class--giving 20+ second rides with a cool variety of drops and rides.  You can spin either way.  The water is always kinda murky, so nothing fun to see.  It\\\\ll only be there when the dam is spilling (so levels above 3,900.  At these flows, there are also great waterfall lines to run and playboating to be had in plastic boats.  Clay and Stephen started playing here early December, It\\\\s REALLY GOOD.\r\n\r\nTo get there, park where you normally would for the Rock Island playspot (if someone cares to write up better directions, go for it).  Latitude and Longitude in a format that sinkspots doesn\\\\t like is 35 48\\\\ 28.66 N by 85 37\\\\ 59.64 W.  I can\\\\t figure out how to convert it.  Walk down the hill and upstream until you\\\\re directly across from the outflow of the generating station.  The seam should be obvious and easy access park and play.  This spot is kinda surgy and vague at times but with plenty of power.  At higher water, the meat of the squeeze is farther river left, and it moves out to the middle as the water drops.  We sometimes ferry across and cycle from the river left eddy, but a longer travel ride will take you back to river right.  Some rides will yield almost no travel, some might travel river left, but most go downstream river right.  It\\\\s often possible to re-surface after losing support, and start a new drop almost immediately.  Deep rides get SMOOTH :)','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (304,'The Outfield','Congaree River','','US','Dirty South','SC','Columbia','Congaree River @ Columbia, SC','3500','4500-5500','6000','33.591837','8.124432','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/sc/nwis/uv?site_no=02169500','','Recently found seem in downtown Columbia.  Situated right beside the South Carolina Gamecocks baseball stadium.  The actual seem itself is directly under the Blossom St bridge on river left.  It is formed by the water backing up in the channel on the opposite side of the bridge pylon and crossing over the water coming directly downstream.  We have sessioned this spot twice now at 3500 cfs.  just about every ride gives up shoulder deep rides.  At 3500 cfs you can manage head under rides up to five seconds.  More water may provide longer downtime.  Eddy service is great.  We shall see.  If you hit it up during the baseball season you should be able to listen to the game while you sink!\r\n\r\nTo reach the spot park at Granby park.  Hike upstream about 1/8th of a mile to the blossom street bridge.  There are some rough trails through the woods that will get you there which will require walking across a few large diameter water pipes.  Put-in in the pool beside the bridge pylon and paddle to the upstream side of the pylon and drop in on the other side.  \r\nTake-out.  When you are done just paddle downstream the 1/8 of a mile you walked to a small cement boat launch on river left.  Walk back to the car.','02169500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (306,'Sparrow Cliffs','Truckee','','US','US Pacific','CA','Reno/Truckee','Truckee R at Farad, CA','450','900','1300','39.367068','-120.049692','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nv/nwis/uv/?site_no=10346000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','','Home to the Worlds Mystery Gathering of 2014!\r\nMore info here: http://swallowcliffs2014.blogspot.com\r\n\r\nWorld class park and sink spot on the Truckee river about 1/2 way between Reno and Truckee.  Discovered by Noah, its a beautiful convergence below and island which drops into a deep pool.  You can camp right there.  It goes great in both directions of spin and often has crystal clear water so you can watch the sand/gravel bar below you.  At good levels (800-1,100), 20 - 30 second rides are common.  The water is often really clear, so lots of gravel/rocks/sticks to see with goggles....nothing to worry about hitting though :)  \r\n\r\nTo get there, Take the Hirschdale Exit off I-80 west from Reno (Or east from truckee).  Turn right off the ramp onto Hirschdale Rd (downstream).  After a few hundred meters, bear left onto Hirschdale Rd.  Cross the river and stay on the dirt road, looking for a right turn onto a smaller dirt road down hill to the right, which is just at the very end of a long chain link fence on the right--If you get to the end of Hirschdale Rd, you went too far....just turn around and take the 1st left back downhill--  Cross the RR tracks and drive down the road to near-river height, looking for a sharp turn to the right, which goes down a steep small hill (non trucks should park across from this turn).  Drive or walk down the hill to the river and the seam is just below the small island.  \r\n\r\nENJOY!!!!!','10346000','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (307,'Dogma','New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Fayettenam','Huntington Corp of Engineers','1800','2100','2400','0','0','','','Next to the sitting rock at the Halls.  The seam is created by the main current and the current coming around the river left side of the huge rock that creates the main channel at the Halls.  The flow from the left side drops over the sitting rock, and can take you deeeep.  You can travel a little upstream into the big eddy right behind the Halls, or a little downstream behind the sitting rock, or not travel at all.  It\\\\\\\\s a finicky spot. If you hit it right, it will take you deep, getting 30+ second rides.  If you don\\\\\\\\t and try to work it, it\\\\\\\\ll wear you out! If it does take you deep, it\\\\\\\\s a great, smooth ride.  It will make you feel neutrally buoyant and it will seem like you can stay there for as long as you like.  Great visuals as well, as you are right next to the sitting rock, sometimes looking like you are under the rock!','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (308,'Gator Pit','Broad','','US','Dirty South','SC','Columbia','','?','?','?','0','0','','','New potential spot at the canal park on the broad river.\r\nEnter the park from river drive and park at the end of the road. \r\nYou\\ll see the old canal locks. You can walk over the bridge and look down and pick your seam.\r\n\r\nYes, there are gators in the Broad. You have been warned.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (309,'Dirty Ol South','James','','US','US Eastern','VA','Richmond','James near Richmond','5.5','7-8','9','37.531981','-77.434523','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02037500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062','','From standard lower james takeout off 14th street by river left floodwall, paddle upstream to the railroad trestle on far river left.  High tide alternative follow river left floodwall upstream from parking, cross tracks then take steps down to pipe walkway to a nice launching beach.  Occasional bums here.   Spot is fed by a trestle current pillowing up on piling then dropping into channel, and a stream current from a side branch returning to main flow.  This spot is also tide dependent, explorations in progress but seems low tide is better.  Pretty classic current convergence, best in Richmond.  3-4 seconds under about the average ride so far.  Long low cut boats best here.  Also great stern squirt and screwing around spot, though you may clip rocks at low tide.  Spot named for graffiti on opposite side of trestle.  Discovered by Gordon Miller.','02037500','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (310,'Timmys Super Fun Time Spot','Collawash','','US','US Pacific','OR','Estacada','','','','','44.9883','-122.0661','','','exploratory spot.. tim and weaver noticed it when doing the run from twin fan down to 2 rivers (which incidently is a fun class 3 section in plastic).\r\n\r\na convergence its just around the first turn of the river, after you put in at twin fan... ie. 100ft.. also right above the convergence is a shallow but yet fun and exciting play wave that i was tearing it up on, in my plastic boat.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (311,'1 mile','Tedori','','JP','','Ishikawa Prefecture','mikawa','','','','','36.468164','136.491122','','','not sure exactly where this is, but considering that Toru named this the 1 mile spot, ive tried to pinpoint a spot on the river 1 mile from the mouth of the river.... \r\n\r\ncheck out the vid.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (312,'Yough Exploratory-Connellsville','Youghiogheny','','US','US Eastern','PA','Connellsville','Youghiogheny River at Connellsville','?1000','?2000','?3000','39.9830722','-79.588587','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/pa/nwis/uv/?site_no=03082500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,00010','http://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=pbz&gage=cllp1&hydro_type=0','The spot is about midway down the river left channel where a large island splits the river about 2 miles upstream from Connellsville, PA.  It\\\\\\\\s a large deltoid rock sloping into the water with a wing-like cross section and a deep pool.  It has all the attributes of a quality DT spot.  To get there:  South of Connellsville on 119, turn onto Clair Street, then immediately right onto Riverside Drive, which will take you across Dunbar Creek.  Bear right at a fork in the road near the railroad bridge, and follow it all the way up to the gate of the North Fayette Water Treatment Plant.  Park here, and take the footpath up to the rail-trail.  Head upstream about 1/2 mile.  Look left for the island, and find the rock - hard to miss.  As you are walking upstream, you\\ll pass a small covered bench and then a large rock outcropping that hides the river from your view.  As soon as the river comes back in view, there\\s a trail to the left.  Bank is really steep and there is not much of a trail.  Levels are just a guess.','03082500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (313,'Peace Bridge','Niagara River','','CA','','','','','','','','0','0','','','On July 8, 2012 I tested the first Pylon out from the Canadian side.  The other pylons as well as the weird structure below the bridge should be looked at as well.  It seems there is not much in the way of eddy service but walking laps of the spots is not all that difficult.  Being by myself with big boils and a substantial amount of boat traffic kept me from letting her rip here.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (314,'Going Going Gone','Stura','','IT','','Turin','Lanzo','','','','','43.0789','-79.0762','','','Have found a new squirt spot in Italy for you fun loving travellers to check out.\r\n\r\nThere are two spots on the \\\\Stura River\\\\ @ Lanzo near Turin\r\nThis is a locals swimming spot with super clean water about 2 and a half meters deep and long mysteries to be had, don\\\\t miss the brake out on the 1st spot or you have to run a crappy bolder rapid that forms the 2nd down time spot.\r\n\r\n1st spot is called \\\\Going Going Gone\\\\\r\n2nd spot is called \\\\Slam Dunk\\\\\r\nEnjoy Maverick','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (315,'Slam Dunk (Italy)','Stura','','IT','','Turin','Lanzo','','','','','43.0789','-79.0762','','','Have found a new squirt spot in Italy for you fun loving travellers to check out.\r\n\r\nThere are two spots on the \\\\Stura River\\\\ @ Lanzo near Turin\r\nThis is a locals swimming spot with super clean water about 2 and a half meters deep and long mysteries to be had, don\\\\t miss the brake out on the 1st spot or you have to run a crappy bolder rapid that forms the 2nd down time spot.\r\n\r\n1st spot is called \\\\Going Going Gone\\\\\r\n2nd spot is called \\\\Slam Dunk\\\\\r\nEnjoy Maverick','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (316,'The Leslie','Hiwassee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Reliance','','Unknown','2 or more generators','Unknown','43.0789','-79.0762','http://www.tva.gov/lakes/aph_r.htm','http://www.tva.gov/river/recreation/sched_apalachia.htm','The leslie is a great spot on the Hiwassee river next to the Ocoee river. The spot is a convergence that drops off a ledge into a pool that is 20\\ plus deep. It\\s truly an amazing spot were the rider has a complete variety of charc\\s, depths, and length of rides. If you like head under 20 sec. mysteries, she\\ll give them to you, if you like scary deep, compression rides, she\\ll let you squeeze in a little deeper. If you want to potentially hit a one minute mystery, you could make it happen here. You can fly with yer buds too, and see them. The sky really is the limit here. There is very little traffic from tubers and fishermen, but when they come by, you can watch from below as they watch above. The gorge you are in is completely unique in itself. Come check it out. \r\n\r\nThe Leslie gets it\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\s  name from the spinning action & Doppler effect sound of A Leslie Speaker cabinet, spinning heads since the 1930\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\s. You can put in @ the Big Bend parking area and float down river right thru two sets of shoals, The Leslie awaits your charc @ the bottom of the 2nd set which contains The Three Bears, which are rad blast holes at certain flows. Anyhow a large outcrop of rock on the right bank,dubbed \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\the wall\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\ by Joe indicates\r\n you have arrived. \r\nyou can hike back out ,up river in 25-30 min.  Be mindful of the wood on the \r\ndownstream end of the boiler eddy on river right , this should not be a problem to anyone paying attention.','','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (317,'Randolph Sampler','Hiwassee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Reliance','','1 turbine','2 or more turbine','Unknown','0','0','','','Named in the honor of the honorable Captian Randolph Samples','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (318,'North South Confluence','south santiam','','US','US Pacific','Or','Jefferson','','','','','0','0','','','This is located at the South and North Santiam confluence. gps 44.41\\\\15.0   123.00\\\\24.7.  the flows on the north were 2070 at the Greens Bridge gauge and 1309 (waterloo gauge) on the South Santiam. Not epic at these flows but i think could get better at higher flows. 6-8 second rides consistently, here is a video. https://vimeo.com/51371930   \r\nDefinitely going back at higher flows to check it out. oh, got there by putting in at greens bridge on the north and taking out at bridge in jefferson...about 4 mile float.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (319,'Indian Pool','Maury River','','US','US Eastern','VA','Goshen','Maury @rockbridge baths','600','800-1200','2500','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02021500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,00062','','Pretty obvious spot located at the primary steps takeout for the Goshen Pass \\\\meat\\\\ section.  Walk down the steps and upstream to a large beach with a fire ring.   Slide in here, cross the flow to set up in the eddy behind the smooth marble-ish ledge.  This is the last plug of water that empties into Indian Pool, but take a look at the next few spots above, sometimes they can give up rides too but need to catch the eddy quickly.  The charc here is tricky.  You have to paddle all the way up the diagonal ledge, and drop in parallel to the ledge/trough with a lefty charc.  I try to be under right when my bow gets to the obvious fold.  You WILL smack the rock here with your bow until you get it dialed.  Smack away, unlike the Bubbler the rock here is smooth and not pinnable.  I try to stay as flat as possible and only take a small bite out of the plug.  If you get both ends under and have a bit of leftward momentum it will carry you almost immediately over a second ledge for a double suck.  The second ledge is underwater and usually not visible, and I think it is also about 30 degrees left of the set up ledge.  The best rides are when you miss the rock by inches and get slammed down perfectly parallel to the 2nd ledge, but you can still get sent with some rock taps.  The rides go from 0 to 60, getting sent plugs you right into the last wave train entering the pool.  Best control comes from being right on the eddyline, half in half out.      \r\n\r\nIf you live in Virginia you know exactly where this spot is.  Out of towners:  From I-81 take exit 195.  Driving west on 39 from Lexington, pass through Rockbridge Baths --SEE also Going Postal-- following the Maury on river right another couple miles.  About a mile after the valley closes in, the road takes a sharp turn to the left, then a huge paved pulloff appears on the right that can hold 15 cars single file.  Park here and walk down the steps.  Bring a plastic boat, this is the main takeout for people getting their laps in on the classic class 3/4 goshen pass.  For significant others, there is good fishing on the opposite side of the river, and several good crags to climb.  The pebbly beach is actually pretty epic too, perfect view of the arena.','02021500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (320,'Wheaties','North Santiam','','US','US Pacific','Or','scio/jefferson','Greens Bridge','500','2800','30000','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/or/nwis/uv/?site_no=14184100&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060','','I found a new spot on the north Santiam. Located at Buell-Miller boat ramp. Maybe 15 minutes outside of jefferson. Seam is created by a large boil converging with the main current. Enter from eddy on river right. Initiate just above the boil and keep spinning until it pulls you down. You can go DEEP here. I think well over 30 second rides are possible. 2800 cfs on greens bridge gauge offered scary good rides. 2300 cfs and the boil was significantly smaller and the seam is much less defined. it was also much more difficult go deep. \r\n\r\nHazards: very popular fishing spot. watch out for speeding boats during salmon runs. If someone is fishing here when you get there, offer them a beer and ask to take turns. Also logs and possibly old construction debris from railroad bridge on bottom. I\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\ve gone deep and have only seen the bottom once...looks like large cobblestones.  ENJOY!\r\n\r\nAdd the gauge # and Gauge url, a min and max based on the stream flow table, so it\\ll show as  always in until better beta is established.  6/13/13 stro','14184100','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (321,'Rabbit Hole','Winnipesaukee','','US','US Eastern','NH','Northfield','Tilton','900','1200-1900','2500','43.443241','-71.622915','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?01081000','','A classic recirculating eddy/squeeze seam, located just downstream of the Cross Mill Rd. Bridge (put in for the Lower Winni run).  The local beavers have dropped some trees in the eddy- only an issue when paddling back up the eddy, but not while underwater.\r\n\r\nLevels need more exploration.\r\nMin is a guess.  It\\\\s less powerful below 1000.\r\nIt seems to get better/more powered up as the flow increases.\r\nMax is a guess. it almost never gets that high.','01081000','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (322,'Traffic Accident','Androscoggin River','','US','US Eastern','ME','Brunswick','','3000','TBD','14000','43.916169','-69.975169','','','This spot forms under the bridge from the concrete bridge abutment.  Don\\t look to hit this in the middle of the summer unless after quite a bit of rain as there is not enough flow.\r\nat big water- over 14K- the spot turns into an elevator ride to a deep, dark turbulent place.  I have come up several times upstream from where I entered, and close...too close... to the abutment.\r\nThis is named traffic accident as it is in plain view right next to a very busy road where traffic is often backed up and moving slow.  It is a matter of time before the sinking causes an accident.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (323,'Perfect Wave','Gauley','','US','US Eastern','WV','Summersville','Gauley at Belva','200','1500','4000','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03192000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','Who knows when somebody will actually show up here with a sinker... the main attraction is the year round glassy wave that can be carved to pieces.  However there is a really good looking squeeze when the flow is in the teens on river right.  Deep pool behind so probe away.  Do NOT probe any seams on river left per Steve O... junky neighborhood awaits.  Will downtime here ever be had?  You would be the first if you can tear yourself away from the wave.\r\n\r\nThe Perfect Wave is located one mile downstream from the Mason\\s Branch takeout for the Upper Gauley (aka Last Chance).  Park at the first available gravel pull off after the river comes into view driving to the normal takeout.','03192000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (324,'Sushi Sandwich','Payette','','US','US Mountain','Idaho','Horseshoe Bend','Main Payette','Unknown','Unknown','3000','43.0789','-79.0762','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/id/nwis/uv?site_no=13247500','','Exploratory dunker that runs at summer levels when North Fork is at standard summer release levels and South Fork is running low\r\nJust downstream of the Magic Bus on river right.','13247500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (328,'Middle Fork Salmon','Middle Fork Salmon','','US','US Mountain','Idaho','Stanley','MFS','?','?','?','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/id/nwis/uv?site_no=13309220','','Backcountry exploratory sinking at its finest.  Journaled here for help with future trip planning for one lucky permit lottery winner.  First come, first serve permits also available outside peak season.  Before will be snowy, high water, maybe Marsh Creek put in.  After will be ELF run, but great fishing and chucker grouse hunting seasons.  Local guides say you can still get a raft down from Boundary Creek at 1.7.  On an oar rig with the sleds strapped for Park and Play is the way to go.  Downriver would shred your boat, too many rapids with fresh angular granite in shallow water.  Taking a boat with a soft hull would be ideal, it would open up a lot more spots for sessioning.  Lots of drop zones with leaky eddies, so a mad dash a la Bermuda Triangle is necessary after your ride plays out.  Following is my recollection of the most prominent spots I observed during a trip in July 2015 at the level of about 2 feet or 850 cfs.  ---MP 12.5, Sheepeater Island.  Looks like 2 big slabs squeezing into each other at a 60 degree angle.  River right channel, bouncing off a RR wall and the island.  Reminded me of Swallow Cliffs.  Excellent Hot springs downstream at mp 13.   ---MP 32.7, Marble Right Camp.  Current bends to the right, falling off cobble bar and going deep next to a wall on river left.  Nice recirculation in eddy squeezes back in, big boils and long recovery pool.  Just down stream at ---MP 33.0. Ski Jump Rapid.  Ski Jump Rock came out at low water, sloped rock drops into deep long pool.  Looked like Fascination Alley on river left.  Best looking spot on the river at 2 feet.  ---MP 43.6, Pine Flat Rapid Ender Spot.  Massive Fucking downtime.  If there aren\\t any rocks in outflow, this one will be epic.  Huge whirlpools, massive slab drop.  MP 51.1 Underwater Canyon.  Explore at own risk, def worth a stop, swim and fish.  ---MP 58, Tappan Rapids.  Great looking eddylines, drops, and whirlpools this whole 2 mile stretch. Could probably downriver this small section.  ---MP 70.5 Earthquake Rock.  Great wave surfing.  You are bringing a 7.5 foot slicey plastic boat too right?  ---MP 79-95, Impassable Canyon.  The best eddylines on this river are when the walls pinch in and the river gets deep.  That describes this last long section.  Post up if you see a spot, once you go past it the MF lives up to its name River Of No Return.  Any climbers in your group will get fired up about the walls.  2 30 foot slings and a top rope could get you on a lot of rock, watch out for snakes in the scree.  Hope this is helpful, when somebody gets a permit to pull this off, invite me!   By Josh Tracy.','13309220','ft','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (325,'The Shark','Yuba','','US','US Pacific','California','Grass Valley','Yuba below Deer Creek','450','700','1000','0','0','http://www.dreamflows.com/graphs/day.607.php','','Great little spot on the lower Yuba river, which receives plenty of regular flow, since the water is used to irrigate the highly fertile central valley of California. Better at lower flows, which makes it great when nothing else is running. Very unique underwater scenery makes it very fun even though the rides usually don\\t extend past 15 seconds. I called it the Shark because the rock in the middle of the river resembles a shark fin sticking up, and also because it isn\\t very deep and you can really get bitten quite hard by the yuba river rock. Contact me at willpruett@gmail.com if you wanna check it out. Cheers!','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (326,'Rat Trap','Russel Fork','','US','US Eastern','VA','Breaks','Russel Fork Elkhorn City','300','500-800','1500','37.299353','-82.317236','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?site_no=03209300','','From Rat Hole takeout/campground walk all the way upstream on the dirt road at river level, river right.  Ferry across the pool to river left.  Walk upstream on ATV trails to the top of the rapid.  Put in the pool above and paddle up to the sloping rock on river left.  Same structure as Thread the Needle on the NRG, lefty charc.  Old School Spot.  Name inspired by the feeling of hitting it perfect, like a rat trap slamming shut.  As well as the proximity to the classic campground.  River is dam released but runs 300 days a year at various levels.  Seam still looks good at 400 cfs.','03209300','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (327,'Indian Bends','watauga','','US','Dirty South','TN','Elizabethton','wilbur/watauga','1 generator','1 rising to 2','2+ generators','36.389547','-82.315940','http://www.tva.gov/lakes/wih_r.htm','http://www.tva.gov/river/recreation/sched_wat-wilb.htm','park on herb hodge road. there are several pull offs. you can see the island and seam easily from the road. the river right channel is shallow then it drops off in to a sandy pit right where it meets the river left channel. the recovery eddy leaves something to be desired but it works. herb hodge road is popular with cyclists so be courteous to them. and the water is cold','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (329,'K-Hole','Kanawha/New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Gauley Bridge/Glen Ferris','Kanawha River at Kanawha Falls','3,500?','4,000-6,000','10000?','38.145678','-81.213293','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?03193000','','This is at Kanawha Falls, just downstream of the convergence of the New and Gauley rivers.  These spots are classic convergence seams--they remind me a bit of Bermuda on the Potomac or Powerhouse in Rock Island.  It is a super cool place to run some fun falls and drop a world class sink spot in one trip.  Park in the park just below the falls, and paddle up (it is a fairly long flatwater padde, so I may take a playboat or creek boat next time and tow my squirt up).  So far, I have only explored it for 2 days and just the seams up the river left channel.  The main one that I have played from 4,000-6,000 was in the outflow of the falls just upstream of the crack drop  Basically paddle as far up the river left channel as you can, and you will find it no problem.  At lower flows, the obvious squeeze just upstream of this one may become safer to probe, but there are definitely some rocks in the convergence.  Stephen Wright\r\n\r\nUPDATE: while we were there the other day, it dropped to around from 4,000  to around 3,700.  You could still get rides, but they were very inconsistent.  Seems like 4,000 is the lowest level for consistent longer rides...it\\\\d probably still drop a small boat down to 3,500, but only if you\\\\re desperate.','03193000','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (330,'Spun Out Frat Boy','Maury','','US','US Central','Virginia','Lexington','Maury at Rockbridge Baths','100','600-1400','2000','37.851060','-79.421622','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/va/nwis/uv/?site_no=02021500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62620,62614','','Best convergence spot between the Bubbler and the Potomac river.  Located on the river left channel around a big island, 200 yards upstream of the bridge over route 622 or Alone Mills Road.  Find the westernmost sharp turn in the river with an island complex inside the curve about 10 miles north of Lexington, VA, or GPS Alone Mills Schoolhouse.  Discovered by Mason Basten, First D by Josh Tracy.  Park at a pulloff on the east side of the bridge, keep a low profile.  There are reports of territorial canoeists, fishermen and landowners.  Access by attaining to big island then bushwhack, or walk up river leftâ€”possibly trespassing on posted land?   Spot is formed when a feeder channel not visible on google cuts through the big island squeezes back into the main river left side channel.  A steep wall on river left is close to the seam.  Sample carefully, spot has not been scouted at low water yet, but appears very deep and clean if you do not bump the wall.  Dash back to the river right set up eddy.  At higher levels of 1000? Cfs plus, maybe a good idea to bring a stick or boat with a soft hull to make the quick dash right easier.  At lower levels the eddyline seam is reported to become crisper with regular whirlpools shearing off.  Also reports of summertime swimmers getting unwanted downtime.  How low will it go?!?   Named for the legendary party house just downstream of the bridge on river left.  HOOTERVILLE has hosted numerous W and L boaters over the years, and even counts the legendary Gordon Dalton among former tenants.  Name may change if anybody who could impact access gets their panties in a bunch.','02021500','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (331,'***BLANK***','','','','','','','','','','','0','0','','','','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (332,'Beaver Junction','Deerfield','','US','US Eastern','MA','','USGS 01168500 DEERFIELD RIVER AT CHARLEMONT, MA','','800','','42.6669222','-72.9571669','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/?site_no=01168500','','Beaver Junction is at the confluence behind Beaver Island on the Deerfield River in MA. It\\s a solid okay-to-good spot, but nowhere near epic like CJ, which takes release water another 50 minutes to get to. BJ is pretty mellow and consistent and I was getting 10-20 s rides. The hike-in was extremely strenuous -- DO NOT do it. If you want to check out this spot, I would suggest either doing a 1-mile float trip or contacting the owner of the nice camp right next to BJ for permission to use the property (which would make access to BJ super easy).\r\n-- Peter Lo','01168500','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (333,'The Icebox','SF Payette','','US','US Mountain','Idaho','Garden Valley','','unknown','1100-1600+','unknown','0','0','','','The spot is on the river right side where a rock extends out into the flow creating the drop. The eddy feeds back into the flow and you can see some nice whirlpools down the eddy line. There is excellent eddy service and amazing beach for loading/unloading between sets. \r\n\r\nYou can spin right or left (backcut). There are several different types of rides you can take. I have had a few rides where I have gone deep and come up precisely where I dropped. These were very promising! Most rides though have been traveling ones. The drop is excellent and the accomplished squirt boater should have a very high success rate. The channel seems to be around 10-12â€™ deep. \r\n\r\nThere are two rocks in the eddy downstream of the drop, but I havenâ€™t tangled with them yet. Itâ€™s still something to be aware of, and you can see them when you are sitting in the eddy. I think they are pretty benign. \r\n\r\nThe name is a product of the fact that the water is frigid, a result of the snowmelt from the Sawtooth mountains on the SF Payette and the dam release out of the bottom of the Deadwood River (colder than the SF). However, the temperatures are routinely 100 degrees and the water is crystal clear. Very refreshing! There is excellent camping, and a beautiful beach. Also, most people get cell service here. \r\n\r\nNot too sure yet about the high and low level limits, but the Deadwood release ends at Labor Day and it wonâ€™t be in at that time. \r\n\r\nTo get here drive from Banks, ID up the SF Payette on the Banks-Lowman Highway approximately 12 miles (through Garden Valley) to the Alder Creek Bridge on the right. Cross the bridge over the SF (takeout for the Swirly Canyon) and then take the first left. Cross the little one lane bridge over Alder Creek (nearly dry during summer) and then look immediately for the â€œSF Payette Recreation Areaâ€ sign on the left. This is the site of excellent camping. Walk from the campsites down to the beach. The beach can be a popular spot for swimming and fishing during the summer. There are some good cliff jumps just downstream of the dropzone. \r\n\r\nYou may also see some fish while here. Weâ€™ve seen several very large ones (possibly Salmon). Just downstream there was a herd of young elk in the river and an Osprey carrying a fish. This is a beautiful spot!\r\n\r\nThe level is the combination of the gauges for USGS SF Payette @ Lowman, ID and Deadwood River. Links below. It\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\s likely good above 1600, possibly being good well towards 2000 cfs. We won\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\t know that until next year though. \r\n\r\nDeadwood:\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/id/nwis/uv?site_no=13236500\r\n\r\nSF Payette @ Lowman:\r\nhttp://waterdata.usgs.gov/id/nwis/uv?site_no=13235000\r\n\r\n-Curtis Heishman','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (334,'THE ROCK','Lower Provo','','US','US Mountain','Utah','Provo','Lower Provo','600','700+','Unknown (yet)','40.356604','111.569899','http://data.cuwcd.com/data/streamflows/index.htm','','This spot is on the Lower Provo River, upstream from Vivian Park about 100 yards.   Park in the Vivian Park parking area on river left, not the commercial parking lot on river right.   Enter the railroad tracks walking path via the access point in the fence and walk downstream about 100 yards.  You\\ll see the very obvious river access on the left and you\\ll see \\The rock\\.  The feature is created in a right hand turn in the river with the main current hitting a large rock.  The defined seam is obvious.   Locals say it goes with left or right spin.  Short rides with quick recovery paddles to the river left eddy to miss a shallow runout and mid stream bushy island. Moderately clear and noticeably cold water.   This is also a \\Blue Ribbon River\\ with excellent trout fishing through this stretch.    The \\Tuber Hatch\\ is quite thick during hot summer months.     Slightly downstream is a quality class 4 run called Bridal Veil where you can get your river running on if you are so inclined. http://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/10738/','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (335,'THE ROCK','Lower Provo','','US','US Mountain','Utah','Provo','Lower Provo','600','700+','Unknown (yet)','40.356604','111.569899','http://data.cuwcd.com/data/streamflows/index.htm','','This spot is on the Lower Provo River, upstream from Vivian Park about 100 yards.   Park in the Vivian Park parking area on river left, not the commercial parking lot on river right.   Enter the railroad tracks walking path via the access point in the fence and walk downstream about 100 yards.  You\\ll see the very obvious river access on the left and you\\ll see \\The rock\\.  The feature is created in a right hand turn in the river with the main current hitting a large rock.  The defined seam is obvious.   Locals say it goes with left or right spin.  Short rides with quick recovery paddles to the river left eddy to miss a shallow runout and mid stream bushy island. Moderately clear and noticeably cold water.   This is also a \\Blue Ribbon River\\ with excellent trout fishing through this stretch.    The \\Tuber Hatch\\ is quite thick during hot summer months.     Slightly downstream is a quality class 4 run called Bridal Veil where you can get your river running on if you are so inclined. http://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/10738/','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (336,'Crystal Wave','Ogden River','','US','US Mountain','Utah','Ogden','Ogden River NR Gibson Ave','85','200','375','41.135826','111.585626','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ut/nwis/uv/?site_no=10140700&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,72020,00010,00095,00400,00300,00045','','Crystal Wave, located behind the Walmart at 21st street and Wall Ave in Ogden Utah.   This is a low water play feature created with the City of Ogden and the Ogden River Restoration Project a few years ago.   Pool drop with decent front surf at low water and great river left eddy service at all levels. The depth is around 10\\ immediately below the wave and a pool is formed that rises to a riverwide shallow section about 40 yards downstream.  The river left seam gives up short head-under rides with both left or right spins.   At slightly higher water, 180ish and above, the river right eddy line is powered up with water coming over the river right rocks and forming a pinch.   Right spin in the pinch gives up 10 second rides with some bottom bouncing in the murky water until you run out of depth and surface downstream in the thinner water.     \r\n\r\nThis is a popular swimming hole with the locals, so early or late sessions are less crowded.  \r\n\r\nIf the water level is 200 or higher and you\\re looking for a creek to run in your plastic boat, check out the Ogden Narrows upstream in the canyon.   One of the best class 4 creeks in the state.  http://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/1863/','10140700','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (337,'Bikini Bottom','Weber River','','US','US Mountain','Utah','Hennifer','Weber River at Echo, UT','Unknown (yet)','400+','Unknown (yet)','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ut/nwis/uv/?site_no=10132000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,72020,00010,00095,00400,00300,00045','','At the big parking lot put in, for Utah\\s most popular whitewater run called Hentag (Hennifer to Taggart) is \\Bikini Bottom\\.  Named for the many many tuber girls prancing in the parking lot in their bikinis.   When the \\rubber hatch\\ happens in the summer, this parking lot is super busy.    Bikini Bottom is located about 25 yards upstream from the put in.   There is a river right protrusion of rocks that create a strong eddy that feeds back into the pool at the seam.   Although the seam pushes downstream into the river right wall, rides that hover at the top of the eddy are possible.   Locals are exploring the potential but should be good for some head under goodness.  Hentag, a classic class 3 run awaits you after your session.','10132000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (338,'Bikini Bottom','Weber River','','US','US Mountain','Utah','Hennifer','Weber River at Echo, UT','Unknown (yet)','400+','Unknown (yet)','0','0','http://waterdata.usgs.gov/ut/nwis/uv/?site_no=10132000&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,72020,00010,00095,00400,00300,00045','','At the big parking lot put in, for Utah\\s most popular whitewater run called Hentag (Hennifer to Taggart) is \\Bikini Bottom\\.  Named for the many many tuber girls prancing in the parking lot in their bikinis.   When the \\rubber hatch\\ happens in the summer, this parking lot is super busy.    Bikini Bottom is located about 25 yards upstream from the put in.   There is a river right protrusion of rocks that create a strong eddy that feeds back into the pool at the seam.   Although the seam pushes downstream into the river right wall, rides that hover at the top of the eddy are possible.   Locals are exploring the potential but should be good for some head under goodness.  Hentag, a classic class 3 run awaits you after your session.','10132000','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (339,'Pretty Drive No Downtime','Glady Fork','','US','US Eastern','WV','','','','','','39.0082501','-79.5493906','','','This spot was explored on May 26, 2017.  It is one of the prettiest places I have been in West Virginia.  However, their is land access issues and even worse there is no downtime to be had here.','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (340,'Cheat Forks Convergence','Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','Parsons','Parsons','4000 at Parsons with 1500 on Shavers?','?','?','39.1084717','-79.68226','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03069500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','A crew in search of a worlds option explored this seam on May 28, 2017.  The Shavers fork was flowing at 857 and the Parsons Gauge was 2840.  There was no downtime here this day but there was a seam.  This would be worth checking out again and I would do just that if the Shavers Fork was 1500 and Parsons was at 4000.  There is no park and play.  However, there is easy access for a 3-mile run.  Park at CJs Pizza in Parsons and the takeout is just across the Bridge on Holly Meadows Rd. on River Right.  The seam may or may not be a one and done with higher flows.','03069500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (341,'Laurel Fork Confluence','Dry Fork of the Cheat','','US','US Eastern','WV','','Parsons','2500?','?','?','38.9796372','-79.5454781','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/wv/nwis/uv/?site_no=03069500&PARAmeter_cd=00065,00060,62614','','There are a number of us who have seen this seam and I have heard one story where this seam mysteried a shredder at really high flows.  That said, it probably lacks eddy-service.  Still, it deserves another look.','03069500','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (342,'Happy Creek','Sandy','','US','US Pacific','OR','','','','2200?','around 3300?','0','0','','','In Fall of 2016, this little spot was first explored by myself a couple of times, then Nick B joined in to help figure it out.  The first sets were at 2400 then 2700 and rides were there but it\\s a juicy little seam the higher the CFS and above 2400 was pretty powerful.  I went at 3200 and it was rowdier than I\\d like.  Last week, I figured out a good charc at 2240 and was getting under 9 out of 10 times with some rides being deep and in the 10-12 range.   Today, myself, Joel DM,  and the league rookie Gavin made his debut at 1850 and we had a great time getting decent rides.\r\nThere is plenty more exploring to do here with lots of potential.  It\\s also very scenic as it\\s located within Oxbow Regional Park.  Find the Happy Creek beach and you\\re there.  So far, I\\d say 2200 might be the magic level.  \r\nThink deep thoughts - John D','','cfs','','exploratory','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (343,'Flowmaster','Ocoee','','US','Dirty South','TN','Knoxville','Ocoee #2','1100?','1250?','1400?','0','0','','','The Flowmaster seam is off the RL eddy at the top. Easy place for <5-6 sec head dips. Access while going down river, or park at the North Shore pull off and hit this on the way to Staging Eddy. May be the easiest head under on the river, but if you stay down too long you float past the point of eddy service.','','cfs','','moderate','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (344,'King Tubby\\s Hi-Fi','Washougal','','','US Pacific','WA','','','??','2050','2300?','0','0','','','This is a spot on the Washougal river, between MP3 and Hathaway Park.  You must run some whitewater to access this spot, but it is not a difficult run and in fact is a fantastic squirt river with many excellent deep eddy lines and fun waves to surf.  You can also park at a pull off before Hathaway and use it as your take out for a shorter run.  \r\nKing Tubby\\s Hi-Fi is a dynamic spot because there are several ways to get in and there are various different types of rides you may receive depending on your charc.  The higher up entry may drop you deep, or not...you may roam 10 feet upstream, or may resurface at the same spot you dropped in.  Or, you may get into the deeper layers of water and roam downstream for a smooth ride.  Another way to enter is at a fold that surges about midway the length of the seam, which overall is about 40 feet long.  Around where this fold is, the river gets very deep and your boat will compress in the shadowy pocket as you slowly creep around the riverbank towards the feeder creek that comes in on the right.\r\nThe eddy is a  bit of a conveyor belt that seethes back towards the main eddy line, and with that being said, it might not be the best place for a beginner and it\\s not good for more than 3 or 4 boats total.  If you find the spot, then you\\re in the know and deserve your place in the eddy.','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (345,'King Tubby\\s Hi-Fi','Washougal','','','US Pacific','WA','','','??','2050','2300?','0','0','','','This is a spot on the Washougal river, between MP3 and Hathaway Park.  You must run some whitewater to access this spot, but it is not a difficult run and in fact is a fantastic squirt river with many excellent deep eddy lines and fun waves to surf.  You can also park at a pull off before Hathaway and use it as your take out for a shorter run.  \r\nKing Tubby\\s Hi-Fi is a dynamic spot because there are several ways to get in and there are various different types of rides you may receive depending on your charc.  The higher up entry may drop you deep, or not...you may roam 10 feet upstream, or may resurface at the same spot you dropped in.  Or, you may get into the deeper layers of water and roam downstream for a smooth ride.  Another way to enter is at a fold that surges about midway the length of the seam, which overall is about 40 feet long.  Around where this fold is, the river gets very deep and your boat will compress in the shadowy pocket as you slowly creep around the riverbank towards the feeder creek that comes in on the right.\r\nThe eddy is a  bit of a conveyor belt that seethes back towards the main eddy line, and with that being said, it might not be the best place for a beginner and it\\s not good for more than 3 or 4 boats total.  If you find the spot, then you\\re in the know and deserve your place in the eddy.','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (346,'Gates of Mordor','Mamquam River','','CA','US Pacific','British Columbia','Squamish','0','0','0','0','0','0','','0','Put in at mamquam river slalom course, take out at mashiter creek confluence. \r\nSite can also be accessed by walking up from mashiter, take out.  \r\nGates of Mordor is located on mamquam after ring creek confluence.\r\n\r\nVideo of spot - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njtc5H0oY-A','0','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (347,'Blood Rock','Lewis River','','US','US Pacific','Washington','Etna','LEWIS RIVER AT ARIEL, WA','1400','?','?','45.936299','-122.622959','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?site_no=14220500','','Found this spot the local fishermen calls Blood Rock. Its fucking epic... get ready to shit your pants! And its good at low water... stoked!','USGS14220500','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (348,'Mavericks','Little River Canyon','','US','Dirty South','AL','Fort Payne','USGS Little River at Blue Pond, AL','~450','','~850','34.395066','-85.626962','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv?02399200','','This is the seam at the base of Little River Canyon Falls, it may the same spot as The Chicken Shack on here http://sinkspots.org/index.php?spot_id=125 but no one calls it that. Named by Ben Friberg some years back, but dusted off and reinvigorated in ~2017. Sometimes also called Song of the South.\r\n\r\nTo access the seam, park at the Little River Canyon Falls Park lot, walk down the path a bit, go off road through woods on an unofficial but fairly obvious trail down to essentially river level, and then hike back upstream to get closer to the base of the falls. The hike is only about 1/3 of a mile, but you cover ~90 feet of elevation and there is a fairly steep section. If you know where you are going, it takes about 10-15 minutes to do safely with a boat and gear on your shoulder (watch for snakes).\r\n\r\nThe Range is supposedly 450 cfs to 850 cfs on the Little River at Blue Pond gauge. I have found that the seam offers easier access at more like 600-700 than it does above 800, but my rides are generally topping out at ~20 seconds. Perhaps bigger flows = bigger downtime. Folks have already knocked off 30+ second rides here, and rumors abound about massive potential. \r\n\r\nThere is a rock that you may sometimes tag on rides that involve big downstream travel, but the shape seems friendly on a low-water inspection and it has been harmless to date.\r\n\r\nIn the adapted words of Mr. Sibley: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\Clear Water, natural Flow, 1/2 champagne, 1/2 laminar, epic water fall, 60 second potential.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\ \r\n\r\nA great spot that warrants further exploration.','02399200','cfs','','epic','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (349,'The Rainbow Connection','New','','US','US Eastern','WV','Fayettenam','Thurmond','5000?','6000','6500?','38.07262','-81.08486','https://waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv?03185400','https://water.weather.gov/ahps2/hydrograph.php?wfo=rnk&gage=hinw2','New sink spot on the New River below Flea Flicker (rapid after Fayette Station) has been probed and proven. I\\\\ve been looking at this for about a year and finally got what I thought would be the best water level last night at 3.3\\\\ (6300 cfs) on the FS gauge.\r\nThe ride on this drop is very similar to Mellow Ledge with lots of travel, deep rides (I hit bottom once, guessing about 10-12\\\\ deep), and I even got a double suck a couple times. Lots of travel, no stalling at all at last nights level, but it is a nice smooth drop with good support from flow filling the adjacent eddy. However, unlike Mellow Ledge, there is a great setup/rest eddy right by the rock (which is a perfect observation rock) and one of the best views of the bridge you can get. For easy access you can set a vehicle at Teays takeout and put on above or below Fayette Station rapid.\r\nI\\\\m guessing best levels will be 2.5\\\\-3.5\\\\ (maybe higher if you can still make the approach move). Below 2.5\\\\ the rock that makes the seam is starting to show and the juice just isn\\\\t there, but low cut boats might still get in.\r\nPete Iscaro gets the nod for the first head under at the spot and that was with a PFD on! I got at least 8 seconds on a number of rides and there is definitely more to be had.','03185400','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (350,'Picnic Rock','Cache la Poudre','','US','US Mountain','CO','Ft Collins','Poudre Rock Report','3â€™â€™?','3.5-5.5â€™','TBD','0','0','','','100 yards downstream of picnic rock parking lot. Mouth of the Canyon. First dropped by Clay Wright in May of 2018 @ around 3.5â€™\r\nIâ€™ve been there now at 3.8, 4.2, & 5.2ft with consistent 10+ second rides.\r\nGreat eddy service on river left, beer & a concert afterwards @ Mishawaka Amphitheatre a few miles upstream.','','ft','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
    INSERT INTO spots VALUES (351,'Pont de Pedra / 19 Sort Worlds spot','Noguera Pallasera','','ES','','','Rialp','','10','33','','0','0','','','First bridge upstream or Rialp where an old stone bridge sits abandoned.  Drop zone is below Jump-off cliffs river right, hidden shelf 2\\\\ out from pourover so drop 2-3\\\\ out with hard left hip.  Can ride downstream or drop again hard into gravel ballroom not far downstream of the drop rock. When deep, you travel less and can swim towards the eddy for bubble-free swirls.  The drop rock is overhanging, so it\\\\s similar to Fascination when you get it right.. your ends will spin under the rock and you can see the bubbles from the pourover above.  Alternate drop comes in from upstream river left eddy and drops into the pillow off the drop-rock, connects to the main seam nicely.    Hazards:  new fallen rock above river left get-out eddy and old bridge cement corner above downstream river right get-out spot.  Both are 2\\\\ under the surface.    Big gravel bottom is super-safe.. 8-10\\\\ depth with endless potential once locked into ballroom. 25 was my max as it\\\\s some effort to get into.  Water clarity is amazing - bring goggles.','','cfs','','great','','2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400', '2019-09-10 12:03:55 -0400'),
)

